INSERT INTO verses (book_id, chapter, verse, text, version) VALUES
(18, 36, 7, 'Nebuchadnezzar also took some of the treasures from the Temple of the LORD, and he placed them in his palace in Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 8, 'The rest of the events of Jehoiakim''s reign, including all the evil things he did and everything found against him, are recorded in The Book of the Kings of Israel and Judah. Then his son Jehoiachin became the next king.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 9, 'Jehoiachin was eighteen years old when he became king, but he reigned in Jerusalem only three months and ten days. Jehoiachin did what was evil in the LORD''s sight.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 10, 'In the spring of the following year, Jehoiachin was summoned to Babylon by King Nebuchadnezzar. Many treasures from the Temple of the LORD were taken to Babylon at that time. And Nebuchadnezzar appointed Jehoiachin''s uncle, Zedekiah, to be the next king in Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 11, 'Zedekiah was twenty-one years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem eleven years.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 12, 'He did what was evil in the sight of the LORD his God, and he refused to humble himself in the presence of the prophet Jeremiah, who spoke for the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 13, 'He also rebelled against King Nebuchadnezzar, even though he had taken an oath of loyalty in God''s name. Zedekiah was a hard and stubborn man, refusing to turn to the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 14, 'All the leaders of the priests and the people became more and more unfaithful. They followed the pagan practices of the surrounding nations, desecrating the Temple of the LORD in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 15, 'The LORD, the God of their ancestors, repeatedly sent his prophets to warn them, for he had compassion on his people and his Temple.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 16, 'But the people mocked these messengers of God and despised their words. They scoffed at the prophets until the LORD''s anger could no longer be restrained and there was no remedy.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 17, 'So the LORD brought the king of Babylon against them. The Babylonians killed Judah''s young men, even chasing after them into the Temple. They had no pity on the people, killing both young and old, men and women, healthy and sick. God handed them all over to Nebuchadnezzar.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 18, 'The king also took home to Babylon all the utensils, large and small, used in the Temple of God, and the treasures from both the LORD''s Temple and the royal palace. He also took with him all the royal princes.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 19, 'Then his army set fire to the Temple of God, broke down the walls of Jerusalem, burned all the palaces, and completely destroyed everything of value.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 20, 'The few who survived were taken away to Babylon, and they became servants to the king and his sons until the kingdom of Persia came to power.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 21, 'So the message of the LORD spoken through Jeremiah was fulfilled. The land finally enjoyed its Sabbath rest, lying desolate for seventy years, just as the prophet had said.', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 22, 'In the first year of King Cyrus of Persia, the LORD fulfilled Jeremiah''s prophecy by stirring the heart of Cyrus to put this proclamation into writing and to send it throughout his kingdom:', 'NLT'),
(18, 36, 23, '"This is what King Cyrus of Persia says: The LORD, the God of heaven, has given me all the kingdoms of the earth. He has appointed me to build him a Temple at Jerusalem in the land of Judah. All of you who are the LORD''s people may return to Israel for this task. May the LORD your God be with you!"', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 1, 'In the first year of King Cyrus of Persia, the LORD fulfilled Jeremiah''s prophecy by stirring the heart of Cyrus to put this proclamation into writing and to send it throughout his kingdom:', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 2, '"This is what King Cyrus of Persia says: The LORD, the God of heaven, has given me all the kingdoms of the earth. He has appointed me to build him a Temple at Jerusalem in the land of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 3, 'All of you who are his people may return to Jerusalem in Judah to rebuild this Temple of the LORD, the God of Israel, who lives in Jerusalem. And may your God be with you!', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 4, 'Those who live in any place where Jewish survivors are found should contribute toward their expenses by supplying them with silver and gold, supplies for the journey, and livestock, as well as a freewill offering for the Temple of God in Jerusalem."', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 5, 'Then God stirred the hearts of the priests and Levites and the leaders of the tribes of Judah and Benjamin to return to Jerusalem to rebuild the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 6, 'And all their neighbors assisted by giving them vessels of silver and gold, supplies for the journey, and livestock. They gave them many choice gifts in addition to all the freewill offerings.', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 7, 'King Cyrus himself brought out the valuable items which King Nebuchadnezzar had taken from the LORD''s Temple in Jerusalem and had placed in the temple of his own gods.', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 8, 'Cyrus directed Mithredath, the treasurer of Persia, to count these items and present them to Sheshbazzar, the leader of the exiles returning to Judah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 9, 'These were the items Cyrus donated: gold trays............. 30 silver trays.......... 1,000 silver censers......... 29', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 10, 'gold bowls............ 30 silver bowls.......... 410 other items.......... 1,000', 'NLT'),
(19, 1, 11, 'In all, 5,400 gold and silver items were turned over to Sheshbazzar to take back to Jerusalem when the exiles returned there from Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 1, 'Here is the list of the Jewish exiles of the provinces who returned from their captivity to Jerusalem and to the other towns of Judah. They had been deported to Babylon by King Nebuchadnezzar.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 2, 'Their leaders were Zerubbabel, Jeshua, Nehemiah, Seraiah, Reelaiah, Mordecai, Bilshan, Mispar, Bigvai, Rehum, and Baanah. This is the number of the men of Israel who returned from exile:', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 3, 'The family of Parosh.................... 2,172', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 4, 'The family of Shephatiah.................. 372', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 5, 'The family of Arah....................... 775', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 6, 'The family of Pahath-moab (descendants of Jeshua and Joab)......... 2,812', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 7, 'The family of Elam..................... 1,254', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 8, 'The family of Zattu....................... 945', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 9, 'The family of Zaccai...................... 760', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 10, 'The family of Bani....................... 642', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 11, 'The family of Bebai...................... 623', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 12, 'The family of Azgad.................... 1,222', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 13, 'The family of Adonikam.................. 666', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 14, 'The family of Bigvai.................... 2,056', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 15, 'The family of Adin....................... 454', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 16, 'The family of Ater (descendants of Hezekiah)................. 98', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 17, 'The family of Bezai...................... 323', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 18, 'The family of Jorah...................... 112', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 19, 'The family of Hashum.................... 223', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 20, 'The family of Gibbar...................... 95', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 21, 'The people of Bethlehem.................. 123', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 22, 'The people of Netophah.................... 56', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 23, 'The people of Anathoth.................... 128', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 24, 'The people of Beth-azmaveth.............. 42', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 25, 'The peoples of Kiriath-jearim, Kephirah, and Beeroth................... 743', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 26, 'The peoples of Ramah and Geba............. 621', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 27, 'The people of Micmash.................... 122', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 28, 'The peoples of Bethel and Ai................ 223', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 29, 'The citizens of Nebo....................... 52', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 30, 'The citizens of Magbish.................... 156', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 31, 'The citizens of Elam...................... 1,254', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 32, 'The citizens of Harim...................... 320', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 33, 'The citizens of Lod, Hadid, and Ono............................... 725', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 34, 'The citizens of Jericho..................... 345', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 35, 'The citizens of Senaah.................... 3,630', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 36, 'These are the priests who returned from exile: The family of Jedaiah (through the line of Jeshua)...... 973', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 37, 'The family of Immer.......... 1,052', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 38, 'The family of Pashhur......... 1,247', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 39, 'The family of Harim.......... 1,017', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 40, 'These are the Levites who returned from exile: The families of Jeshua and Kadmiel (descendants of Hodaviah).......... 74', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 41, 'The singers of the family of Asaph.... 128', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 42, 'The gatekeepers of the families of Shallum, Ater, Talmon, Akkub, Hatita, and Shobai................ 139', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 43, 'The descendants of the following Temple servants returned from exile: Ziha, Hasupha, Tabbaoth,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 44, 'Keros, Siaha, Padon,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 45, 'Lebanah, Hagabah, Akkub,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 46, 'Hagab, Shalmai, Hanan,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 47, 'Giddel, Gahar, Reaiah,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 48, 'Rezin, Nekoda, Gazzam,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 49, 'Uzza, Paseah, Besai,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 50, 'Asnah, Meunim, Nephusim,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 51, 'Bakbuk, Hakupha, Harhur,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 52, 'Bazluth, Mehida, Harsha,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 53, 'Barkos, Sisera, Temah,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 54, 'Neziah, and Hatipha.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 55, 'The descendants of these servants of King Solomon returned from exile: Sotai, Sophereth, Peruda,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 56, 'Jaalah, Darkon, Giddel,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 57, 'Shephatiah, Hattil, Pokereth-hazzebaim, and Ami.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 58, 'In all, the Temple servants and the descendants of Solomon''s servants numbered 392.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 59, 'Another group returned to Jerusalem at this time from the towns of Tel-melah, Tel-harsha, Kerub, Addan, and Immer. However, they could not prove that they or their families were descendants of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 60, 'This group consisted of the families of Delaiah, Tobiah, and Nekoda--a total of 652 people.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 61, 'Three families of priests--Hobaiah, Hakkoz, and Barzillai--also returned to Jerusalem. (This Barzillai had married a woman who was a descendant of Barzillai of Gilead, and he had taken her family name.)', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 62, 'But they had lost their genealogical records, so they were not allowed to serve as priests.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 63, 'The governor would not even let them eat the priests'' share of food from the sacrifices until there was a priest who could consult the LORD about the matter by means of sacred lots.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 64, 'So a total of 42,360 people returned to Judah,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 65, 'in addition to 7,337 servants and 200 singers, both men and women.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 66, 'They took with them 736 horses, 245 mules,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 67, '435 camels, and 6,720 donkeys.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 68, 'When they arrived at the Temple of the LORD in Jerusalem, some of the family leaders gave generously toward the rebuilding of God''s Temple on its original site,', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 69, 'and each leader gave as much as he could. The total of their gifts came to 61,000 gold coins, 6,250 pounds of silver, and 100 robes for the priests.', 'NLT'),
(19, 2, 70, 'So the priests, the Levites, the singers, the gatekeepers, the Temple servants, and some of the common people settled in villages near Jerusalem. The rest of the people returned to the other towns of Judah from which they had come.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 1, 'Now in early autumn, when the Israelites had settled in their towns, all the people assembled together as one person in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 2, 'Then Jeshua son of Jehozadak with his fellow priests and Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel with his family began to rebuild the altar of the God of Israel so they could sacrifice burnt offerings on it, as instructed in the law of Moses, the man of God.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 3, 'Even though the people were afraid of the local residents, they rebuilt the altar at its old site. Then they immediately began to sacrifice burnt offerings on the altar to the LORD. They did this each morning and evening.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 4, 'They celebrated the Festival of Shelters as prescribed in the law of Moses, sacrificing the burnt offerings specified for each day of the festival.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 5, 'They also offered the regular burnt offerings and the offerings required for the new moon celebrations and the other annual festivals to the LORD. Freewill offerings were also sacrificed to the LORD by the people.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 6, 'Fifteen days before the Festival of Shelters began, the priests had begun to sacrifice burnt offerings to the LORD. This was also before they had started to lay the foundation of the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 7, 'Then they hired masons and carpenters and bought cedar logs from the people of Tyre and Sidon, paying them with food, wine, and olive oil. The logs were brought down from the Lebanon mountains and floated along the coast of the Mediterranean Sea to Joppa, for King Cyrus had given permission for this.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 8, 'The construction of the Temple of God began in midspring, during the second year after they arrived in Jerusalem. The work force was made up of everyone who had returned from exile, including Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel, Jeshua son of Jehozadak and his fellow priests, and all the Levites. The Levites who were twenty years old or older were put in charge of rebuilding the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 9, 'The workers at the Temple of God were supervised by Jeshua with his sons and relatives, and Kadmiel and his sons, all descendants of Hodaviah. They were helped in this task by the Levites of the family of Henadad.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 10, 'When the builders completed the foundation of the LORD''s Temple, the priests put on their robes and took their places to blow their trumpets. And the Levites, descendants of Asaph, clashed their cymbals to praise the LORD, just as King David had prescribed.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 11, 'With praise and thanks, they sang this song to the LORD: "He is so good! His faithful love for Israel endures forever!" Then all the people gave a great shout, praising the LORD because the foundation of the LORD''s Temple had been laid.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 12, 'Many of the older priests, Levites, and other leaders remembered the first Temple, and they wept aloud when they saw the new Temple''s foundation. The others, however, were shouting for joy.', 'NLT'),
(19, 3, 13, 'The joyful shouting and weeping mingled together in a loud commotion that could be heard far in the distance.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 1, 'The enemies of Judah and Benjamin heard that the exiles were rebuilding a Temple to the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 2, 'So they approached Zerubbabel and the other leaders and said, "Let us build with you, for we worship your God just as you do. We have sacrificed to him ever since King Esarhaddon of Assyria brought us here."', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 3, 'But Zerubbabel, Jeshua, and the other leaders of Israel replied, "You may have no part in this work, for we have nothing in common. We alone will build the Temple for the LORD, the God of Israel, just as King Cyrus of Persia commanded us."', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 4, 'Then the local residents tried to discourage and frighten the people of Judah to keep them from their work.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 5, 'They bribed agents to work against them and to frustrate their aims. This went on during the entire reign of King Cyrus of Persia and lasted until King Darius of Persia took the throne.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 6, 'Years later when Xerxes began his reign, the enemies of Judah wrote him a letter of accusation against the people of Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 7, 'And even later, during the reign of King Artaxerxes of Persia, the enemies of Judah, led by Bishlam, Mithredath, and Tabeel, sent a letter to Artaxerxes in the Aramaic language, and it was translated for the king.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 8, 'Rehum the governor and Shimshai the court secretary wrote the letter, telling King Artaxerxes about the situation in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 9, 'They greeted the king for all their colleagues--the judges and local leaders, the people of Tarpel, the Persians, the Babylonians, and the people of Erech and Susa (that is, Elam).', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 10, 'They also sent greetings from the rest of the people whom the great and noble Ashurbanipal had deported and relocated in Samaria and throughout the neighboring lands of the province west of the Euphrates River.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 11, 'This is a copy of the letter they sent him: "To Artaxerxes, from your loyal subjects in the province west of the Euphrates River.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 12, '"Please be informed that the Jews who came here to Jerusalem from Babylon are rebuilding this rebellious and evil city. They have already laid the foundation for its walls and will soon complete them.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 13, 'But we wish you to know that if this city is rebuilt and its walls are completed, it will be much to your disadvantage, for the Jews will then refuse to pay their tribute, customs, and tolls to you.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 14, '"Since we are loyal to you as your subjects and we do not want to see you dishonored in this way, we have sent you this information.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 15, 'We suggest that you search your ancestors'' records, where you will discover what a rebellious city this has been in the past. In fact, it was destroyed because of its long history of sedition against the kings and countries who attempted to control it.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 16, 'We declare that if this city is rebuilt and its walls are completed, the province west of the Euphrates River will be lost to you."', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 17, 'Then Artaxerxes made this reply: "To Rehum the governor, Shimshai the court secretary, and their colleagues living in Samaria and throughout the province west of the Euphrates River.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 18, '"Greetings. The letter you sent has been translated and read to me.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 19, 'I have ordered a search to be made of the records and have indeed found that Jerusalem has in times past been a hotbed of insurrection against many kings. In fact, rebellion and sedition are normal there!', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 20, 'Powerful kings have ruled over Jerusalem and the entire province west of the Euphrates River and have received vast tribute, customs, and tolls.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 21, 'Therefore, issue orders to have these people stop their work. That city must not be rebuilt except at my express command.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 22, 'Do not delay, for we must not permit the situation to get out of control."', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 23, 'When this letter from King Artaxerxes was read to Rehum, Shimshai, and their colleagues, they hurried to Jerusalem and forced the Jews to stop building.', 'NLT'),
(19, 4, 24, 'The work on the Temple of God in Jerusalem had stopped, and it remained at a standstill until the second year of the reign of King Darius of Persia.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 1, 'At that time the prophets Haggai and Zechariah son of Iddo prophesied in the name of the God of Israel to the Jews in Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 2, 'Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel and Jeshua son of Jehozadak responded by beginning the task of rebuilding the Temple of God in Jerusalem. And the prophets of God were with them and helped them.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 3, 'But Tattenai, governor of the province west of the Euphrates, and Shethar-bozenai and their colleagues soon arrived in Jerusalem and asked, "Who gave you permission to rebuild this Temple and restore this structure?"', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 4, 'They also asked for a list of the names of all the people who were working on the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 5, 'But because their God was watching over them, the leaders of the Jews were not prevented from building until a report was sent to Darius and he returned his decision.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 6, 'This is the letter that Tattenai the governor, Shethar-bozenai, and the other officials of the province west of the Euphrates River sent to King Darius:', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 7, '"Greetings to King Darius.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 8, 'We wish to inform you that we went to the construction site of the Temple of the great God in the province of Judah. It is being rebuilt with specially prepared stones, and timber is being laid in its walls. The work is going forward with great energy and success.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 9, 'We asked the leaders, `Who gave you permission to rebuild this Temple and restore this structure?''', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 10, 'And we demanded their names so that we could tell you who the leaders were.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 11, '"This was their answer: `We are the servants of the God of heaven and earth, and we are rebuilding the Temple that was built here many years ago by a great king of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 12, 'But because our ancestors angered the God of heaven, he abandoned them to King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon, who destroyed this Temple and exiled the people to Babylonia.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 13, 'However, King Cyrus of Babylon, during the first year of his reign, issued a decree that the Temple of God should be rebuilt.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 14, 'King Cyrus returned the gold and silver utensils that Nebuchadnezzar had taken from the Temple of God in Jerusalem and had placed in the temple of Babylon. These items were taken from that temple and delivered into the safekeeping of a man named Sheshbazzar, whom King Cyrus appointed as governor of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 15, 'The king instructed him to return the utensils to their place in Jerusalem and to rebuild the Temple of God there as it had been before.', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 16, 'So this Sheshbazzar came and laid the foundations of the Temple of God in Jerusalem. The people have been working on it ever since, though it is not yet completed.''', 'NLT'),
(19, 5, 17, '"So now, if it pleases the king, we request that you search in the royal archives of Babylon to discover whether King Cyrus ever issued a decree to rebuild God''s Temple in Jerusalem. And then let the king send us his decision in this matter."', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 1, 'So King Darius issued orders that a search be made in the Babylonian archives, where treasures were stored.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 2, 'But it was at the fortress at Ecbatana in the province of Media that a scroll was found. This is what it said:', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 3, '"Memorandum: "In the first year of King Cyrus''s reign, a decree was sent out concerning the Temple of God at Jerusalem. It must be rebuilt on the site where Jews used to offer their sacrifices, retaining the original foundations. Its height will be ninety feet, and its width will be ninety feet.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 4, 'Every three layers of specially prepared stones will be topped by a layer of timber. All expenses will be paid by the royal treasury.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 5, 'And the gold and silver utensils, which were taken to Babylon by Nebuchadnezzar from the Temple of God in Jerusalem, will be taken back to Jerusalem and put into God''s Temple as they were before."', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 6, 'So King Darius sent this message: "To Tattenai, governor of the province west of the Euphrates River, to Shethar-bozenai, and to your colleagues and other officials west of the Euphrates: "Stay away from there!', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 7, 'Do not disturb the construction of the Temple of God. Let it be rebuilt on its former site, and do not hinder the governor of Judah and the leaders of the Jews in their work.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 8, 'Moreover I hereby decree that you are to help these leaders of the Jews as they rebuild this Temple of God. You must pay the full construction costs without delay from my taxes collected in your province so that the work will not be discontinued.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 9, 'Give the priests in Jerusalem whatever is needed in the way of young bulls, rams, and lambs for the burnt offerings presented to the God of heaven. And without fail, provide them with the wheat, salt, wine, and olive oil that they need each day.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 10, 'Then they will be able to offer acceptable sacrifices to the God of heaven and pray for me and my sons.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 11, '"Those who violate this decree in any way will have a beam pulled from their house. Then they will be tied to it and flogged, and their house will be reduced to a pile of rubble.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 12, 'May the God who has chosen the city of Jerusalem as the place to honor his name destroy any king or nation that violates this command and destroys this Temple. I, Darius, have issued this decree. Let it be obeyed with all diligence."', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 13, 'Tattenai, governor of the province west of the Euphrates River, and Shethar-bozenai and their colleagues complied at once with the command of King Darius.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 14, 'So the Jewish leaders continued their work, and they were greatly encouraged by the preaching of the prophets Haggai and Zechariah son of Iddo. The Temple was finally finished, as had been commanded by the God of Israel and decreed by Cyrus, Darius, and Artaxerxes, the kings of Persia.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 15, 'The Temple was completed on March 12, during the sixth year of King Darius''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 16, 'The Temple of God was then dedicated with great joy by the people of Israel, the priests, the Levites, and the rest of the people who had returned from exile.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 17, 'During the dedication ceremony for the Temple of God, one hundred young bulls, two hundred rams, and four hundred lambs were sacrificed. And twelve male goats were presented as a sin offering for the twelve tribes of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 18, 'Then the priests and Levites were divided into their various divisions to serve at the Temple of God in Jerusalem, following all the instructions recorded in the Book of Moses.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 19, 'On April 21 the returned exiles celebrated Passover.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 20, 'The priests and Levites had purified themselves and were ceremonially clean. So they slaughtered the Passover lamb for all the returned exiles, for the other priests, and for themselves.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 21, 'The Passover meal was eaten by the people of Israel who had returned from exile and by the others in the land who had turned from their immoral customs to worship the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(19, 6, 22, 'They ate the Passover meal and celebrated the Festival of Unleavened Bread for seven days. There was great joy throughout the land because the LORD had changed the attitude of the king of Assyria toward them, so that he helped them to rebuild the Temple of God, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 1, 'Many years later, during the reign of King Artaxerxes of Persia, there was a man named Ezra. He was the son of Seraiah, son of Azariah, son of Hilkiah,', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 2, 'son of Shallum, son of Zadok, son of Ahitub,', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 3, 'son of Amariah, son of Azariah, son of Meraioth,', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 4, 'son of Zerahiah, son of Uzzi, son of Bukki,', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 5, 'son of Abishua, son of Phinehas, son of Eleazar, son of Aaron the high priest.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 6, 'This Ezra was a scribe, well versed in the law of Moses, which the LORD, the God of Israel, had given to the people of Israel. He came up to Jerusalem from Babylon, and the king gave him everything he asked for, because the gracious hand of the LORD his God was on him.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 7, 'Some of the people of Israel, as well as some of the priests, Levites, singers, gatekeepers, and Temple servants, traveled up to Jerusalem with him in the seventh year of King Artaxerxes'' reign.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 8, 'Ezra arrived in Jerusalem in August of that year.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 9, 'He had left Babylon on April 8 and came to Jerusalem on August 4, for the gracious hand of his God was on him.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 10, 'This was because Ezra had determined to study and obey the law of the LORD and to teach those laws and regulations to the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 11, 'King Artaxerxes had given a copy of the following letter to Ezra, the priest and scribe who studied and taught the commands and laws of the LORD to Israel:', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 12, '"Greetings from Artaxerxes, the king of kings, to Ezra the priest, the teacher of the law of the God of heaven.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 13, '"I decree that any of the people of Israel in my kingdom, including the priests and Levites, may volunteer to return to Jerusalem with you.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 14, 'I and my Council of Seven hereby instruct you to conduct an inquiry into the situation in Judah and Jerusalem, based on your God''s law, which is in your hand.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 15, 'We also commission you to take with you some silver and gold, which we are freely presenting as an offering to the God of Israel who lives in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 16, '"Moreover you are to take any silver and gold which you may obtain from the province of Babylon, as well as the freewill offerings of the people and the priests that are presented for the Temple of their God in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 17, 'These donations are to be used specifically for the purchase of bulls, rams, lambs, and the appropriate grain offerings and drink offerings, all of which will be offered on the altar of the Temple of your God in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 18, 'Any money that is left over may be used in whatever way you and your colleagues feel is the will of your God.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 19, 'But as for the utensils we are entrusting to you for the service of the Temple of your God, deliver them in full to the God of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 20, 'If you run short of money for anything necessary for your God''s Temple or for any similar needs, you may requisition funds from the royal treasury.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 21, '"I, Artaxerxes the king, hereby send this decree to all the treasurers in the province west of the Euphrates River: `You are to give Ezra whatever he requests of you, for he is a priest and teacher of the law of the God of heaven.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 22, 'You are to give him up to 7,500 pounds of silver, 500 bushels of wheat, 550 gallons of wine, 550 gallons of olive oil, and an unlimited supply of salt.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 23, 'Be careful to provide whatever the God of heaven demands for his Temple, for why should we risk bringing God''s anger against the realm of the king and his sons?', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 24, 'I also decree that no priest, Levite, singer, gatekeeper, Temple servant, or other worker in this Temple of God will be required to pay taxes of any kind.''', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 25, '"And you, Ezra, are to use the wisdom God has given you to appoint magistrates and judges who know your God''s laws to govern all the people in the province west of the Euphrates River. If the people are not familiar with those laws, you must teach them.', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 26, 'Anyone who refuses to obey the law of your God and the law of the king will be punished immediately by death, banishment, confiscation of goods, or imprisonment."', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 27, 'Praise the LORD, the God of our ancestors, who made the king want to beautify the Temple of the LORD in Jerusalem!', 'NLT'),
(19, 7, 28, 'And praise him for demonstrating such unfailing love to me by honoring me before the king, his council, and all his mighty princes! I felt encouraged because the gracious hand of the LORD my God was on me. And I gathered some of the leaders of Israel to return with me to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 1, 'Here is a list of the family leaders and the genealogies of those who came with me from Babylon during the reign of King Artaxerxes:', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 2, 'From the family of Phinehas: Gershom. From the family of Ithamar: Daniel.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 3, 'From the family of David: Hattush son of Shecaniah. From the family of Parosh: Zechariah and 150 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 4, 'From the family of Pahath-moab: Eliehoenai son of Zerahiah and 200 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 5, 'From the family of Zattu: Shecaniah son of Jahaziel and 300 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 6, 'From the family of Adin: Ebed son of Jonathan and 50 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 7, 'From the family of Elam: Jeshaiah son of Athaliah and 70 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 8, 'From the family of Shephatiah: Zebadiah son of Michael and 80 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 9, 'From the family of Joab: Obadiah son of Jehiel and 218 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 10, 'From the family of Bani: Shelomith son of Josiphiah and 160 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 11, 'From the family of Bebai: Zechariah son of Bebai and 28 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 12, 'From the family of Azgad: Johanan son of Hakkatan and 110 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 13, 'From the family of Adonikam, who came later: Eliphelet, Jeuel, Shemaiah, and 60 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 14, 'From the family of Bigvai: Uthai, Zaccur, and 70 other men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 15, 'I assembled the exiles at the Ahava Canal, and we camped there for three days while I went over the lists of the people and the priests who had arrived. I found that not one Levite had volunteered to come along.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 16, 'So I sent for Eliezer, Ariel, Shemaiah, Elnathan, Jarib, Elnathan, Nathan, Zechariah, and Meshullam, who were leaders of the people. I also sent for Joiarib and Elnathan, who were very wise men.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 17, 'I sent them to Iddo, the leader of the Levites at Casiphia, to ask him and his relatives and the Temple servants to send us ministers for the Temple of God at Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 18, 'Since the gracious hand of our God was on us, they sent us a man named Sherebiah, along with eighteen of his sons and brothers. He was a very astute man and a descendant of Mahli, who was a descendant of Levi son of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 19, 'They also sent Hashabiah, together with Jeshaiah from the descendants of Merari, and twenty of his sons and brothers,', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 20, 'and 220 Temple servants. The Temple servants were assistants to the Levites--a group of Temple workers first instituted by King David. They were all listed by name.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 21, 'And there by the Ahava Canal, I gave orders for all of us to fast and humble ourselves before our God. We prayed that he would give us a safe journey and protect us, our children, and our goods as we traveled.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 22, 'For I was ashamed to ask the king for soldiers and horsemen to accompany us and protect us from enemies along the way. After all, we had told the king, "Our God protects all those who worship him, but his fierce anger rages against those who abandon him."', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 23, 'So we fasted and earnestly prayed that our God would take care of us, and he heard our prayer.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 24, 'I appointed twelve leaders of the priests--Sherebiah, Hashabiah, and ten other priests--', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 25, 'to be in charge of transporting the silver, the gold, the gold bowls, and the other items that the king, his council, his leaders, and the people of Israel had presented for the Temple of God.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 26, 'I weighed the treasure as I gave it to them and found the totals to be as follows: 24 tons of silver, 7,500 pounds of silver utensils, 7,500 pounds of gold,', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 27, '20 gold bowls, equal in value to 1,000 gold coins, 2 fine articles of polished bronze, as precious as gold.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 28, 'And I said to these priests, "You and these treasures have been set apart as holy to the LORD. This silver and gold is a freewill offering to the LORD, the God of our ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 29, 'Guard these treasures well until you present them, without an ounce lost, to the leading priests, the Levites, and the leaders of Israel at the storerooms of the LORD''s Temple in Jerusalem."', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 30, 'So the priests and the Levites accepted the task of transporting these treasures to the Temple of our God in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 31, 'We broke camp at the Ahava Canal on April 19 and started off to Jerusalem. And the gracious hand of our God protected us and saved us from enemies and bandits along the way.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 32, 'So at last we arrived safely in Jerusalem, where we rested for three days.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 33, 'On the fourth day after our arrival, the silver, gold, and other valuables were weighed at the Temple of our God and entrusted to Meremoth son of Uriah the priest and to Eleazar son of Phinehas, along with Jozabad son of Jeshua and Noadiah son of Binnui--both of whom were Levites.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 34, 'Everything was accounted for by number and weight, and the total weight was officially recorded.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 35, 'Then the exiles who had returned from captivity sacrificed burnt offerings to the God of Israel. They presented twelve oxen for the people of Israel, as well as ninety-six rams and seventy-seven lambs. They also offered twelve goats as a sin offering. All this was given as a burnt offering to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(19, 8, 36, 'The king''s decrees were delivered to his lieutenants and the governors of the province west of the Euphrates River, who then cooperated by supporting the people and the Temple of God.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 1, 'But then the Jewish leaders came to me and said, "Many of the people of Israel, and even some of the priests and Levites, have not kept themselves separate from the other peoples living in the land. They have taken up the detestable practices of the Canaanites, Hittites, Perizzites, Jebusites, Ammonites, Moabites, Egyptians, and Amorites.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 2, 'For the men of Israel have married women from these people and have taken them as wives for their sons. So the holy race has become polluted by these mixed marriages. To make matters worse, the officials and leaders are some of the worst offenders."', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 3, 'When I heard this, I tore my clothing, pulled hair from my head and beard, and sat down utterly shocked.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 4, 'Then all who trembled at the words of the God of Israel came and sat with me because of this unfaithfulness of his people. And I sat there utterly appalled until the time of the evening sacrifice.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 5, 'At the time of the sacrifice, I stood up from where I had sat in mourning with my clothes torn. I fell to my knees, lifted my hands to the LORD my God.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 6, 'I prayed, "O my God, I am utterly ashamed; I blush to lift up my face to you. For our sins are piled higher than our heads, and our guilt has reached to the heavens.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 7, 'Our whole history has been one of great sin. That is why we and our kings and our priests have been at the mercy of the pagan kings of the land. We have been killed, captured, robbed, and disgraced, just as we are today.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 8, '"But now we have been given a brief moment of grace, for the LORD our God has allowed a few of us to survive as a remnant. He has given us security in this holy place. Our God has brightened our eyes and granted us some relief from our slavery.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 9, 'For we were slaves, but in his unfailing love our God did not abandon us in our slavery. Instead, he caused the kings of Persia to treat us favorably. He revived us so that we were able to rebuild the Temple of our God and repair its ruins. He has given us a protective wall in Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 10, '"And now, O our God, what can we say after all of this? For once again we have ignored your commands!', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 11, 'Your servants the prophets warned us that the land we would possess was totally defiled by the detestable practices of the people living there. From one end to the other, the land is filled with corruption.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 12, 'You told us not to let our daughters marry their sons, and not to let our sons marry their daughters, and not to help those nations in any way. You promised that if we avoided these things, we would become a prosperous nation. You promised that we would enjoy the good produce of the land and leave this prosperity to our children as an inheritance forever.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 13, '"Now we are being punished because of our wickedness and our great guilt. But we have actually been punished far less than we deserve, for you, our God, have allowed some of us to survive as a remnant.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 14, 'But now we are again breaking your commands and intermarrying with people who do these detestable things. Surely your anger will destroy us until even this little remnant no longer survives.', 'NLT'),
(19, 9, 15, 'O LORD, God of Israel, you are just. We stand before you in our guilt as nothing but an escaped remnant, though in such a condition none of us can stand in your presence."', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 1, 'While Ezra prayed and made this confession, weeping and throwing himself to the ground in front of the Temple of God, a large crowd of people from Israel--men, women, and children--gathered and wept bitterly with him.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 2, 'Then Shecaniah son of Jehiel, a descendant of Elam, said to Ezra, "We confess that we have been unfaithful to our God, for we have married these pagan women of the land. But there is hope for Israel in spite of this.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 3, 'Let us now make a covenant with our God to divorce our pagan wives and to send them away with their children. We will follow the advice given by you and by the others who respect the commands of our God. We will obey the law of God.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 4, 'Take courage, for it is your duty to tell us how to proceed in setting things straight, and we will cooperate fully."', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 5, 'So Ezra stood up and demanded that the leaders of the priests and the Levites and all the people of Israel swear that they would do as Shecaniah had said. And they all swore a solemn oath.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 6, 'Then Ezra left the front of the Temple of God and went to the room of Jehohanan son of Eliashib. He spent the night there, but he did not eat any food or drink. He was still in mourning because of the unfaithfulness of the returned exiles.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 7, 'Then a proclamation was made throughout Judah and Jerusalem that all the returned exiles should come to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 8, 'Those who failed to come within three days would, if the leaders and elders so decided, forfeit all their property and be expelled from the assembly of the exiles.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 9, 'Within three days, all the people of Judah and Benjamin had gathered in Jerusalem. This took place on December 19, and all the people were sitting in the square before the Temple of God. They were trembling both because of the seriousness of the matter and because it was raining.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 10, 'Then Ezra the priest stood and said to them: "You have sinned, for you have married pagan women. Now we are even more deeply under condemnation than we were before.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 11, 'Confess your sin to the LORD, the God of your ancestors, and do what he demands. Separate yourselves from the people of the land and from these pagan women."', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 12, 'Then the whole assembly raised their voices and answered, "Yes, you are right; we must do as you say!"', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 13, 'Then they added, "This isn''t something that can be done in a day or two, for many of us are involved in this extremely sinful affair. This is the rainy season, so we cannot stay out here much longer.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 14, 'Let our leaders act on behalf of us all. Everyone who has a pagan wife will come at the scheduled time with the leaders and judges of his city, so that the fierce anger of our God may be turned away from us concerning this affair."', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 15, 'Only Jonathan son of Asahel and Jahzeiah son of Tikvah opposed this course of action, and Meshullam and Shabbethai the Levite supported them.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 16, 'So this was the plan that they followed. Ezra selected leaders to represent their families, designating each of the representatives by name. On December 29, the leaders sat down to investigate the matter.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 17, 'By March 27 of the next year they had finished dealing with all the men who had married pagan wives.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 18, 'These are the priests who had married pagan wives: From the family of Jeshua son of Jehozadak and his brothers: Maaseiah, Eliezer, Jarib, and Gedaliah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 19, 'They vowed to divorce their wives, and they each acknowledged their guilt by offering a ram as a guilt offering.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 20, 'From the family of Immer: Hanani and Zebadiah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 21, 'From the family of Harim: Maaseiah, Elijah, Shemaiah, Jehiel, and Uzziah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 22, 'From the family of Pashhur: Elioenai, Maaseiah, Ishmael, Nethanel, Jozabad, and Elasah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 23, 'These are the Levites who were guilty: Jozabad, Shimei, Kelaiah (also called Kelita), Pethahiah, Judah, and Eliezer.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 24, 'This is the singer who was guilty: Eliashib. These are the gatekeepers who were guilty: Shallum, Telem, and Uri.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 25, 'These are the other people of Israel who were guilty: From the family of Parosh: Ramiah, Izziah, Malkijah, Mijamin, Eleazar, Hashabiah, and Benaiah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 26, 'From the family of Elam: Mattaniah, Zechariah, Jehiel, Abdi, Jeremoth, and Elijah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 27, 'From the family of Zattu: Elioenai, Eliashib, Mattaniah, Jeremoth, Zabad, and Aziza.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 28, 'From the family of Bebai: Jehohanan, Hananiah, Zabbai, and Athlai.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 29, 'From the family of Bani: Meshullam, Malluch, Adaiah, Jashub, Sheal, and Jeremoth.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 30, 'From the family of Pahath-moab: Adna, Kelal, Benaiah, Maaseiah, Mattaniah, Bezalel, Binnui, and Manasseh.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 31, 'From the family of Harim: Eliezer, Ishijah, Malkijah, Shemaiah, Shimeon,', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 32, 'Benjamin, Malluch, and Shemariah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 33, 'From the family of Hashum: Mattenai, Mattattah, Zabad, Eliphelet, Jeremai, Manasseh, and Shimei.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 34, 'From the family of Bani: Maadai, Amram, Uel,', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 35, 'Benaiah, Bedeiah, Keluhi,', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 36, 'Vaniah, Meremoth, Eliashib,', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 37, 'Mattaniah, Mattenai, and Jaasu.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 38, 'From the family of Binnui: Shimei,', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 39, 'Shelemiah, Nathan, Adaiah,', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 40, 'Macnadebai, Shashai, Sharai,', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 41, 'Azarel, Shelemiah, Shemariah,', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 42, 'Shallum, Amariah, and Joseph.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 43, 'From the family of Nebo: Jeiel, Mattithiah, Zabad, Zebina, Jaddai, Joel, and Benaiah.', 'NLT'),
(19, 10, 44, 'Each of these men had a pagan wife, and some even had children by these wives.', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 1, 'These are the memoirs of Nehemiah son of Hacaliah. In late autumn of the twentieth year of King Artaxerxes'' reign, I was at the fortress of Susa.', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 2, 'Hanani, one of my brothers, came to visit me with some other men who had just arrived from Judah. I asked them about the Jews who had survived the captivity and about how things were going in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 3, 'They said to me, "Things are not going well for those who returned to the province of Judah. They are in great trouble and disgrace. The wall of Jerusalem has been torn down, and the gates have been burned."', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 4, 'When I heard this, I sat down and wept. In fact, for days I mourned, fasted, and prayed to the God of heaven.', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 5, 'Then I said, "O LORD, God of heaven, the great and awesome God who keeps his covenant of unfailing love with those who love him and obey his commands,', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 6, 'listen to my prayer! Look down and see me praying night and day for your people Israel. I confess that we have sinned against you. Yes, even my own family and I have sinned!', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 7, 'We have sinned terribly by not obeying the commands, laws, and regulations that you gave us through your servant Moses.', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 8, '"Please remember what you told your servant Moses: ''If you sin, I will scatter you among the nations.', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 9, 'But if you return to me and obey my commands, even if you are exiled to the ends of the earth, I will bring you back to the place I have chosen for my name to be honored.''', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 10, '"We are your servants, the people you rescued by your great power and might.', 'NLT'),
(20, 1, 11, 'O Lord, please hear my prayer! Listen to the prayers of those of us who delight in honoring you. Please grant me success now as I go to ask the king for a great favor. Put it into his heart to be kind to me." In those days I was the king''s cup-bearer.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 1, 'Early the following spring, during the twentieth year of King Artaxerxes'' reign, I was serving the king his wine. I had never appeared sad in his presence before this time.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 2, 'So the king asked me, "Why are you so sad? You aren''t sick, are you? You look like a man with deep troubles." Then I was badly frightened,', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 3, 'but I replied, "Long live the king! Why shouldn''t I be sad? For the city where my ancestors are buried is in ruins, and the gates have been burned down."', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 4, 'The king asked, "Well, how can I help you?" With a prayer to the God of heaven,', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 5, 'I replied, "If it please Your Majesty and if you are pleased with me, your servant, send me to Judah to rebuild the city where my ancestors are buried."', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 6, 'The king, with the queen sitting beside him, asked, "How long will you be gone? When will you return?" So the king agreed, and I set a date for my departure.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 7, 'I also said to the king, "If it please Your Majesty, give me letters to the governors of the province west of the Euphrates River, instructing them to let me travel safely through their territories on my way to Judah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 8, 'And please send a letter to Asaph, the manager of the king''s forest, instructing him to give me timber. I will need it to make beams for the gates of the Temple fortress, for the city walls, and for a house for myself." And the king granted these requests, because the gracious hand of God was on me.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 9, 'When I came to the governors of the province west of the Euphrates River, I delivered the king''s letters to them. The king, I should add, had sent along army officers and horsemen to protect me.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 10, 'But when Sanballat the Horonite and Tobiah the Ammonite official heard of my arrival, they were very angry that someone had come who was interested in helping Israel.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 11, 'Three days after my arrival at Jerusalem,', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 12, 'I slipped out during the night, taking only a few others with me. I had not told anyone about the plans God had put in my heart for Jerusalem. We took no pack animals with us, except the donkey that I myself was riding.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 13, 'I went out through the Valley Gate, past the Jackal''s Well, and over to the Dung Gate to inspect the broken walls and burned gates.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 14, 'Then I went to the Fountain Gate and to the King''s Pool, but my donkey couldn''t get through the rubble.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 15, 'So I went up the Kidron Valley instead, inspecting the wall before I turned back and entered again at the Valley Gate.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 16, 'The city officials did not know I had been out there or what I was doing, for I had not yet said anything to anyone about my plans. I had not yet spoken to the religious and political leaders, the officials, or anyone else in the administration.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 17, 'But now I said to them, "You know full well the tragedy of our city. It lies in ruins, and its gates are burned. Let us rebuild the wall of Jerusalem and rid ourselves of this disgrace!"', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 18, 'Then I told them about how the gracious hand of God had been on me, and about my conversation with the king. They replied at once, "Good! Let''s rebuild the wall!" So they began the good work.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 19, 'But when Sanballat, Tobiah, and Geshem the Arab heard of our plan, they scoffed contemptuously. "What are you doing, rebelling against the king like this?" they asked.', 'NLT'),
(20, 2, 20, 'But I replied, "The God of heaven will help us succeed. We his servants will start rebuilding this wall. But you have no stake or claim in Jerusalem."', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 1, 'Then Eliashib the high priest and the other priests started to rebuild at the Sheep Gate. They dedicated it and set up its doors, building the wall as far as the Tower of the Hundred, which they dedicated, and the Tower of Hananel.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 2, 'People from the city of Jericho worked next to them, and beyond them was Zaccur son of Imri.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 3, 'The Fish Gate was built by the sons of Hassenaah. They did the whole thing--laid the beams, hung the doors, and put the bolts and bars in place.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 4, 'Meremoth son of Uriah and grandson of Hakkoz repaired the next section of wall. Beside him were Meshullam son of Berekiah and grandson of Meshezabel, and then Zadok son of Baana.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 5, 'Next were the people from Tekoa, though their leaders refused to help.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 6, 'The Old City Gate was repaired by Joiada son of Paseah and Meshullam son of Besodeiah. They laid the beams, set up the doors, and installed the bolts and bars.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 7, 'Next to them were Melatiah from Gibeon, Jadon from Meronoth, and people from Gibeon and Mizpah, the headquarters of the governor of the province west of the Euphrates River.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 8, 'Next was Uzziel son of Harhaiah, a goldsmith by trade, who also worked on the wall. Beyond him was Hananiah, a manufacturer of perfumes. They left out a section of Jerusalem as far as the Broad Wall.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 9, 'Rephaiah son of Hur, the leader of half the district of Jerusalem, was next to them on the wall.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 10, 'Next Jedaiah son of Harumaph repaired the wall beside his own house, and next to him was Hattush son of Hashabneiah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 11, 'Then came Malkijah son of Harim and Hasshub son of Pahath-moab, who repaired the Tower of the Ovens, in addition to another section of the wall.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 12, 'Shallum son of Hallohesh and his daughters repaired the next section. He was the leader of the other half of the district of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 13, 'The people from Zanoah, led by Hanun, rebuilt the Valley Gate, hung its doors, and installed the bolts and bars. They also repaired the fifteen hundred feet of wall to the Dung Gate.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 14, 'The Dung Gate was repaired by Malkijah son of Recab, the leader of the Beth-hakkerem district. After rebuilding it, he hung the doors and installed the bolts and bars.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 15, 'Shallum son of Col-hozeh, the leader of the Mizpah district, repaired the Fountain Gate. He rebuilt it, roofed it, hung its doors, and installed its bolts and bars. Then he repaired the wall of the pool of Siloam near the king''s garden, and he rebuilt the wall as far as the stairs that descend from the City of David.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 16, 'Next to him was Nehemiah son of Azbuk, the leader of half the district of Beth-zur. He rebuilt the wall to a place opposite the royal cemetery as far as the water reservoir and the House of the Warriors.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 17, 'Next was a group of Levites working under the supervision of Rehum son of Bani. Then came Hashabiah, the leader of half the district of Keilah, who supervised the building of the wall on behalf of his own district.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 18, 'Next down the line were his countrymen led by Binnui son of Henadad, the leader of the other half of the district of Keilah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 19, 'Next to them, Ezer son of Jeshua, the leader of Mizpah, repaired another section of wall opposite the armory by the buttress.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 20, 'Next to him was Baruch son of Zabbai, who repaired an additional section from the buttress to the door of the home of Eliashib the high priest.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 21, 'Meremoth son of Uriah and grandson of Hakkoz rebuilt another section of the wall extending from a point opposite the door of Eliashib''s house to the side of the house.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 22, 'Then came the priests from the surrounding region.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 23, 'After them, Benjamin, Hasshub, and Azariah son of Maaseiah and grandson of Ananiah repaired the sections next to their own houses.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 24, 'Next was Binnui son of Henadad, who rebuilt another section of the wall from Azariah''s house to the buttress and the corner.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 25, 'Palal son of Uzai carried on the work from a point opposite the buttress and the corner to the upper tower that projects from the king''s house beside the court of the guard. Next to him were Pedaiah son of Parosh', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 26, 'and the Temple servants living on the hill of Ophel, who repaired the wall as far as the Water Gate toward the east and the projecting tower.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 27, 'Then came the people of Tekoa, who repaired another section opposite the great projecting tower and over to the wall of Ophel.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 28, 'The priests repaired the wall up the hill from the Horse Gate, each one doing the section immediately opposite his own house.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 29, 'Next Zadok son of Immer also rebuilt the wall next to his own house, and beyond him was Shemaiah son of Shecaniah, the gatekeeper of the East Gate.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 30, 'Next Hananiah son of Shelemiah and Hanun, the sixth son of Zalaph, repaired another section, while Meshullam son of Berekiah rebuilt the wall next to his own house.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 31, 'Malkijah, one of the goldsmiths, repaired the wall as far as the housing for the Temple servants and merchants, opposite the Inspection Gate. Then he continued as far as the upper room at the corner.', 'NLT'),
(20, 3, 32, 'The other goldsmiths and merchants repaired the wall from that corner to the Sheep Gate.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 1, 'Sanballat was very angry when he learned that we were rebuilding the wall. He flew into a rage and mocked the Jews,', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 2, 'saying in front of his friends and the Samarian army officers, "What does this bunch of poor, feeble Jews think they are doing? Do they think they can build the wall in a day if they offer enough sacrifices? Look at those charred stones they are pulling out of the rubbish and using again!"', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 3, 'Tobiah the Ammonite, who was standing beside him, remarked, "That stone wall would collapse if even a fox walked along the top of it!"', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 4, 'Then I prayed, "Hear us, O our God, for we are being mocked. May their scoffing fall back on their own heads, and may they themselves become captives in a foreign land!', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 5, 'Do not ignore their guilt. Do not blot out their sins, for they have provoked you to anger here in the presence of the builders."', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 6, 'At last the wall was completed to half its original height around the entire city, for the people had worked very hard.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 7, 'But when Sanballat and Tobiah and the Arabs, Ammonites, and Ashdodites heard that the work was going ahead and that the gaps in the wall were being repaired, they became furious.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 8, 'They all made plans to come and fight against Jerusalem and to bring about confusion there.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 9, 'But we prayed to our God and guarded the city day and night to protect ourselves.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 10, 'Then the people of Judah began to complain that the workers were becoming tired. There was so much rubble to be moved that we could never get it done by ourselves.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 11, 'Meanwhile, our enemies were saying, "Before they know what''s happening, we will swoop down on them and kill them and end their work."', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 12, 'The Jews who lived near the enemy came and told us again and again, "They will come from all directions and attack us!"', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 13, 'So I placed armed guards behind the lowest parts of the wall in the exposed areas. I stationed the people to stand guard by families, armed with swords, spears, and bows.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 14, 'Then as I looked over the situation, I called together the leaders and the people and said to them, "Don''t be afraid of the enemy! Remember the Lord, who is great and glorious, and fight for your friends, your families, and your homes!"', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 15, 'When our enemies heard that we knew of their plans and that God had frustrated them, we all returned to our work on the wall.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 16, 'But from then on, only half my men worked while the other half stood guard with spears, shields, bows, and coats of mail. The officers stationed themselves behind the people of Judah', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 17, 'who were building the wall. The common laborers carried on their work with one hand supporting their load and one hand holding a weapon.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 18, 'All the builders had a sword belted to their side. The trumpeter stayed with me to sound the alarm.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 19, 'Then I explained to the nobles and officials and all the people, "The work is very spread out, and we are widely separated from each other along the wall.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 20, 'When you hear the blast of the trumpet, rush to wherever it is sounding. Then our God will fight for us!"', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 21, 'We worked early and late, from sunrise to sunset. And half the men were always on guard.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 22, 'I also told everyone living outside the walls to move into Jerusalem. That way they and their servants could go on guard duty at night as well as work during the day.', 'NLT'),
(20, 4, 23, 'During this time, none of us--not I, nor my relatives, nor my servants, nor the guards who were with me--ever took off our clothes. We carried our weapons with us at all times, even when we went for water.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 1, 'About this time some of the men and their wives raised a cry of protest against their fellow Jews.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 2, 'They were saying, "We have such large families. We need more money just so we can buy the food we need to survive."', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 3, 'Others said, "We have mortgaged our fields, vineyards, and homes to get food during the famine."', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 4, 'And others said, "We have already borrowed to the limit on our fields and vineyards to pay our taxes.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 5, 'We belong to the same family, and our children are just like theirs. Yet we must sell our children into slavery just to get enough money to live. We have already sold some of our daughters, and we are helpless to do anything about it, for our fields and vineyards are already mortgaged to others."', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 6, 'When I heard their complaints, I was very angry.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 7, 'After thinking about the situation, I spoke out against these nobles and officials. I told them, "You are oppressing your own relatives by charging them interest when they borrow money!" Then I called a public meeting to deal with the problem.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 8, 'At the meeting I said to them, "The rest of us are doing all we can to redeem our Jewish relatives who have had to sell themselves to pagan foreigners, but you are selling them back into slavery again. How often must we redeem them?" And they had nothing to say in their defense.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 9, 'Then I pressed further, "What you are doing is not right! Should you not walk in the fear of our God in order to avoid being mocked by enemy nations?', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 10, 'I myself, as well as my brothers and my workers, have been lending the people money and grain, but now let us stop this business of loans.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 11, 'You must restore their fields, vineyards, olive groves, and homes to them this very day. Repay the interest you charged on their money, grain, wine, and olive oil."', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 12, 'Then they replied, "We will give back everything and demand nothing more from the people. We will do as you say." Then I called the priests and made the nobles and officials formally vow to do what they had promised.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 13, 'I shook out the fold of my robe and said, "If you fail to keep your promise, may God shake you from your homes and from your property!" The whole assembly responded, "Amen," and they praised the LORD. And the people did as they had promised.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 14, 'I would like to mention that for the entire twelve years that I was governor of Judah--from the twentieth until the thirty-second year of the reign of King Artaxerxes--neither I nor my officials drew on our official food allowance.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 15, 'This was quite a contrast to the former governors who had laid heavy burdens on the people, demanding a daily ration of food and wine, besides a pound of silver. Even their assistants took advantage of the people. But because of my fear of God, I did not act that way.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 16, 'I devoted myself to working on the wall and refused to acquire any land. And I required all my officials to spend time working on the wall.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 17, 'I asked for nothing, even though I regularly fed 150 Jewish officials at my table, besides all the visitors from other lands!', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 18, 'The provisions required at my expense for each day were one ox, six fat sheep, and a large number of domestic fowl. And every ten days we needed a large supply of all kinds of wine. Yet I refused to claim the governor''s food allowance because the people were already having a difficult time.', 'NLT'),
(20, 5, 19, 'Remember, O my God, all that I have done for these people, and bless me for it.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 1, 'When Sanballat, Tobiah, Geshem the Arab, and the rest of our enemies found out that I had finished rebuilding the wall and that no gaps remained--though we had not yet hung the doors in the gates--', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 2, 'Sanballat and Geshem sent me a message asking me to meet them at one of the villages in the plain of Ono. But I realized they were plotting to harm me,', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 3, 'so I replied by sending this message to them: "I am doing a great work! I cannot stop to come and meet with you."', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 4, 'Four times they sent the same message, and each time I gave the same reply.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 5, 'The fifth time, Sanballat''s servant came with an open letter in his hand,', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 6, 'and this is what it said: "Geshem tells me that everywhere he goes he hears that you and the Jews are planning to rebel and that is why you are building the wall. According to his reports, you plan to be their king.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 7, 'He also reports that you have appointed prophets to prophesy about you in Jerusalem, saying, ''Look! There is a king in Judah!''"You can be very sure that this report will get back to the king, so I suggest that you come and talk it over with me."', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 8, 'My reply was, "You know you are lying. There is no truth in any part of your story."', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 9, 'They were just trying to intimidate us, imagining that they could break our resolve and stop the work. So I prayed for strength to continue the work.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 10, 'Later I went to visit Shemaiah son of Delaiah and grandson of Mehetabel, who was confined to his home. He said, "Let us meet together inside the Temple of God and bolt the doors shut. Your enemies are coming to kill you tonight."', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 11, 'But I replied, "Should someone in my position run away from danger? Should someone in my position enter the Temple to save his life? No, I won''t do it!"', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 12, 'I realized that God had not spoken to him, but that he had uttered this prophecy against me because Tobiah and Sanballat had hired him.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 13, 'They were hoping to intimidate me and make me sin by following his suggestion. Then they would be able to accuse and discredit me.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 14, 'Remember, O my God, all the evil things that Tobiah and Sanballat have done. And remember Noadiah the prophet and all the prophets like her who have tried to intimidate me.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 15, 'So on October 2 the wall was finally finished--just fifty-two days after we had begun.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 16, 'When our enemies and the surrounding nations heard about it, they were frightened and humiliated. They realized that this work had been done with the help of our God.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 17, 'During those fifty-two days, many letters went back and forth between Tobiah and the officials of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 18, 'For many in Judah had sworn allegiance to him because his father-in-law was Shecaniah son of Arah and because his son Jehohanan was married to the daughter of Meshullam son of Berekiah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 6, 19, 'They kept telling me what a wonderful man Tobiah was, and then they told him everything I said. And Tobiah sent many threatening letters to intimidate me.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 1, 'After the wall was finished and I had hung the doors in the gates, the gatekeepers, singers, and Levites were appointed.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 2, 'I gave the responsibility of governing Jerusalem to my brother Hanani, along with Hananiah, the commander of the fortress, for he was a faithful man who feared God more than most.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 3, 'I said to them, "Do not leave the gates open during the hottest part of the day. And while the gatekeepers are still on duty, have them shut and bar the doors. Appoint the residents of Jerusalem to act as guards, everyone on a regular watch. Some will serve at their regular posts and some in front of their own homes."', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 4, 'At that time the city was large and spacious, but the population was small. And only a few houses were scattered throughout the city.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 5, 'So my God gave me the idea to call together all the leaders of the city, along with the ordinary citizens, for registration. I had found the genealogical record of those who had first returned to Judah. This is what was written there:', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 6, '"Here is the list of the Jewish exiles of the provinces who returned from their captivity to Jerusalem and to the other towns of Judah. They had been deported to Babylon by King Nebuchadnezzar.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 7, 'Their leaders were Zerubbabel, Jeshua, Nehemiah, Seraiah, Reelaiah, Nahamani, Mordecai, Bilshan, Mispar, Bigvai, Rehum, and Baanah. This is the number of men of Israel who returned from exile:', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 8, 'The family of Parosh.................... 2,172', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 9, 'The family of Shephatiah.................. 372', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 10, 'The family of Arah...................... 652', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 11, 'The family of Pahath-moab (descendants of Jeshua and Joab)......... 2,818', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 12, 'The family of Elam..................... 1,254', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 13, 'The family of Zattu....................... 845', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 14, 'The family of Zaccai...................... 760', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 15, 'The family of Bani..................... 648', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 16, 'The family of Bebai...................... 628', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 17, 'The family of Azgad.................... 2,322', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 18, 'The family of Adonikam.................. 667', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 19, 'The family of Bigvai.................... 2,067', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 20, 'The family of Adin...................... 655', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 21, 'The family of Ater (descendants of Hezekiah)................. 98', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 22, 'The family of Hashum.................... 328', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 23, 'The family of Bezai...................... 324', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 24, 'The family of Jorah.................... 112', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 25, 'The family of Gibbar.................... 95', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 26, 'The peoples of Bethlehem and Netophah......................... 188', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 27, 'The people of Anathoth.................... 128', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 28, 'The people of Beth-azmaveth............... 42', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 29, 'The peoples of Kiriath-jearim, Kephirah, and Beeroth................... 743', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 30, 'The peoples of Ramah and Geba............. 621', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 31, 'The people of Micmash.................... 122', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 32, 'The peoples of Bethel and Ai................ 123', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 33, 'The people of Nebo........................ 52', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 34, 'The citizens of Elam...................... 1,254', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 35, 'The citizens of Harim...................... 320', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 36, 'The citizens of Jericho..................... 345', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 37, 'The citizens of Lod, Hadid, and Ono.............................. 721', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 38, 'The citizens of Senaah.................... 3,930', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 39, '"These are the priests who returned from exile: The family of Jedaiah (through the line of Jeshua)...... 973', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 40, 'The family of Immer.......... 1,052', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 41, 'The family of Pashhur......... 1,247', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 42, 'The family of Harim.......... 1,017', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 43, '"These are the Levites who returned from exile: The families of Jeshua and Kadmiel (descendants of Hodaviah )...... 74', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 44, 'The singers of the family of Asaph...148', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 45, 'The gatekeepers of the families of Shallum, Ater, Talmon, Akkub, Hatita, and Shobai.............. 138', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 46, '"The descendants of the following Temple servants returned from exile: Ziha, Hasupha, Tabbaoth,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 47, 'Keros, Siaha, Padon,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 48, 'Lebanah, Hagabah, Shalmai,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 49, 'Hanan, Giddel, Gahar,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 50, 'Reaiah, Rezin, Nekoda,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 51, 'Gazzam, Uzza, Paseah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 52, 'Besai, Meunim, Nephusim,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 53, 'Bakbuk, Hakupha, Harhur,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 54, 'Bazluth, Mehida, Harsha,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 55, 'Barkos, Sisera, Temah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 56, 'Neziah, and Hatipha.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 57, '"The descendants of these servants of King Solomon returned from exile: Sotai, Sophereth, Peruda,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 58, 'Jaalah, Darkon, Giddel,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 59, 'Shephatiah, Hattil, Pokereth-hazzebaim, and Ami.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 60, '"In all, the Temple servants and the descendants of Solomon''s servants numbered 392.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 61, '"Another group returned to Jerusalem at this time from the towns of Tel-melah, Tel-harsha, Kerub, Addan, and Immer. However, they could not prove that they or their families were descendants of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 62, 'This group included the families of Delaiah, Tobiah, and Nekoda--a total of 642 people.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 63, '"Three families of priests--Hobaiah, Hakkoz, and Barzillai--also returned to Jerusalem. (This Barzillai had married a woman who was a descendant of Barzillai of Gilead, and he had taken her family name.)', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 64, 'But they had lost their genealogical records, so they were not allowed to serve as priests.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 65, 'The governor would not even let them eat the priests'' share of food from the sacrifices until there was a priest who could consult the LORD about the matter by means of sacred lots.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 66, '"So a total of 42,360 people returned to Judah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 67, 'in addition to 7,337 servants and 245 singers, both men and women.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 68, 'They took with them 736 horses, 245 mules,', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 69, '435 camels, and 6,720 donkeys.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 70, '"Some of the family leaders gave gifts for the work. The governor gave to the treasury 1,000 gold coins, 50 gold basins, and 530 robes for the priests.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 71, 'The other leaders gave to the treasury a total of 20,000 gold coins and some 2,750 pounds of silver for the work.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 72, 'The rest of the people gave 20,000 gold coins, about 2,500 pounds of silver, and 67 robes for the priests.', 'NLT'),
(20, 7, 73, '"So the priests, the Levites, the gatekeepers, the singers, the Temple servants, along with some of the people--that is to say, all Israel--settled in their own towns." Now in midautumn, when the Israelites had settled in their towns,', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 1, 'all the people assembled together as one person at the square just inside the Water Gate. They asked Ezra the scribe to bring out the Book of the Law of Moses, which the LORD had given for Israel to obey. 1', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 2, 'So on October 8 Ezra the priest brought the scroll of the law before the assembly, which included the men and women and all the children old enough to understand.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 3, 'He faced the square just inside the Water Gate from early morning until noon and read aloud to everyone who could understand. All the people paid close attention to the Book of the Law.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 4, 'Ezra the scribe stood on a high wooden platform that had been made for the occasion. To his right stood Mattithiah, Shema, Anaiah, Uriah, Hilkiah, and Maaseiah. To his left stood Pedaiah, Mishael, Malkijah, Hashum, Hashbaddanah, Zechariah, and Meshullam.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 5, 'Ezra stood on the platform in full view of all the people. When they saw him open the book, they all rose to their feet.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 6, 'Then Ezra praised the LORD, the great God, and all the people chanted, "Amen! Amen!" as they lifted their hands toward heaven. Then they bowed down and worshiped the LORD with their faces to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 7, 'Now the Levites--Jeshua, Bani, Sherebiah, Jamin, Akkub, Shabbethai, Hodiah, Maaseiah, Kelita, Azariah, Jozabad, Hanan, and Pelaiah--instructed the people who were standing there.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 8, 'They read from the Book of the Law of God and clearly explained the meaning of what was being read, helping the people understand each passage.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 9, 'Then Nehemiah the governor, Ezra the priest and scribe, and the Levites who were interpreting for the people said to them, "Don''t weep on such a day as this! For today is a sacred day before the LORD your God." All the people had been weeping as they listened to the words of the law.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 10, 'And Nehemiah continued, "Go and celebrate with a feast of choice foods and sweet drinks, and share gifts of food with people who have nothing prepared. This is a sacred day before our Lord. Don''t be dejected and sad, for the joy of the LORD is your strength!"', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 11, 'And the Levites, too, quieted the people, telling them, "Hush! Don''t weep! For this is a sacred day."', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 12, 'So the people went away to eat and drink at a festive meal, to share gifts of food, and to celebrate with great joy because they had heard God''s words and understood them.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 13, 'On October 9 the family leaders and the priests and Levites met with Ezra to go over the law in greater detail.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 14, 'As they studied the law, they discovered that the LORD had commanded through Moses that the Israelites should live in shelters during the festival to be held that month.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 15, 'He had said that a proclamation should be made throughout their towns and especially in Jerusalem, telling the people to go to the hills to get branches from olive, wild olive, myrtle, palm, and fig trees. They were to use these branches to make shelters in which they would live during the festival, as it was prescribed in the law.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 16, 'So the people went out and cut branches and used them to build shelters on the roofs of their houses, in their courtyards, in the courtyards of God''s Temple, or in the squares just inside the Water Gate and the Ephraim Gate.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 17, 'So everyone who had returned from captivity lived in these shelters for the seven days of the festival, and everyone was filled with great joy! The Israelites had not celebrated this way since the days of Joshua son of Nun.', 'NLT'),
(20, 8, 18, 'Ezra read from the Book of the Law of God on each of the seven days of the festival. Then on October 15 they held a solemn assembly, as the law of Moses required.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 1, 'On October 31 the people returned for another observance. This time they fasted and dressed in sackcloth and sprinkled dust on their heads.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 2, 'Those of Israelite descent separated themselves from all foreigners as they confessed their own sins and the sins of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 3, 'The Book of the Law of the LORD their God was read aloud to them for about three hours. Then for three more hours they took turns confessing their sins and worshiping the LORD their God.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 4, 'Some of the Levites were standing on the stairs, crying out to the LORD their God. Their names were Jeshua, Bani, Kadmiel, Shebaniah, Bunni, Sherebiah, Bani, and Kenani.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 5, 'Then the leaders of the Levites--Jeshua, Kadmiel, Bani, Hashabneiah, Sherebiah, Hodiah, Shebaniah, and Pethahiah--called out to the people: "Stand up and praise the LORD your God, for he lives from everlasting to everlasting!" Then they continued, "Praise his glorious name! It is far greater than we can think or say.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 6, 'You alone are the LORD. You made the skies and the heavens and all the stars. You made the earth and the seas and everything in them. You preserve and give life to everything, and all the angels of heaven worship you.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 7, '"You are the LORD God, who chose Abram and brought him from Ur of the Chaldeans and renamed him Abraham.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 8, 'When he had proved himself faithful, you made a covenant with him to give him and his descendants the land of the Canaanites, Hittites, Amorites, Perizzites, Jebusites, and Girgashites. And you have done what you promised, for you are always true to your word.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 9, '"You saw the sufferings and sorrows of our ancestors in Egypt, and you heard their cries from beside the Red Sea.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 10, 'You displayed miraculous signs and wonders against Pharaoh, his servants, and all his people, for you knew how arrogantly the Egyptians were treating them. You have a glorious reputation that has never been forgotten.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 11, 'You divided the sea for your people so they could walk through on dry land! And then you hurled their enemies into the depths of the sea. They sank like stones beneath the mighty waters.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 12, 'You led our ancestors by a pillar of cloud during the day and a pillar of fire at night so that they could find their way.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 13, '"You came down on Mount Sinai and spoke to them from heaven. You gave them regulations and instructions that were just, and laws and commands that were true.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 14, 'You instructed them concerning the laws of your holy Sabbath. And you commanded them, through Moses your servant, to obey all your commands, laws, and instructions.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 15, '"You gave them bread from heaven when they were hungry and water from the rock when they were thirsty. You commanded them to go and take possession of the land you had sworn to give them.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 16, 'But our ancestors were a proud and stubborn lot, and they refused to obey your commands.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 17, '"They refused to listen and did not remember the miracles you had done for them. Instead, they rebelled and appointed a leader to take them back to their slavery in Egypt! But you are a God of forgiveness, gracious and merciful, slow to become angry, and full of unfailing love and mercy. You did not abandon them,', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 18, 'even though they made an idol shaped like a calf and said, ''This is your god who brought you out of Egypt!'' They sinned and committed terrible blasphemies.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 19, 'But in your great mercy you did not abandon them to die in the wilderness. The pillar of cloud still led them forward by day, and the pillar of fire showed them the way through the night.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 20, 'You sent your good Spirit to instruct them, and you did not stop giving them bread from heaven or water for their thirst.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 21, 'For forty years you sustained them in the wilderness. They lacked nothing in all that time. Their clothes did not wear out, and their feet did not swell!', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 22, '"Then you helped our ancestors conquer great kingdoms and many nations, and you placed your people in every corner of the land. They completely took over the land of King Sihon of Heshbon and the land of King Og of Bashan.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 23, 'You made their descendants as numerous as the stars in the sky and brought them into the land you had promised to their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 24, 'They went in and took possession of the land. You subdued whole nations before them. Even the kings and the Canaanites, who inhabited the land, were powerless! Your people could deal with them as they pleased.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 25, 'Our ancestors captured fortified cities and fertile land. They took over houses full of good things, with cisterns already dug and vineyards and olive groves and orchards in abundance. So they ate until they were full and grew fat and enjoyed themselves in all your blessings.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 26, '"But despite all this, they were disobedient and rebelled against you. They threw away your law, they killed the prophets who encouraged them to return to you, and they committed terrible blasphemies.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 27, 'So you handed them over to their enemies. But in their time of trouble they cried to you, and you heard them from heaven. In great mercy, you sent them deliverers who rescued them from their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 28, '"But when all was going well, your people turned to sin again, and once more you let their enemies conquer them. Yet whenever your people cried to you again for help, you listened once more from heaven. In your wonderful mercy, you rescued them repeatedly!', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 29, 'You warned them to return to your law, but they became proud and obstinate and disobeyed your commands. They did not follow your regulations, by which people will find life if only they obey. They stubbornly turned their backs on you and refused to listen.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 30, 'In your love, you were patient with them for many years. You sent your Spirit, who, through the prophets, warned them about their sins. But still they wouldn''t listen! So once again you allowed the pagan inhabitants of the land to conquer them.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 31, 'But in your great mercy, you did not destroy them completely or abandon them forever. What a gracious and merciful God you are!', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 32, '"And now, our God, the great and mighty and awesome God, who keeps his covenant of unfailing love, do not let all the hardships we have suffered be as nothing to you. Great trouble has come upon us and upon our kings and princes and priests and prophets and ancestors from the days when the kings of Assyria first triumphed over us until now.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 33, 'Every time you punished us you were being just. We have sinned greatly, and you gave us only what we deserved.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 34, 'Our kings, princes, priests, and ancestors did not obey your law or listen to your commands and solemn warnings.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 35, 'Even while they had their own kingdom, they did not serve you even though you showered your goodness on them. You gave them a large, fertile land, but they refused to turn from their wickedness.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 36, '"So now today we are slaves here in the land of plenty that you gave to our ancestors! We are slaves among all this abundance!', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 37, 'The lush produce of this land piles up in the hands of the kings whom you have set over us because of our sins. They have power over us and our cattle. We serve them at their pleasure, and we are in great misery.', 'NLT'),
(20, 9, 38, '"Yet in spite of all this, we are making a solemn promise and putting it in writing. On this sealed document are the names of our princes and Levites and priests."', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 1, 'The document was ratified and sealed with the following names: Nehemiah the governor, the son of Hacaliah. The priests who signed were Zedekiah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 2, 'Seraiah, Azariah, Jeremiah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 3, 'Pashhur, Amariah, Malkijah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 4, 'Hattush, Shebaniah, Malluch,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 5, 'Harim, Meremoth, Obadiah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 6, 'Daniel, Ginnethon, Baruch,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 7, 'Meshullam, Abijah, Mijamin,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 8, 'Maaziah, Bilgai, and Shemaiah. These were the priests.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 9, 'The Levites who signed were Jeshua son of Azaniah, Binnui from the family of Henadad, Kadmiel,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 10, 'and their fellow Levites: Shebaniah, Hodiah, Kelita, Pelaiah, Hanan,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 11, 'Mica, Rehob, Hashabiah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 12, 'Zaccur, Sherebiah, Shebaniah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 13, 'Hodiah, Bani, and Beninu.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 14, 'The leaders who signed were Parosh, Pahath-moab, Elam, Zattu, Bani,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 15, 'Bunni, Azgad, Bebai,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 16, 'Adonijah, Bigvai, Adin,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 17, 'Ater, Hezekiah, Azzur,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 18, 'Hodiah, Hashum, Bezai,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 19, 'Hariph, Anathoth, Nebai,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 20, 'Magpiash, Meshullam, Hezir,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 21, 'Meshezabel, Zadok, Jaddua,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 22, 'Pelatiah, Hanan, Anaiah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 23, 'Hoshea, Hananiah, Hasshub,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 24, 'Hallohesh, Pilha, Shobek,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 25, 'Rehum, Hashabnah, Maaseiah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 26, 'Ahiah, Hanan, Anan,', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 27, 'Malluch, Harim, and Baanah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 28, 'The rest of the people--the priests, Levites, gatekeepers, singers, Temple servants, and all who had separated themselves from the pagan people of the land in order to serve God, and who were old enough to understand--', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 29, 'now all heartily bound themselves with an oath. They vowed to accept the curse of God if they failed to obey the law of God as issued by his servant Moses. They solemnly promised to carefully follow all the commands, laws, and regulations of the LORD their Lord.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 30, '"We promise not to let our daughters marry the pagan people of the land, nor to let our sons marry their daughters.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 31, 'We further promise that if the people of the land should bring any merchandise or grain to be sold on the Sabbath or on any other holy day, we will refuse to buy it. And we promise not to do any work every seventh year and to cancel the debts owed to us by other Jews.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 32, '"In addition, we promise to obey the command to pay the annual Temple tax of an eighth of an ounce of silver, so that there will be enough money to care for the Temple of our God.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 33, 'This will provide for the Bread of the Presence; for the regular grain offerings and burnt offerings; for the offerings on the Sabbaths, the new moon celebrations, and the annual festivals; for the holy offerings; and for the sin offerings to make atonement for Israel. It will also provide for the other items necessary for the work of the Temple of our God.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 34, '"We have cast sacred lots to determine when--at regular times each year--the families of the priests, Levites, and the common people should bring wood to God''s Temple to be burned on the altar of the LORD our God, as required in the law.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 35, '"We promise always to bring the first part of every harvest to the LORD''s Temple--whether it be a crop from the soil or from our fruit trees.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 36, 'We agree to give to God our oldest sons and the firstborn of all our herds and flocks, just as the law requires. We will present them to the priests who minister in the Temple of our God.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 37, 'We will store the produce in the storerooms of the Temple of our God. We will bring the best of our flour and other grain offerings, the best of our fruit, and the best of our new wine and olive oil. And we promise to bring to the Levites a tenth of everything our land produces, for it is the Levites who collect the tithes in all our rural towns.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 38, 'A priest--a descendant of Aaron--will be with the Levites as they receive these tithes. And a tenth of all that is collected as tithes will be delivered by the Levites to the Temple of our God and placed in the storerooms.', 'NLT'),
(20, 10, 39, 'The people and the Levites must bring these offerings of grain, new wine, and olive oil to the Temple and place them in the sacred containers near the ministering priests, the gatekeepers, and the singers. "So we promise together not to neglect the Temple of our God."', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 1, 'Now the leaders of the people were living in Jerusalem, the holy city, at this time. A tenth of the people from the other towns of Judah and Benjamin were chosen by sacred lots to live there, too, while the rest stayed where they were.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 2, 'And the people commended everyone who volunteered to resettle in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 3, 'Here is a list of the names of the provincial officials who came to Jerusalem. Most of the people, priests, Levites, Temple servants, and descendants of Solomon''s servants continued to live in their own homes in the various towns of Judah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 4, 'but some of the people from Judah and Benjamin resettled in Jerusalem. From the tribe of Judah: Athaiah son of Uzziah, son of Zechariah, son of Amariah, son of Shephatiah, son of Mahalalel, of the family of Perez;', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 5, 'and Maaseiah son of Baruch, son of Col-hozeh, son of Hazaiah, son of Adaiah, son of Joiarib, son of Zechariah, of the family of Shelah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 6, 'There were also 468 descendants of Perez who lived in Jerusalem--all outstanding men.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 7, 'From the tribe of Benjamin: Sallu son of Meshullam, son of Joed, son of Pedaiah, son of Kolaiah, son of Maaseiah, son of Ithiel, son of Jeshaiah;', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 8, 'and after him there were Gabbai and Sallai, and a total of 928 relatives.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 9, 'Their chief officer was Joel son of Zicri, who was assisted by Judah son of Hassenuah, second-in-command over the city.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 10, 'From the priests: Jedaiah son of Joiarib; Jakin;', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 11, 'and Seraiah son of Hilkiah, son of Meshullam, son of Zadok, son of Meraioth, son of Ahitub, the supervisor of the Temple of God;', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 12, 'together with 822 of their associates, who worked at the Temple. Also, there was Adaiah son of Jeroham, son of Pelaliah, son of Amzi, son of Zechariah, son of Pashhur, son of Malkijah;', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 13, 'and 242 of his associates, who were heads of their families. There were also Amashsai son of Azarel, son of Ahzai, son of Meshillemoth, son of Immer;', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 14, 'and 128 of his outstanding associates. Their chief officer was Zabdiel son of Haggedolim.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 15, 'From the Levites: Shemaiah son of Hasshub, son of Azrikam, son of Hashabiah, son of Bunni;', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 16, 'Shabbethai and Jozabad, who were in charge of the work outside the Temple of God;', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 17, 'Mattaniah son of Mica, son of Zabdi, a descendant of Asaph, who opened the thanksgiving services with prayer; Bakbukiah, who was Mattaniah''s assistant; and Abda son of Shammua, son of Galal, son of Jeduthun.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 18, 'In all, there were 284 Levites in the holy city.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 19, 'From the gatekeepers: Akkub, Talmon, and 172 of their associates, who guarded the gates.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 20, 'The other priests, Levites, and the rest of the Israelites lived wherever their family inheritance was located in any of the towns of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 21, 'However, the Temple servants, whose leaders were Ziha and Gishpa, all lived on the hill of Ophel.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 22, 'The chief officer of the Levites in Jerusalem was Uzzi son of Bani, son of Hashabiah, son of Mattaniah, son of Mica, a descendant of Asaph, whose family served as singers at God''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 23, 'They were under royal orders, which determined their daily activities.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 24, 'Pethahiah son of Meshezabel, a descendant of Zerah son of Judah, was the king''s agent in all matters of public administration.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 25, 'Some of the people of Judah lived in Kiriath-arba with its villages, Dibon with its villages, and Jekabzeel with its villages.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 26, 'They also lived in Jeshua, Moladah, Beth-pelet,', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 27, 'Hazar-shual, Beersheba with its villages,', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 28, 'Ziklag, and Meconah with its villages.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 29, 'They were also in En-rimmon, Zorah, Jarmuth,', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 30, 'Zanoah, and Adullam with their villages. They were also in Lachish and its nearby fields and Azekah with its surrounding villages. So the people of Judah were living all the way from Beersheba to the valley of Hinnom.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 31, 'Some of the people of Benjamin lived at Geba, Micmash, Aija, and Bethel with its surrounding villages.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 32, 'They were also in Anathoth, Nob, Ananiah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 33, 'Hazor, Ramah, Gittaim,', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 34, 'Hadid, Zeboim, Neballat,', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 35, 'Lod, Ono, and the Valley of Craftsmen.', 'NLT'),
(20, 11, 36, 'Some of the Levites who lived in Judah were sent to live with the tribe of Benjamin.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 1, 'Here is the list of the priests and Levites who had returned with Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel and Jeshua the high priest: Seraiah, Jeremiah, Ezra,', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 2, 'Amariah, Malluch, Hattush,', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 3, 'Shecaniah, Harim, Meremoth,', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 4, 'Iddo, Ginnethon, Abijah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 5, 'Miniamin, Moadiah, Bilgah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 6, 'Shemaiah, Joiarib, Jedaiah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 7, 'Sallu, Amok, Hilkiah, and Jedaiah. These were the leaders of the priests and their associates in the days of Jeshua.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 8, 'The Levites who had returned with them were Jeshua, Binnui, Kadmiel, Sherebiah, Judah, and Mattaniah, who with his associates was in charge of the songs of thanksgiving.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 9, 'Their associates, Bakbukiah and Unni, stood opposite them during the service.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 10, 'Jeshua the high priest was the father of Joiakim. Joiakim was the father of Eliashib. Eliashib was the father of Joiada.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 11, 'Joiada was the father of Johanan. Johanan was the father of Jaddua.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 12, 'Now when Joiakim was high priest, the family leaders of the priests were as follows: Meraiah was leader of the family of Seraiah. Hananiah was leader of the family of Jeremiah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 13, 'Meshullam was leader of the family of Ezra. Jehohanan was leader of the family of Amariah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 14, 'Jonathan was leader of the family of Malluch. Joseph was leader of the family of Shecaniah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 15, 'Adna was leader of the family of Harim. Helkai was leader of the family of Meremoth.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 16, 'Zechariah was leader of the family of Iddo. Meshullam was leader of the family of Ginnethon.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 17, 'Zicri was leader of the family of Abijah. There was also a leader of the family of Miniamin. Piltai was leader of the family of Moadiah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 18, 'Shammua was leader of the family of Bilgah. Jehonathan was leader of the family of Shemaiah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 19, 'Mattenai was leader of the family of Joiarib. Uzzi was leader of the family of Jedaiah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 20, 'Kallai was leader of the family of Sallu. Eber was leader of the family of Amok.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 21, 'Hashabiah was leader of the family of Hilkiah. Nethanel was leader of the family of Jedaiah.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 22, 'During the reign of Darius II of Persia, a list was compiled of the family leaders of the Levites and the priests in the days of the following high priests: Eliashib, Joiada, Johanan, and Jaddua.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 23, 'The heads of the Levite families were recorded in The Book of History down to the days of Johanan, the grandson of Eliashib.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 24, 'These were the family leaders of the Levites: Hashabiah, Sherebiah, Jeshua, Binnui, Kadmiel, and other associates, who stood opposite them during the ceremonies of praise and thanksgiving, one section responding to the other, just as commanded by David, the man of God.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 25, 'This included Mattaniah, Bakbukiah, and Obadiah. Meshullam, Talmon, and Akkub were the gatekeepers in charge of the storerooms at the gates.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 26, 'These all served in the days of Joiakim son of Jeshua, son of Jehozadak, and in the days of Nehemiah the governor and of Ezra the priest and scribe.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 27, 'During the dedication of the new wall of Jerusalem, the Levites throughout the land were asked to come to Jerusalem to assist in the ceremonies. They were to take part in the joyous occasion with their songs of thanksgiving and with the music of cymbals, lyres, and harps.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 28, 'The singers were brought together from Jerusalem and its surrounding villages and from the villages of the Netophathites.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 29, 'They also came from Beth-gilgal and the area of Geba and Azmaveth, for the singers had built their own villages around Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 30, 'The priests and Levites first dedicated themselves, then the people, the gates, and the wall.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 31, 'I led the leaders of Judah to the top of the wall and organized two large choirs to give thanks. One of the choirs proceeded southward along the top of the wall to the Dung Gate.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 32, 'Hoshaiah and half the leaders of Judah followed them,', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 33, 'along with Azariah, Ezra, Meshullam,', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 34, 'Judah, Benjamin, Shemaiah, Jeremiah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 35, 'and some priests who played trumpets. Then came Zechariah son of Jonathan, son of Shemaiah, son of Mattaniah, son of Micaiah, son of Zaccur, a descendant of Asaph.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 36, 'And finally came Zechariah''s colleagues Shemaiah, Azarel, Milalai, Gilalai, Maai, Nethanel, Judah, and Hanani. They used the musical instruments prescribed by David, the man of God. Ezra the scribe led this procession.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 37, 'At the Fountain Gate they went straight up the steps on the ascent of the city wall toward the City of David. They passed the house of David and then proceeded to the Water Gate on the east.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 38, 'The second choir went northward around the other way to meet them. I followed them, with the other half of the people, along the top of the wall past the Tower of the Ovens to the Broad Wall,', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 39, 'then past the Ephraim Gate to the Old City Gate, past the Fish Gate and the Tower of Hananel, and went on to the Tower of the Hundred. Then we continued on to the Sheep Gate and stopped at the Guard Gate.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 40, 'The two choirs that were giving thanks then proceeded to the Temple of God, where they took their places. So did I, together with the group of leaders who were with me.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 41, 'We went together with the trumpet-playing priests--Eliakim, Maaseiah, Miniamin, Micaiah, Elioenai, Zechariah, and Hananiah--', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 42, 'and the singers--Maaseiah, Shemaiah, Eleazar, Uzzi, Jehohanan, Malkijah, Elam, and Ezer. They played and sang loudly and clearly under the direction of Jezrahiah the choir director.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 43, 'Many sacrifices were offered on that joyous day, for God had given the people cause for great joy. The women and children also participated in the celebration, and the joy of the people of Jerusalem could be heard far away.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 44, 'On that day men were appointed to be in charge of the storerooms for the gifts, the first part of the harvest, and the tithes. They were responsible to collect these from the fields as required by the law for the priests and Levites, for all the people of Judah valued the priests and Levites and their work.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 45, 'They performed the service of their God and the service of purification, as required by the laws of David and his son Solomon, and so did the singers and the gatekeepers.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 46, 'The custom of having choir directors to lead the choirs in hymns of praise and thanks to God began long ago in the days of David and Asaph.', 'NLT'),
(20, 12, 47, 'So now, in the days of Zerubbabel and of Nehemiah, the people brought a daily supply of food for the singers, the gatekeepers, and the Levites. The Levites, in turn, gave a portion of what they received to the priests, the descendants of Aaron.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 1, 'On that same day, as the Book of Moses was being read, the people found a statement which said that no Ammonite or Moabite should ever be permitted to enter the assembly of God.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 2, 'For they had not been friendly to the Israelites when they left Egypt. Instead, they hired Balaam to curse them, though our God turned the curse into a blessing.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 3, 'When this law was read, all those of mixed ancestry were immediately expelled from the assembly.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 4, 'Before this had happened, Eliashib the priest, who had been appointed as supervisor of the storerooms of the Temple of our God and who was also a relative of Tobiah,', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 5, 'had converted a large storage room and placed it at Tobiah''s disposal. The room had previously been used for storing the grain offerings, frankincense, Temple utensils, and tithes of grain, new wine, olive oil, and the special portion set aside for the priests. Moses had decreed that these offerings belonged to the Levites, the singers, and the gatekeepers.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 6, 'I was not in Jerusalem at that time, for I had returned to the king in the thirty-second year of the reign of King Artaxerxes of Babylon, though I later received his permission to return.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 7, 'When I arrived back in Jerusalem and learned the extent of this evil deed of Eliashib--that he had provided Tobiah with a room in the courtyards of the Temple of God--', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 8, 'I became very upset and threw all of Tobiah''s belongings from the room.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 9, 'Then I demanded that the rooms be purified, and I brought back the utensils for God''s Temple, the grain offerings, and the frankincense.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 10, 'I also discovered that the Levites had not been given what was due them, so they and the singers who were to conduct the worship services had all returned to work their fields.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 11, 'I immediately confronted the leaders and demanded, "Why has the Temple of God been neglected?" Then I called all the Levites back again and restored them to their proper duties.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 12, 'And once more all the people of Judah began bringing their tithes of grain, new wine, and olive oil to the Temple storerooms.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 13, 'I put Shelemiah the priest, Zadok the scribe, and Pedaiah, one of the Levites, in charge of the storerooms. And I appointed Hanan son of Zaccur and grandson of Mattaniah as their assistant. These men had an excellent reputation, and it was their job to make honest distributions to their fellow Levites.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 14, 'Remember this good deed, O my God, and do not forget all that I have faithfully done for the Temple of my God.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 15, 'One Sabbath day I saw some men of Judah treading their winepresses. They were also bringing in bundles of grain and loading them on their donkeys. And on that day they were bringing their wine, grapes, figs, and all sorts of produce to Jerusalem to sell. So I rebuked them for selling their produce on the Sabbath.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 16, 'There were also some men from Tyre bringing in fish and all kinds of merchandise. They were selling it on the Sabbath to the people of Judah--and in Jerusalem at that!', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 17, 'So I confronted the leaders of Judah, "Why are you profaning the Sabbath in this evil way?', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 18, 'Wasn''t it enough that your ancestors did this sort of thing, so that our God brought the present troubles upon us and our city? Now you are bringing even more wrath upon the people of Israel by permitting the Sabbath to be desecrated in this way!"', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 19, 'So I commanded that from then on the gates of the city should be shut as darkness fell every Friday evening, not to be opened until the Sabbath ended. I also sent some of my own servants to guard the gates so that no merchandise could be brought in on the Sabbath day.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 20, 'The merchants and tradesmen with a variety of wares camped outside Jerusalem once or twice.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 21, 'But I spoke sharply to them and said, "What are you doing out here, camping around the wall? If you do this again, I will arrest you!" And that was the last time they came on the Sabbath.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 22, 'Then I commanded the Levites to purify themselves and to guard the gates in order to preserve the holiness of the Sabbath. Remember this good deed also, O my God! Have compassion on me according to your great and unfailing love.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 23, 'About the same time I realized that some of the men of Judah had married women from Ashdod, Ammon, and Moab.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 24, 'Even worse, half their children spoke in the language of Ashdod or some other people and could not speak the language of Judah at all.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 25, 'So I confronted them and called down curses on them. I beat some of them and pulled out their hair. I made them swear before God that they would not let their children intermarry with the pagan people of the land.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 26, '"Wasn''t this exactly what led King Solomon of Israel into sin?" I demanded. "There was no king from any nation who could compare to him, and God loved him and made him king over all Israel. But even he was led into sin by his foreign wives.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 27, 'How could you even think of committing this sinful deed and acting unfaithfully toward God by marrying foreign women?"', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 28, 'One of the sons of Joiada son of Eliashib the high priest had married a daughter of Sanballat the Horonite, so I banished him from my presence.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 29, 'Remember them, O my God, for they have defiled the priesthood and the promises and vows of the priests and Levites.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 30, 'So I purged out everything foreign and assigned tasks to the priests and Levites, making certain that each knew his work.', 'NLT'),
(20, 13, 31, 'I also made sure that the supply of wood for the altar was brought at the proper times and that the first part of the harvest was collected for the priests. Remember this in my favor, O my God.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 1, 'This happened in the days of King Xerxes, who reigned over 127 provinces stretching from India to Ethiopia.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 2, 'At that time he ruled his empire from his throne at the fortress of Susa.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 3, 'In the third year of his reign, he gave a banquet for all his princes and officials. He invited all the military officers of Media and Persia, as well as the noblemen and provincial officials.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 4, 'The celebration lasted six months--a tremendous display of the opulent wealth and glory of his empire.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 5, 'When it was all over, the king gave a special banquet for all the palace servants and officials--from the greatest to the least. It lasted for seven days and was held at Susa in the courtyard of the palace garden.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 6, 'The courtyard was decorated with beautifully woven white and blue linen hangings, fastened by purple ribbons to silver rings embedded in marble pillars. Gold and silver couches stood on a mosaic pavement of porphyry, marble, mother-of-pearl, and other costly stones.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 7, 'Drinks were served in gold goblets of many designs, and there was an abundance of royal wine, just as the king had commanded.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 8, 'The only restriction on the drinking was that no one should be compelled to take more than he wanted. But those who wished could have as much as they pleased, for the king had instructed his staff to let everyone decide this matter for himself.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 9, 'Queen Vashti gave a banquet for the women of the palace at the same time.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 10, 'On the seventh day of the feast, when King Xerxes was half drunk with wine, he told Mehuman, Biztha, Harbona, Bigtha, Abagtha, Zethar, and Carcas, the seven eunuchs who attended him,', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 11, 'to bring Queen Vashti to him with the royal crown on her head. He wanted all the men to gaze on her beauty, for she was a very beautiful woman.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 12, 'But when they conveyed the king''s order to Queen Vashti, she refused to come. This made the king furious, and he burned with anger.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 13, 'He immediately consulted with his advisers, who knew all the Persian laws and customs, for he always asked their advice.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 14, 'The names of these men were Carshena, Shethar, Admatha, Tarshish, Meres, Marsena, and Memucan--seven high officials of Persia and Media. They were his closest associates and held the highest positions in the empire.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 15, '"What must be done to Queen Vashti?" the king demanded. "What penalty does the law provide for a queen who refuses to obey the king''s orders, properly sent through his eunuchs?"', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 16, 'Memucan answered the king and his princes, "Queen Vashti has wronged not only the king but also every official and citizen throughout your empire.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 17, 'Women everywhere will begin to despise their husbands when they learn that Queen Vashti has refused to appear before the king.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 18, 'Before this day is out, the wife of every one of us, your officials throughout the empire, will hear what the queen did and will start talking to their husbands the same way. There will be no end to the contempt and anger throughout your realm.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 19, 'So if it please the king, we suggest that you issue a written decree, a law of the Persians and Medes that cannot be revoked. It should order that Queen Vashti be forever banished from your presence and that you choose another queen more worthy than she.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 20, 'When this decree is published throughout your vast empire, husbands everywhere, whatever their rank, will receive proper respect from their wives!"', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 21, 'The king and his princes thought this made good sense, so he followed Memucan''s counsel.', 'NLT'),
(21, 1, 22, 'He sent letters to all parts of the empire, to each province in its own script and language, proclaiming that every man should be the ruler of his home.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 1, 'But after Xerxes'' anger had cooled, he began thinking about Vashti and what she had done and the decree he had made.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 2, 'So his attendants suggested, "Let us search the empire to find beautiful young virgins for the king.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 3, 'Let the king appoint agents in each province to bring these beautiful young women into the royal harem at Susa. Hegai, the eunuch in charge, will see that they are all given beauty treatments.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 4, 'After that, the young woman who pleases you most will be made queen instead of Vashti." This advice was very appealing to the king, so he put the plan into effect immediately.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 5, 'Now at the fortress of Susa there was a certain Jew named Mordecai son of Jair. He was from the tribe of Benjamin and was a descendant of Kish and Shimei.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 6, 'His family had been exiled from Jerusalem to Babylon by King Nebuchadnezzar, along with King Jehoiachin of Judah and many others.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 7, 'This man had a beautiful and lovely young cousin, Hadassah, who was also called Esther. When her father and mother had died, Mordecai adopted her into his family and raised her as his own daughter.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 8, 'As a result of the king''s decree, Esther, along with many other young women, was brought to the king''s harem at the fortress of Susa and placed in Hegai''s care.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 9, 'Hegai was very impressed with Esther and treated her kindly. He quickly ordered a special menu for her and provided her with beauty treatments. He also assigned her seven maids specially chosen from the king''s palace, and he moved her and her maids into the best place in the harem.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 10, 'Esther had not told anyone of her nationality and family background, for Mordecai had told her not to.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 11, 'Every day Mordecai would take a walk near the courtyard of the harem to ask about Esther and to find out what was happening to her.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 12, 'Before each young woman was taken to the king''s bed, she was given the prescribed twelve months of beauty treatments--six months with oil of myrrh, followed by six months with special perfumes and ointments.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 13, 'When the time came for her to go in to the king, she was given her choice of whatever clothing or jewelry she wanted to enhance her beauty.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 14, 'That evening she was taken to the king''s private rooms, and the next morning she was brought to the second harem, where the king''s wives lived. There she would be under the care of Shaashgaz, another of the king''s eunuchs. She would live there for the rest of her life, never going to the king again unless he had especially enjoyed her and requested her by name.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 15, 'When it was Esther''s turn to go to the king, she accepted the advice of Hegai, the eunuch in charge of the harem. She asked for nothing except what he suggested, and she was admired by everyone who saw her.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 16, 'When Esther was taken to King Xerxes at the royal palace in early winter of the seventh year of his reign,', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 17, 'the king loved her more than any of the other young women. He was so delighted with her that he set the royal crown on her head and declared her queen instead of Vashti.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 18, 'To celebrate the occasion, he gave a banquet in Esther''s honor for all his princes and servants, giving generous gifts to everyone and declaring a public festival for the provinces.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 19, 'Even after all the young women had been transferred to the second harem and Mordecai had become a palace official,', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 20, 'Esther continued to keep her nationality and family background a secret. She was still following Mordecai''s orders, just as she did when she was living in his home.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 21, 'One day as Mordecai was on duty at the palace, two of the king''s eunuchs, Bigthana and Teresh--who were guards at the door of the king''s private quarters--became angry at King Xerxes and plotted to assassinate him.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 22, 'But Mordecai heard about the plot and passed the information on to Queen Esther. She then told the king about it and gave Mordecai credit for the report.', 'NLT'),
(21, 2, 23, 'When an investigation was made and Mordecai''s story was found to be true, the two men were hanged on a gallows. This was all duly recorded in The Book of the History of King Xerxes'' Reign.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 1, 'Some time later, King Xerxes promoted Haman son of Hammedatha the Agagite to prime minister, making him the most powerful official in the empire next to the king himself.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 2, 'All the king''s officials would bow down before Haman to show him respect whenever he passed by, for so the king had commanded. But Mordecai refused to bow down or show him respect.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 3, 'Then the palace officials at the king''s gate asked Mordecai, "Why are you disobeying the king''s command?"', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 4, 'They spoke to him day after day, but still he refused to comply with the order. So they spoke to Haman about this to see if he would tolerate Mordecai''s conduct, since Mordecai had told them he was a Jew.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 5, 'When Haman saw that Mordecai would not bow down or show him respect, he was filled with rage.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 6, 'So he decided it was not enough to lay hands on Mordecai alone. Since he had learned that Mordecai was a Jew, he decided to destroy all the Jews throughout the entire empire of Xerxes.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 7, 'So in the month of April, during the twelfth year of King Xerxes'' reign, lots were cast (the lots were called purim) to determine the best day and month to take action. And the day selected was March 7, nearly a year later.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 8, 'Then Haman approached King Xerxes and said, "There is a certain race of people scattered through all the provinces of your empire. Their laws are different from those of any other nation, and they refuse to obey even the laws of the king. So it is not in the king''s interest to let them live.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 9, 'If it please Your Majesty, issue a decree that they be destroyed, and I will give 375 tons of silver to the government administrators so they can put it into the royal treasury."', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 10, 'The king agreed, confirming his decision by removing his signet ring from his finger and giving it to Haman son of Hammedatha the Agagite--the enemy of the Jews.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 11, '"Keep the money," the king told Haman, "but go ahead and do as you like with these people."', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 12, 'On April 17 Haman called in the king''s secretaries and dictated letters to the princes, the governors of the respective provinces, and the local officials of each province in their own scripts and languages. These letters were signed in the name of King Xerxes, sealed with his ring,', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 13, 'and sent by messengers into all the provinces of the empire. The letters decreed that all Jews--young and old, including women and children--must be killed, slaughtered, and annihilated on a single day. This was scheduled to happen nearly a year later on March 7. The property of the Jews would be given to those who killed them.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 14, 'A copy of this decree was to be issued in every province and made known to all the people, so that they would be ready to do their duty on the appointed day.', 'NLT'),
(21, 3, 15, 'At the king''s command, the decree went out by the swiftest messengers, and it was proclaimed in the fortress of Susa. Then the king and Haman sat down to drink, but the city of Susa fell into confusion.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 1, 'When Mordecai learned what had been done, he tore his clothes, put on sackcloth and ashes, and went out into the city, crying with a loud and bitter wail.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 2, 'He stood outside the gate of the palace, for no one was allowed to enter while wearing clothes of mourning.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 3, 'And as news of the king''s decree reached all the provinces, there was great mourning among the Jews. They fasted, wept, and wailed, and many people lay in sackcloth and ashes.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 4, 'When Queen Esther''s maids and eunuchs came and told her about Mordecai, she was deeply distressed. She sent clothing to him to replace the sackcloth, but he refused it.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 5, 'Then Esther sent for Hathach, one of the king''s eunuchs who had been appointed as her attendant. She ordered him to go to Mordecai and find out what was troubling him and why he was in mourning.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 6, 'So Hathach went out to Mordecai in the square in front of the palace gate.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 7, 'Mordecai told him the whole story and told him how much money Haman had promised to pay into the royal treasury for the destruction of the Jews.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 8, 'Mordecai gave Hathach a copy of the decree issued in Susa that called for the death of all Jews, and he asked Hathach to show it to Esther. He also asked Hathach to explain it to her and to urge her to go to the king to beg for mercy and plead for her people.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 9, 'So Hathach returned to Esther with Mordecai''s message.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 10, 'Then Esther told Hathach to go back and relay this message to Mordecai:', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 11, '"The whole world knows that anyone who appears before the king in his inner court without being invited is doomed to die unless the king holds out his gold scepter. And the king has not called for me to come to him in more than a month."', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 12, 'So Hathach gave Esther''s message to Mordecai.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 13, 'Mordecai sent back this reply to Esther: "Don''t think for a moment that you will escape there in the palace when all other Jews are killed.', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 14, 'If you keep quiet at a time like this, deliverance for the Jews will arise from some other place, but you and your relatives will die. What''s more, who can say but that you have been elevated to the palace for just such a time as this?"', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 15, 'Then Esther sent this reply to Mordecai:', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 16, '"Go and gather together all the Jews of Susa and fast for me. Do not eat or drink for three days, night or day. My maids and I will do the same. And then, though it is against the law, I will go in to see the king. If I must die, I am willing to die."', 'NLT'),
(21, 4, 17, 'So Mordecai went away and did as Esther told him.', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 1, 'Three days later, Esther put on her royal robes and entered the inner court of the palace, just across from the king''s hall. The king was sitting on his royal throne, facing the entrance.', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 2, 'When he saw Queen Esther standing there in the inner court, he welcomed her, holding out the gold scepter to her. So Esther approached and touched its tip.', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 3, 'Then the king asked her, "What do you want, Queen Esther? What is your request? I will give it to you, even if it is half the kingdom!"', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 4, 'And Esther replied, "If it please Your Majesty, let the king and Haman come today to a banquet I have prepared for the king."', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 5, 'The king turned to his attendants and said, "Tell Haman to come quickly to a banquet, as Esther has requested." So the king and Haman went to Esther''s banquet.', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 6, 'And while they were drinking wine, the king said to Esther, "Now tell me what you really want. What is your request? I will give it to you, even if it is half the kingdom!"', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 7, 'Esther replied, "This is my request and deepest wish.', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 8, 'If Your Majesty is pleased with me and wants to grant my request, please come with Haman tomorrow to the banquet I will prepare for you. Then tomorrow I will explain what this is all about."', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 9, 'What a happy man Haman was as he left the banquet! But when he saw Mordecai sitting at the gate, not standing up or trembling nervously before him, he was furious.', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 10, 'However, he restrained himself and went on home. Then he gathered together his friends and Zeresh, his wife,', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 11, 'and boasted to them about his great wealth and his many children. He bragged about the honors the king had given him and how he had been promoted over all the other officials and leaders.', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 12, 'Then Haman added, "And that''s not all! Queen Esther invited only me and the king himself to the banquet she prepared for us. And she has invited me to dine with her and the king again tomorrow!"', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 13, 'Then he added, "But all this is meaningless as long as I see Mordecai the Jew just sitting there at the palace gate."', 'NLT'),
(21, 5, 14, 'So Haman''s wife, Zeresh, and all his friends suggested, "Set up a gallows that stands seventy-five feet tall, and in the morning ask the king to hang Mordecai on it. When this is done, you can go on your merry way to the banquet with the king." This pleased Haman immensely, and he ordered the gallows set up.', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 1, 'That night the king had trouble sleeping, so he ordered an attendant to bring the historical records of his kingdom so they could be read to him.', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 2, 'In those records he discovered an account of how Mordecai had exposed the plot of Bigthana and Teresh, two of the eunuchs who guarded the door to the king''s private quarters. They had plotted to assassinate the king.', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 3, '"What reward or recognition did we ever give Mordecai for this?" the king asked. His attendants replied, "Nothing has been done."', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 4, '"Who is that in the outer court?" the king inquired. Now, as it happened, Haman had just arrived in the outer court of the palace to ask the king to hang Mordecai from the gallows he had prepared.', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 5, 'So the attendants replied to the king, "Haman is out there.Bring him in," the king ordered.', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 6, 'So Haman came in, and the king said, "What should I do to honor a man who truly pleases me?" Haman thought to himself, "Whom would the king wish to honor more than me?"', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 7, 'So he replied, "If the king wishes to honor someone,', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 8, 'he should bring out one of the king''s own royal robes, as well as the king''s own horse with a royal emblem on its head.', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 9, 'Instruct one of the king''s most noble princes to dress the man in the king''s robe and to lead him through the city square on the king''s own horse. Have the prince shout as they go, `This is what happens to those the king wishes to honor!''"', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 10, '"Excellent!" the king said to Haman. "Hurry and get the robe and my horse, and do just as you have said for Mordecai the Jew, who sits at the gate of the palace. Do not fail to carry out everything you have suggested."', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 11, 'So Haman took the robe and put it on Mordecai, placed him on the king''s own horse, and led him through the city square, shouting, "This is what happens to those the king wishes to honor!"', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 12, 'Afterward Mordecai returned to the palace gate, but Haman hurried home dejected and completely humiliated.', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 13, 'When Haman told his wife, Zeresh, and all his friends what had happened, they said, "Since Mordecai--this man who has humiliated you--is a Jew, you will never succeed in your plans against him. It will be fatal to continue to oppose him."', 'NLT'),
(21, 6, 14, 'While they were still talking, the king''s eunuchs arrived to take Haman to the banquet Esther had prepared.', 'NLT'),
(21, 7, 1, 'So the king and Haman went to Queen Esther''s banquet.', 'NLT'),
(21, 7, 2, 'And while they were drinking wine that day, the king again asked her, "Tell me what you want, Queen Esther. What is your request? I will give it to you, even if it is half the kingdom!"', 'NLT'),
(21, 7, 3, 'And so Queen Esther replied, "If Your Majesty is pleased with me and wants to grant my request, my petition is that my life and the lives of my people will be spared.', 'NLT'),
(21, 7, 4, 'For my people and I have been sold to those who would kill, slaughter, and annihilate us. If we had only been sold as slaves, I could remain quiet, for that would have been a matter too trivial to warrant disturbing the king."', 'NLT'),
(21, 7, 5, '"Who would do such a thing?" King Xerxes demanded. "Who would dare touch you?"', 'NLT'),
(21, 7, 6, 'Esther replied, "This wicked Haman is our enemy." Haman grew pale with fright before the king and queen.', 'NLT'),
(21, 7, 7, 'Then the king jumped to his feet in a rage and went out into the palace garden. But Haman stayed behind to plead for his life with Queen Esther, for he knew that he was doomed.', 'NLT'),
(21, 7, 8, 'In despair he fell on the couch where Queen Esther was reclining, just as the king returned from the palace garden. "Will he even assault the queen right here in the palace, before my very eyes?" the king roared. And as soon as the king spoke, his attendants covered Haman''s face, signaling his doom.', 'NLT'),
(21, 7, 9, 'Then Harbona, one of the king''s eunuchs, said, "Haman has set up a gallows that stands seventy-five feet tall in his own courtyard. He intended to use it to hang Mordecai, the man who saved the king from assassination.Then hang Haman on it!" the king ordered.', 'NLT'),
(21, 7, 10, 'So they hanged Haman on the gallows he had set up for Mordecai, and the king''s anger was pacified.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 1, 'On that same day King Xerxes gave the estate of Haman, the enemy of the Jews, to Queen Esther. Then Mordecai was brought before the king, for Esther had told the king how they were related.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 2, 'The king took off his signet ring--which he had taken back from Haman--and gave it to Mordecai. And Esther appointed Mordecai to be in charge of Haman''s property.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 3, 'Now once more Esther came before the king, falling down at his feet and begging him with tears to stop Haman''s evil plot against the Jews.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 4, 'Again the king held out the gold scepter to Esther. So she rose and stood before him', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 5, 'and said, "If Your Majesty is pleased with me and if he thinks it is right, send out a decree reversing Haman''s orders to destroy the Jews throughout all the provinces of the king.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 6, 'For how can I endure to see my people and my family slaughtered and destroyed?"', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 7, 'Then King Xerxes said to Queen Esther and Mordecai the Jew, "I have given Esther the estate of Haman, and he has been hanged on the gallows because he tried to destroy the Jews.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 8, 'Now go ahead and send a message to the Jews in the king''s name, telling them whatever you want, and seal it with the king''s signet ring. But remember that whatever is written in the king''s name and sealed with his ring can never be revoked."', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 9, 'So on June 25 the king''s secretaries were summoned. As Mordecai dictated, they wrote a decree to the Jews and to the princes, governors, and local officials of all the 127 provinces stretching from India to Ethiopia. The decree was written in the scripts and languages of all the peoples of the empire, including the Jews.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 10, 'Mordecai wrote in the name of King Xerxes and sealed the message with the king''s signet ring. He sent the letters by swift messengers, who rode horses especially bred for the king''s service.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 11, 'The king''s decree gave the Jews in every city authority to unite to defend their lives. They were allowed to kill, slaughter, and annihilate anyone of any nationality or province who might attack them or their children and wives, and to take the property of their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 12, 'The day chosen for this event throughout all the provinces of King Xerxes was March 7 of the next year.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 13, 'A copy of this decree was to be recognized as law in every province and proclaimed to all the people. That way the Jews would be ready on that day to take revenge on their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 14, 'So urged on by the king''s command, the messengers rode out swiftly on horses bred for the king''s service. The same decree was also issued at the fortress of Susa.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 15, 'Then Mordecai put on the royal robe of blue and white and the great crown of gold, and he wore an outer cloak of fine linen and purple. And the people of Susa celebrated the new decree.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 16, 'The Jews were filled with joy and gladness and were honored everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(21, 8, 17, 'In every city and province, wherever the king''s decree arrived, the Jews rejoiced and had a great celebration and declared a public festival and holiday. And many of the people of the land became Jews themselves, for they feared what the Jews might do to them.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 1, 'So on March 7 the two decrees of the king were put into effect. On that day, the enemies of the Jews had hoped to destroy them, but quite the opposite happened.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 2, 'The Jews gathered in their cities throughout all the king''s provinces to defend themselves against anyone who might try to harm them. But no one could make a stand against them, for everyone was afraid of them.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 3, 'And all the commanders of the provinces, the princes, the governors, and the royal officials helped the Jews for fear of Mordecai.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 4, 'For Mordecai had been promoted in the king''s palace, and his fame spread throughout all the provinces as he became more and more powerful.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 5, 'But the Jews went ahead on the appointed day and struck down their enemies with the sword. They killed and annihilated their enemies and did as they pleased with those who hated them.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 6, 'They killed five hundred people in the fortress of Susa.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 7, 'They also killed Parshandatha, Dalphon, Aspatha,', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 8, 'Poratha, Adalia, Aridatha,', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 9, 'Parmashta, Arisai, Aridai, and Vaizatha--', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 10, 'the ten sons of Haman son of Hammedatha, the enemy of the Jews. But they did not take any plunder.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 11, 'That evening, when the king was informed of the number of people killed in the fortress of Susa,', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 12, 'he called for Queen Esther and said, "The Jews have killed five hundred people in the fortress of Susa alone and also Haman''s ten sons. If they have done that here, what has happened in the rest of the provinces? But now, what more do you want? It will be granted to you; tell me and I will do it."', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 13, 'And Esther said, "If it please Your Majesty, give the Jews in Susa permission to do again tomorrow as they have done today, and have the bodies of Haman''s ten sons hung from the gallows. "', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 14, 'So the king agreed, and the decree was announced in Susa. They also hung the bodies of Haman''s ten sons from the gallows.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 15, 'Then the Jews at Susa gathered together on March 8 and killed three hundred more people, though again they took no plunder.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 16, 'Meanwhile, the other Jews throughout the king''s provinces had gathered together to defend their lives. They gained relief from all their enemies, killing seventy-five thousand of those who hated them. But they did not take any plunder.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 17, 'Throughout the provinces this was done on March 7. Then on the following day they rested, celebrating their victory with a day of feasting and gladness.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 18, 'But the Jews at Susa continued killing their enemies on the second day also, and then rested on the third day, making that their day of feasting and gladness.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 19, 'So to this day, rural Jews living in unwalled villages celebrate an annual festival and holiday in late winter, when they rejoice and send gifts to each other.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 20, 'Mordecai recorded these events and sent letters to the Jews near and far, throughout all the king''s provinces,', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 21, 'encouraging them to celebrate an annual festival on these two days.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 22, 'He told them to celebrate these days with feasting and gladness and by giving gifts to each other and to the poor. This would commemorate a time when the Jews gained relief from their enemies, when their sorrow was turned into gladness and their mourning into joy.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 23, 'So the Jews adopted Mordecai''s suggestion and began this annual custom.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 24, 'Haman son of Hammedatha the Agagite, the enemy of the Jews, had plotted to crush and destroy them on the day and month determined by casting lots (the lots were called purim).', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 25, 'But when Esther came before the king, he issued a decree causing Haman''s evil plot to backfire, and Haman and his sons were hanged on the gallows.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 26, '(That is why this celebration is called Purim, because it is the ancient word for casting lots.) So because of Mordecai''s letter and because of what they had experienced,', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 27, 'the Jews throughout the realm agreed to inaugurate this tradition and to pass it on to their descendants and to all who became Jews. They declared they would never fail to celebrate these two prescribed days at the appointed time each year.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 28, 'These days would be remembered and kept from generation to generation and celebrated by every family throughout the provinces and cities of the empire. These days would never cease to be celebrated among the Jews, nor would the memory of what happened ever die out among their descendants.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 29, 'Then Queen Esther, the daughter of Abihail, along with Mordecai the Jew, wrote another letter putting the queen''s full authority behind Mordecai''s letter to establish the Festival of Purim.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 30, 'In addition, letters wishing peace and security were sent to the Jews throughout the 127 provinces of the empire of Xerxes.', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 31, 'These letters established the Festival of Purim--an annual celebration of these days at the appointed time, decreed by both Mordecai the Jew and Queen Esther. (The people decided to observe this festival, just as they had decided for themselves and their descendants to establish the times of fasting and mourning.)', 'NLT'),
(21, 9, 32, 'So the command of Esther confirmed the practices of Purim, and it was all written down in the records.', 'NLT'),
(21, 10, 1, 'King Xerxes imposed tribute throughout his empire, even to the distant coastlands.', 'NLT'),
(21, 10, 2, 'His great achievements and the full account of the greatness of Mordecai, whom the king had promoted, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Media and Persia.', 'NLT'),
(21, 10, 3, 'Mordecai the Jew became the prime minister, with authority next to that of King Xerxes himself. He was very great among the Jews, who held him in high esteem, because he worked for the good of his people and was a friend at the royal court for all of them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 1, 'There was a man named Job who lived in the land of Uz. He was blameless, a man of complete integrity. He feared God and stayed away from evil.', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 2, 'He had seven sons and three daughters.', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 3, 'He owned seven thousand sheep, three thousand camels, five hundred teams of oxen, and five hundred female donkeys, and he employed many servants. He was, in fact, the richest person in that entire area.', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 4, 'Every year when Job''s sons had birthdays, they invited their brothers and sisters to join them for a celebration. On these occasions they would get together to eat and drink.', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 5, 'When these celebrations ended--and sometimes they lasted several days--Job would purify his children. He would get up early in the morning and offer a burnt offering for each of them. For Job said to himself, "Perhaps my children have sinned and have cursed God in their hearts." This was Job''s regular practice.', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 6, 'One day the angels came to present themselves before the LORD, and Satan the Accuser came with them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 7, '"Where have you come from?" the LORD asked Satan. And Satan answered the LORD, "I have been going back and forth across the earth, watching everything that''s going on."', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 8, 'Then the LORD asked Satan, "Have you noticed my servant Job? He is the finest man in all the earth--a man of complete integrity. He fears God and will have nothing to do with evil."', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 9, 'Satan replied to the LORD, "Yes, Job fears God, but not without good reason!', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 10, 'You have always protected him and his home and his property from harm. You have made him prosperous in everything he does. Look how rich he is!', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 11, 'But take away everything he has, and he will surely curse you to your face!"', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 12, '"All right, you may test him," the LORD said to Satan. "Do whatever you want with everything he possesses, but don''t harm him physically." So Satan left the LORD''s presence.', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 13, 'One day when Job''s sons and daughters were dining at the oldest brother''s house,', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 14, 'a messenger arrived at Job''s home with this news: "Your oxen were plowing, with the donkeys feeding beside them,', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 15, 'when the Sabeans raided us. They stole all the animals and killed all the farmhands. I am the only one who escaped to tell you."', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 16, 'While he was still speaking, another messenger arrived with this news: "The fire of God has fallen from heaven and burned up your sheep and all the shepherds. I am the only one who escaped to tell you."', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 17, 'While he was still speaking, a third messenger arrived with this news: "Three bands of Chaldean raiders have stolen your camels and killed your servants. I am the only one who escaped to tell you."', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 18, 'While he was still speaking, another messenger arrived with this news: "Your sons and daughters were feasting in their oldest brother''s home.', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 19, 'Suddenly, a powerful wind swept in from the desert and hit the house on all sides. The house collapsed, and all your children are dead. I am the only one who escaped to tell you."', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 20, 'Job stood up and tore his robe in grief. Then he shaved his head and fell to the ground before God.', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 21, 'He said, "I came naked from my mother''s womb, and I will be stripped of everything when I die. The LORD gave me everything I had, and the LORD has taken it away. Praise the name of the LORD!"', 'NLT'),
(22, 1, 22, 'In all of this, Job did not sin by blaming God.', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 1, 'One day the angels came again to present themselves before the LORD, and Satan the Accuser came with them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 2, '"Where have you come from?" the LORD asked Satan. And Satan answered the LORD, "I have been going back and forth across the earth, watching everything that''s going on."', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 3, 'Then the LORD asked Satan, "Have you noticed my servant Job? He is the finest man in all the earth--a man of complete integrity. He fears God and will have nothing to do with evil. And he has maintained his integrity, even though you persuaded me to harm him without cause."', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 4, 'Satan replied to the LORD, "Skin for skin--he blesses you only because you bless him. A man will give up everything he has to save his life.', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 5, 'But take away his health, and he will surely curse you to your face!"', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 6, '"All right, do with him as you please," the LORD said to Satan. "But spare his life."', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 7, 'So Satan left the LORD''s presence, and he struck Job with a terrible case of boils from head to foot.', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 8, 'Then Job scraped his skin with a piece of broken pottery as he sat among the ashes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 9, 'His wife said to him, "Are you still trying to maintain your integrity? Curse God and die."', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 10, 'But Job replied, "You talk like a godless woman. Should we accept only good things from the hand of God and never anything bad?" So in all this, Job said nothing wrong.', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 11, 'Three of Job''s friends were Eliphaz the Temanite, Bildad the Shuhite, and Zophar the Naamathite. When they heard of the tragedy he had suffered, they got together and traveled from their homes to comfort and console him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 12, 'When they saw Job from a distance, they scarcely recognized him. Wailing loudly, they tore their robes and threw dust into the air over their heads to demonstrate their grief.', 'NLT'),
(22, 2, 13, 'Then they sat on the ground with him for seven days and nights. And no one said a word, for they saw that his suffering was too great for words.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 1, 'At last Job spoke, and he cursed the day of his birth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 2, 'He said:', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 3, '"Cursed be the day of my birth, and cursed be the night when I was conceived.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 4, 'Let that day be turned to darkness. Let it be lost even to God on high, and let it be shrouded in darkness.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 5, 'Yes, let the darkness and utter gloom claim it for its own. Let a black cloud overshadow it, and let the darkness terrify it.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 6, 'Let that night be blotted off the calendar, never again to be counted among the days of the year, never again to appear among the months.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 7, 'Let that night be barren. Let it have no joy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 8, 'Let those who are experts at cursing--those who are ready to rouse the sea monster--curse that day.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 9, 'Let its morning stars remain dark. Let it hope for light, but in vain; may it never see the morning light.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 10, 'Curse it for its failure to shut my mother''s womb, for letting me be born to all this trouble.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 11, '"Why didn''t I die at birth as I came from the womb?', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 12, 'Why did my mother let me live? Why did she nurse me at her breasts?', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 13, 'For if I had died at birth, I would be at peace now, asleep and at rest.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 14, 'I would rest with the world''s kings and prime ministers, famous for their great construction projects.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 15, 'I would rest with wealthy princes whose palaces were filled with gold and silver.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 16, 'Why was I not buried like a stillborn child, like a baby who never lives to see the light?', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 17, 'For in death the wicked cease from troubling, and the weary are at rest.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 18, 'Even prisoners are at ease in death, with no guards to curse them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 19, 'Rich and poor are there alike, and the slave is free from his master.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 20, '"Oh, why should light be given to the weary, and life to those in misery?', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 21, 'They long for death, and it won''t come. They search for death more eagerly than for hidden treasure.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 22, 'It is a blessed relief when they finally die, when they find the grave.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 23, 'Why is life given to those with no future, those destined by God to live in distress?', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 24, 'I cannot eat for sighing; my groans pour out like water.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 25, 'What I always feared has happened to me. What I dreaded has come to be.', 'NLT'),
(22, 3, 26, 'I have no peace, no quietness. I have no rest; instead, only trouble comes."', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 1, 'Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied to Job:', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 2, '"Will you be patient and let me say a word? For who could keep from speaking out?', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 3, '"In the past you have encouraged many a troubled soul to trust in God; you have supported those who were weak.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 4, 'Your words have strengthened the fallen; you steadied those who wavered.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 5, 'But now when trouble strikes, you faint and are broken.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 6, 'Does your reverence for God give you no confidence? Shouldn''t you believe that God will care for those who are upright?', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 7, '"Stop and think! Does the innocent person perish? When has the upright person been destroyed?', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 8, 'My experience shows that those who plant trouble and cultivate evil will harvest the same.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 9, 'They perish by a breath from God. They vanish in a blast of his anger.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 10, 'Though they are fierce young lions, they will all be broken and destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 11, 'The fierce lion will starve, and the cubs of the lioness will be scattered.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 12, '"This truth was given me in secret, as though whispered in my ear.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 13, 'It came in a vision at night as others slept.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 14, 'Fear gripped me; I trembled and shook with terror.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 15, 'A spirit swept past my face. Its wind sent shivers up my spine.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 16, 'It stopped, but I couldn''t see its shape. There was a form before my eyes, and a hushed voice said,', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 17, '`Can a mortal be just and upright before God? Can a person be pure before the Creator?''', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 18, '"If God cannot trust his own angels and has charged some of them with folly,', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 19, 'how much less will he trust those made of clay! Their foundation is dust, and they are crushed as easily as moths.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 20, 'They are alive in the morning, but by evening they are dead, gone forever without a trace.', 'NLT'),
(22, 4, 21, 'Their tent collapses; they die in ignorance.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 1, '"You may cry for help, but no one listens. You may turn to the angels, but they give you no help.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 2, 'Surely resentment destroys the fool, and jealousy kills the simple.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 3, 'From my experience, I know that fools who turn from God may be successful for the moment, but then comes sudden disaster.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 4, 'Their children are abandoned far from help, with no one to defend them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 5, 'Their harvests are stolen, and their wealth satisfies the thirst of many others, not themselves!', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 6, 'But evil does not spring from the soil, and trouble does not sprout from the earth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 7, 'People are born for trouble as predictably as sparks fly upward from a fire.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 8, '"My advice to you is this: Go to God and present your case to him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 9, 'For he does great works too marvelous to understand. He performs miracles without number.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 10, 'He gives rain for the earth. He sends water for the fields.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 11, 'He gives prosperity to the poor and humble, and he takes sufferers to safety.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 12, 'He frustrates the plans of the crafty, so their efforts will not succeed.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 13, 'He catches those who think they are wise in their own cleverness, so that their cunning schemes are thwarted.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 14, 'They grope in the daylight as though they were blind; they see no better in the daytime than at night.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 15, 'He rescues the poor from the cutting words of the strong. He saves them from the clutches of the powerful.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 16, 'And so at last the poor have hope, and the fangs of the wicked are broken.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 17, '"But consider the joy of those corrected by God! Do not despise the chastening of the Almighty when you sin.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 18, 'For though he wounds, he also bandages. He strikes, but his hands also heal.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 19, 'He will rescue you again and again so that no evil can touch you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 20, 'He will save you from death in time of famine, from the power of the sword in time of war.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 21, 'You will be safe from slander and will have no fear of destruction when it comes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 22, 'You will laugh at destruction and famine; wild animals will not terrify you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 23, 'You will be at peace with the stones of the field, and its wild animals will be at peace with you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 24, 'You will know that your home is kept safe. When you visit your pastures, nothing will be missing.', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 25, 'Your children will be many; your descendants will be as plentiful as grass!', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 26, 'You will live to a good old age. You will not be harvested until the proper time!', 'NLT'),
(22, 5, 27, '"We have found from experience that all this is true. Listen to my counsel, and apply it to yourself."', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 1, 'Then Job spoke again:', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 2, '"If my sadness could be weighed and my troubles be put on the scales,', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 3, 'they would be heavier than all the sands of the sea. That is why I spoke so rashly.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 4, 'For the Almighty has struck me down with his arrows. He has sent his poisoned arrows deep within my spirit. All God''s terrors are arrayed against me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 5, 'Don''t I have a right to complain? Wild donkeys bray when they find no green grass, and oxen low when they have no food.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 6, 'People complain when there is no salt in their food. And how tasteless is the uncooked white of an egg!', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 7, 'My appetite disappears when I look at it; I gag at the thought of eating it!', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 8, '"Oh, that I might have my request, that God would grant my hope.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 9, 'I wish he would crush me. I wish he would reach out his hand and kill me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 10, 'At least I can take comfort in this: Despite the pain, I have not denied the words of the Holy One.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 11, 'But I do not have the strength to endure. I do not have a goal that encourages me to carry on.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 12, 'Do I have strength as hard as stone? Is my body made of bronze?', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 13, 'No, I am utterly helpless, without any chance of success.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 14, '"One should be kind to a fainting friend, but you have accused me without the slightest fear of the Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 15, 'My brother, you have proved as unreliable as a seasonal brook that overflows its banks in the spring', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 16, 'when it is swollen with ice and melting snow.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 17, 'But when the hot weather arrives, the water disappears. The brook vanishes in the heat.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 18, 'The caravans turn aside to be refreshed, but there is nothing there to drink, and so they perish in the desert.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 19, 'With high hopes, the caravans from Tema and from Sheba stop for water,', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 20, 'but finding none, their hopes are dashed.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 21, 'You, too, have proved to be of no help. You have seen my calamity, and you are afraid.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 22, 'But why? Have I ever asked you for a gift? Have I begged you to use any of your wealth on my behalf?', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 23, 'Have I ever asked you to rescue me from my enemies? Have I asked you to save me from ruthless people?', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 24, '"All I want is a reasonable answer--then I will keep quiet. Tell me, what have I done wrong?', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 25, 'Honest words are painful, but what do your criticisms amount to?', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 26, 'Do you think your words are convincing when you disregard my cry of desperation?', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 27, 'You would even send an orphan into slavery or sell a friend.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 28, 'Look at me! Would I lie to your face?', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 29, 'Stop assuming my guilt, for I am righteous. Don''t be so unjust.', 'NLT'),
(22, 6, 30, 'Do you think I am lying? Don''t I know the difference between right and wrong?', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 1, '"Is this not the struggle of all humanity? A person''s life is long and hard, like that of a hired hand,', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 2, 'like a worker who longs for the day to end, like a servant waiting to be paid.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 3, 'I, too, have been assigned months of futility, long and weary nights of misery.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 4, 'When I go to bed, I think, `When will it be morning?'' But the night drags on, and I toss till dawn.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 5, 'My skin is filled with worms and scabs. My flesh breaks open, full of pus.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 6, '"My days are swifter than a weaver''s shuttle flying back and forth. They end without hope.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 7, 'O God, remember that my life is but a breath, and I will never again experience pleasure.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 8, 'You see me now, but not for long. Your eyes will be on me, but I will be dead.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 9, 'Just as a cloud dissipates and vanishes, those who die will not come back.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 10, 'They are gone forever from their home--never to be seen again.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 11, '"I cannot keep from speaking. I must express my anguish. I must complain in my bitterness.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 12, 'Am I a sea monster that you place a guard on me?', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 13, 'If I think, `My bed will comfort me, and I will try to forget my misery with sleep,''', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 14, 'you shatter me with dreams. You terrify me with visions.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 15, 'I would rather die of strangulation than go on and on like this.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 16, 'I hate my life. I do not want to go on living. Oh, leave me alone for these few remaining days.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 17, '"What are mere mortals, that you should make so much of us?', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 18, 'For you examine us every morning and test us every moment.', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 19, 'Why won''t you leave me alone--even for a moment?', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 20, 'Have I sinned? What have I done to you, O watcher of all humanity? Why have you made me your target? Am I a burden to you?', 'NLT'),
(22, 7, 21, 'Why not just pardon my sin and take away my guilt? For soon I will lie down in the dust and die. When you look for me, I will be gone."', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 1, 'Then Bildad the Shuhite replied to Job:', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 2, '"How long will you go on like this? Your words are a blustering wind.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 3, 'Does God twist justice? Does the Almighty twist what is right?', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 4, 'Your children obviously sinned against him, so their punishment was well deserved.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 5, 'But if you pray to God and seek the favor of the Almighty,', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 6, 'if you are pure and live with complete integrity, he will rise up and restore your happy home.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 7, 'And though you started with little, you will end with much.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 8, '"Just ask the former generation. Pay attention to the experience of our ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 9, 'For we were born but yesterday and know so little. Our days on earth are as transient as a shadow.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 10, 'But those who came before us will teach you. They will teach you from the wisdom of former generations.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 11, '"Can papyrus reeds grow where there is no marsh? Can bulrushes flourish where there is no water?', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 12, 'While they are still flowering, not ready to be cut, they begin to wither.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 13, 'Such is the fate of all who forget God. The hope of the godless comes to nothing.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 14, 'Everything they count on will collapse. They are leaning on a spiderweb.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 15, 'They cling to their home for security, but it won''t last. They try to hold it fast, but it will not endure.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 16, 'The godless seem so strong, like a lush plant growing in the sunshine, its branches spreading across the garden.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 17, 'Its roots grow down through a pile of rocks to hold it firm.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 18, 'But when it is uprooted, it isn''t even missed!', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 19, 'That is the end of its life, and others spring up from the earth to replace it.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 20, '"But look! God will not reject a person of integrity, nor will he make evildoers prosper.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 21, 'He will yet fill your mouth with laughter and your lips with shouts of joy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 8, 22, 'Those who hate you will be clothed with shame, and the tent of the wicked will be destroyed."', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 1, 'Then Job spoke again:', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 2, '"Yes, I know this is all true in principle. But how can a person be declared innocent in the eyes of God?', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 3, 'If someone wanted to take God to court, would it be possible to answer him even once in a thousand times?', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 4, 'For God is so wise and so mighty. Who has ever challenged him successfully?', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 5, '"Without warning, he moves the mountains, overturning them in his anger.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 6, 'He shakes the earth from its place, and its foundations tremble.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 7, 'If he commands it, the sun won''t rise and the stars won''t shine.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 8, 'He alone has spread out the heavens and marches on the waves of the sea.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 9, 'He made all the stars--the Bear, Orion, the Pleiades, and the constellations of the southern sky.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 10, 'His great works are too marvelous to understand. He performs miracles without number.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 11, '"Yet when he comes near, I cannot see him. When he moves on, I do not see him go.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 12, 'If he sends death to snatch someone away, who can stop him? Who dares to ask him, `What are you doing?''', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 13, 'And God does not restrain his anger. The mightiest forces against him are crushed beneath his feet.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 14, '"And who am I, that I should try to answer God or even reason with him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 15, 'Even if I were innocent, I would have no defense. I could only plead for mercy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 16, 'And even if I summoned him and he responded, he would never listen to me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 17, 'For he attacks me without reason, and he multiplies my wounds without cause.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 18, 'He will not let me catch my breath, but fills me instead with bitter sorrows.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 19, 'As for strength, he has it. As for justice, who can challenge him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 20, 'Though I am innocent, my own mouth would pronounce me guilty. Though I am blameless, it would prove me wicked.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 21, '"I am innocent, but it makes no difference to me--I despise my life.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 22, 'Innocent or wicked, it is all the same to him. That is why I say, `He destroys both the blameless and the wicked.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 23, 'He laughs when a plague suddenly kills the innocent.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 24, 'The whole earth is in the hands of the wicked, and God blinds the eyes of the judges and lets them be unfair. If not he, then who?', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 25, '"My life passes more swiftly than a runner. It flees away, filled with tragedy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 26, 'It disappears like a swift boat, like an eagle that swoops down on its prey.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 27, 'If I decided to forget my complaints, if I decided to end my sadness and be cheerful,', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 28, 'I would dread all the pain he would send. For I know you will not hold me innocent, O God.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 29, 'Whatever happens, I will be found guilty. So what''s the use of trying?', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 30, 'Even if I were to wash myself with soap and cleanse my hands with lye to make them absolutely clean,', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 31, 'you would plunge me into a muddy ditch, and I would be so filthy my own clothing would hate me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 32, '"God is not a mortal like me, so I cannot argue with him or take him to trial.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 33, 'If only there were a mediator who could bring us together, but there is none.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 34, 'The mediator could make God stop beating me, and I would no longer live in terror of his punishment.', 'NLT'),
(22, 9, 35, 'Then I could speak to him without fear, but I cannot do that in my own strength.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 1, '"I am disgusted with my life. Let me complain freely. I will speak in the bitterness of my soul.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 2, 'I will say to God, `Don''t simply condemn me--tell me the charge you are bringing against me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 3, 'What do you gain by oppressing me? Why do you reject me, the work of your own hands, while sending joy and prosperity to the wicked?', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 4, 'Are your eyes only those of a human? Do you see things as people see them?', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 5, 'Is your lifetime merely human? Is your life so short', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 6, 'that you are in a hurry to probe for my guilt, to search for my sin?', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 7, 'Although you know I am not guilty, no one can rescue me from your power.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 8, '" `You formed me with your hands; you made me, and yet you completely destroy me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 9, 'Remember that I am made of dust--will you turn me back to dust so soon?', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 10, 'You guided my conception and formed me in the womb.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 11, 'You clothed me with skin and flesh, and you knit my bones and sinews together.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 12, 'You gave me life and showed me your unfailing love. My life was preserved by your care.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 13, '" `Yet your real motive--I know this was your intent--', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 14, 'was to watch me, and if I sinned, you would not forgive my iniquity.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 15, 'If I am guilty, too bad for me. And even if I''m innocent, I am filled with shame and misery so that I can''t hold my head high.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 16, 'And if I hold my head high, you hunt me like a lion and display your awesome power against me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 17, 'Again and again you witness against me. You pour out an ever-increasing volume of anger upon me and bring fresh armies against me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 18, '" `Why, then, did you bring me out of my mother''s womb? Why didn''t you let me die at birth?', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 19, 'Then I would have been spared this miserable existence. I would have gone directly from the womb to the grave.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 20, 'I have only a little time left, so leave me alone--that I may have a little moment of comfort', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 21, 'before I leave for the land of darkness and utter gloom, never to return.', 'NLT'),
(22, 10, 22, 'It is a land as dark as midnight, a land of utter gloom where confusion reigns and the light is as dark as midnight.''"', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 1, 'Then Zophar the Naamathite replied to Job:', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 2, '"Shouldn''t someone answer this torrent of words? Is a person proved innocent just by talking a lot?', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 3, 'Should I remain silent while you babble on? When you mock God, shouldn''t someone make you ashamed?', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 4, 'You claim, `My teaching is pure,'' and `I am clean in the sight of God.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 5, 'If only God would speak; if only he would tell you what he thinks!', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 6, 'If only he would tell you the secrets of wisdom, for true wisdom is not a simple matter. Listen! God is doubtless punishing you far less than you deserve!', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 7, '"Can you solve the mysteries of God? Can you discover everything there is to know about the Almighty?', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 8, 'Such knowledge is higher than the heavens--but who are you? It is deeper than the underworld--what can you know in comparison to him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 9, 'It is broader than the earth and wider than the sea.', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 10, 'If God comes along and puts a person in prison, or if he calls the court to order, who is going to stop him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 11, 'For he knows those who are false, and he takes note of all their sins.', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 12, 'An empty-headed person won''t become wise any more than a wild donkey can bear human offspring!', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 13, '"If only you would prepare your heart and lift up your hands to him in prayer!', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 14, 'Get rid of your sins and leave all iniquity behind you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 15, 'Then your face will brighten in innocence. You will be strong and free of fear.', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 16, 'You will forget your misery. It will all be gone like water under the bridge.', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 17, 'Your life will be brighter than the noonday. Any darkness will be as bright as morning.', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 18, 'You will have courage because you will have hope. You will be protected and will rest in safety.', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 19, 'You will lie down unafraid, and many will look to you for help.', 'NLT'),
(22, 11, 20, 'But the wicked will lose hope. They have no escape. Their hope becomes despair."', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 1, 'Then Job spoke again:', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 2, '"You really know everything, don''t you? And when you die, wisdom will die with you!', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 3, 'Well, I know a few things myself--and you''re no better than I am. Who doesn''t know these things you''ve been saying?', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 4, 'Yet my friends laugh at me. I am a man who calls on God and receives an answer. I am a just and blameless man, yet they laugh at me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 5, 'People who are at ease mock those in trouble. They give a push to people who are stumbling.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 6, 'But even robbers are left in peace, and those who provoke God--and God has them in his power--live in safety!', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 7, '"Ask the animals, and they will teach you. Ask the birds of the sky, and they will tell you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 8, 'Speak to the earth, and it will instruct you. Let the fish of the sea speak to you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 9, 'They all know that the LORD has done this.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 10, 'For the life of every living thing is in his hand, and the breath of all humanity.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 11, 'Just as the mouth tastes good food, so the ear tests the words it hears.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 12, 'Wisdom belongs to the aged, and understanding to those who have lived many years.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 13, '"But true wisdom and power are with God; counsel and understanding are his.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 14, 'What he destroys cannot be rebuilt. When he closes in on someone, there is no escape.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 15, 'If he holds back the rain, the earth becomes a desert. If he releases the waters, they flood the earth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 16, '"Yes, strength and wisdom are with him; deceivers and deceived are both in his power.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 17, 'He leads counselors away stripped of good judgment; he drives judges to madness.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 18, 'He removes the royal robe of kings. With ropes around their waist, they are led away.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 19, 'He leads priests away stripped of status; he overthrows the mighty.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 20, 'He silences the trusted adviser, and he removes the insight of the elders.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 21, 'He pours disgrace upon princes and confiscates weapons from the strong.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 22, '"He floods the darkness with light; he brings light to the deepest gloom.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 23, 'He raises up nations, and he destroys them. He makes nations expand, and he abandons them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 24, 'He takes away the understanding of kings, and he leaves them wandering in a wasteland without a path.', 'NLT'),
(22, 12, 25, 'They grope in the darkness without a light. He makes them stagger like drunkards.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 1, '"Look, I have seen many instances such as you describe. I understand what you are saying.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 2, 'I know as much as you do. You are no better than I am.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 3, 'Oh, how I long to speak directly to the Almighty. I want to argue my case with God himself.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 4, 'For you are smearing me with lies. As doctors, you are worthless quacks.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 5, 'Please be quiet! That''s the smartest thing you could do.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 6, 'Listen to my charge; pay attention to my arguments.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 7, '"Are you defending God by means of lies and dishonest arguments?', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 8, 'You should be impartial witnesses, but will you slant your testimony in his favor? Will you argue God''s case for him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 9, 'Be careful that he doesn''t find out what you are doing! Or do you think you can fool him as easily as you fool people?', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 10, 'No, you will be in serious trouble with him if even in your hearts you slant your testimony in his favor.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 11, 'Doesn''t his majesty strike terror into your heart? Does not your fear of him seize you?', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 12, 'Your statements have about as much value as ashes. Your defense is as fragile as a clay pot.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 13, '"Be silent now and leave me alone. Let me speak--and I will face the consequences.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 14, 'Yes, I will take my life in my hands and say what I really think.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 15, 'God might kill me, but I cannot wait. I am going to argue my case with him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 16, 'But this is what will save me: that I am not godless. If I were, I would be thrown from his presence.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 17, '"Listen closely to what I am about to say. Hear me out.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 18, 'I have prepared my case; I will be proved innocent.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 19, 'Who can argue with me over this? If you could prove me wrong, I would remain silent until I die.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 20, '"O God, there are two things I beg of you, and I will be able to face you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 21, 'Remove your hand from me, and don''t terrify me with your awesome presence.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 22, 'Now summon me, and I will answer! Or let me speak to you, and you reply.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 23, 'Tell me, what have I done wrong? Show me my rebellion and my sin.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 24, 'Why do you turn away from me? Why do you consider me your enemy?', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 25, 'Would you terrify a leaf that is blown by the wind? Would you chase a dry stalk of grass?', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 26, '"You write bitter accusations against me and bring up all the sins of my youth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 27, 'You put my feet in stocks. You watch all my paths. You trace all my footprints.', 'NLT'),
(22, 13, 28, 'I waste away like rotting wood, like a moth-eaten coat.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 1, '"How frail is humanity! How short is life, and how full of trouble!', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 2, 'Like a flower, we blossom for a moment and then wither. Like the shadow of a passing cloud, we quickly disappear.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 3, 'Must you keep an eye on such a frail creature and demand an accounting from me?', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 4, 'Who can create purity in one born impure? No one!', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 5, 'You have decided the length of our lives. You know how many months we will live, and we are not given a minute longer.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 6, 'So give us a little rest, won''t you? Turn away your angry stare. We are like hired hands, so let us finish the task you have given us.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 7, '"If a tree is cut down, there is hope that it will sprout again and grow new branches.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 8, 'Though its roots have grown old in the earth and its stump decays,', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 9, 'at the scent of water it may bud and sprout again like a new seedling.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 10, '"But when people die, they lose all strength. They breathe their last, and then where are they?', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 11, 'As water evaporates from a lake and as a river disappears in drought,', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 12, 'people lie down and do not rise again. Until the heavens are no more, they will not wake up nor be roused from their sleep.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 13, '"I wish you would hide me with the dead and forget me there until your anger has passed. But mark your calendar to think of me again!', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 14, 'If mortals die, can they live again? This thought would give me hope, and through my struggle I would eagerly wait for release.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 15, 'You would call and I would answer, and you would yearn for me, your handiwork.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 16, 'For then you would count my steps, instead of watching for my sins.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 17, 'My sins would be sealed in a pouch, and you would cover over my iniquity.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 18, '"But as mountains fall and crumble and as rocks fall from a cliff,', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 19, 'as water wears away the stones and floods wash away the soil, so you destroy people''s hope.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 20, 'You always overpower them, and then they pass from the scene. You disfigure them in death and send them away.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 21, 'They never know if their sons grow up in honor or sink to insignificance.', 'NLT'),
(22, 14, 22, 'They are absorbed in their own pain and grief."', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 1, 'Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied:', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 2, '"You are supposed to be a wise man, and yet you give us all this foolish talk. You are nothing but a windbag.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 3, 'It isn''t right to speak so foolishly. What good do such words do?', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 4, 'Have you no fear of God, no reverence for him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 5, 'Your sins are telling your mouth what to say. Your words are based on clever deception.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 6, 'But why should I condemn you? Your own mouth does!', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 7, '"Were you the first person ever born? Were you born before the hills were made?', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 8, 'Were you listening at God''s secret council? Do you have a monopoly on wisdom?', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 9, 'What do you know that we don''t? What do you understand that we don''t?', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 10, 'On our side are aged, gray-haired men much older than your father!', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 11, '"Is God''s comfort too little for you? Is his gentle word not enough?', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 12, 'What has captured your reason? What has weakened your vision,', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 13, 'that you turn against God and say all these evil things?', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 14, 'Can a mortal be pure? Can a human be just?', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 15, 'Why, God doesn''t even trust the angels! Even the heavens cannot be absolutely pure in his sight.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 16, 'How much less pure is a corrupt and sinful person with a thirst for wickedness!', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 17, '"If you will listen, I will answer you from my own experience.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 18, 'And it is confirmed by the experience of wise men who have heard the same thing from their fathers,', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 19, 'those to whom the land was given long before any foreigners arrived.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 20, '"Wicked people are in pain throughout their lives.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 21, 'They are surrounded by terrors, and even on good days they fear the attack of the destroyer.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 22, 'They dare not go out into the darkness for fear they will be murdered.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 23, 'They wander abroad for bread, saying, `Where is it?'' They know their ruin is certain.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 24, 'That dark day terrifies them. They live in distress and anguish, like a king preparing for an attack.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 25, 'For they have clenched their fists against God, defying the Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 26, 'Holding their strong shields, they defiantly charge against him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 27, '"These wicked people are fat and rich,', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 28, 'but their cities will be ruined. They will live in abandoned houses that are ready to tumble down.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 29, 'They will not continue to be rich. Their wealth will not endure, and their possessions will no longer spread across the horizon.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 30, '"They will not escape the darkness. The flame will burn them up, and the breath of God will destroy everything they have.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 31, 'Let them no longer trust in empty riches. They are only fooling themselves, for emptiness will be their only reward.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 32, 'They will be cut down in the prime of life, and all they counted on will disappear.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 33, 'They will be like a vine whose grapes are harvested before they are ripe, like an olive tree that sheds its blossoms so the fruit cannot form.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 34, 'For the godless are barren. Their homes, enriched through bribery, will be consumed by fire.', 'NLT'),
(22, 15, 35, 'They conceive trouble and evil, and their hearts give birth only to deceit."', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 1, 'Then Job spoke again:', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 2, '"I have heard all this before. What miserable comforters you are!', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 3, 'Won''t you ever stop your flow of foolish words? What have I said that makes you speak so endlessly?', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 4, 'I could say the same things if you were in my place. I could spout off my criticisms against you and shake my head at you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 5, 'But that''s not what I would do. I would speak in a way that helps you. I would try to take away your grief.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 6, 'But as it is, my grief remains no matter how I defend myself. And it does not help if I refuse to speak.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 7, '"O God, you have ground me down and devastated my family.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 8, 'You have reduced me to skin and bones--as proof, they say, of my sins.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 9, 'God hates me and tears angrily at my flesh. He gnashes his teeth at me and pierces me with his eyes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 10, 'People jeer and laugh at me. They slap my cheek in contempt. A mob gathers against me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 11, 'God has handed me over to sinners. He has tossed me into the hands of the wicked.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 12, '"I was living quietly until he broke me apart. He took me by the neck and dashed me to pieces. Then he set me up as his target.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 13, 'His archers surrounded me, and his arrows pierced me without mercy. The ground is wet with my blood.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 14, 'Again and again he smashed me, charging at me like a warrior.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 15, 'Here I sit in sackcloth. I have surrendered, and I sit in the dust.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 16, 'My eyes are red with weeping; darkness covers my eyes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 17, 'Yet I am innocent, and my prayer is pure.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 18, '"O earth, do not conceal my blood. Let it cry out on my behalf.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 19, 'Even now my witness is in heaven. My advocate is there on high.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 20, 'My friends scorn me, but I pour out my tears to God.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 21, 'Oh, that someone would mediate between God and me, as a person mediates between friends.', 'NLT'),
(22, 16, 22, 'For soon I must go down that road from which I will never return.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 1, '"My spirit is crushed, and I am near death. The grave is ready to receive me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 2, 'I am surrounded by mockers. I watch how bitterly they taunt me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 3, '"You must defend my innocence, O God, since no one else will stand up for me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 4, 'You have closed their minds to understanding, but do not let them triumph.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 5, 'They denounce their companions for their own advantage, so let their children faint with hunger.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 6, '"God has made a mockery of me among the people; they spit in my face.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 7, 'My eyes are dim with weeping, and I am but a shadow of my former self.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 8, 'The upright are astonished when they see me. The innocent are aroused against the ungodly.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 9, 'The righteous will move onward and forward, and those with pure hearts will become stronger and stronger.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 10, '"As for all of you, come back and try again! But I will not find a wise man among you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 11, 'My days are over. My hopes have disappeared. My heart''s desires are broken.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 12, 'They say that night is day and day is night; how they pervert the truth!', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 13, 'I might go to the grave and make my bed in darkness.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 14, 'And I might call the grave my father, and the worm my mother and my sister.', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 15, 'But where then is my hope? Can anyone find it?', 'NLT'),
(22, 17, 16, 'No, my hope will go down with me to the grave. We will rest together in the dust!"', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 1, 'Then Bildad the Shuhite replied:', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 2, '"How long before you stop talking? Speak sense if you want us to answer!', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 3, 'Do you think we are cattle? Do you think we have no intelligence?', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 4, 'You may tear your hair out in anger, but will that cause the earth to be abandoned? Will it make rocks fall from a cliff?', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 5, '"The truth remains that the light of the wicked will be snuffed out. The sparks of their fire will not glow.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 6, 'The light in their tent will grow dark. The lamp hanging above them will be quenched.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 7, 'The confident stride of the wicked will be shortened. Their own schemes will be their downfall.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 8, '"The wicked walk into a net. They fall into a pit that''s been dug in the path.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 9, 'A trap grabs them by the heel. A noose tightens around them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 10, 'A snare lies hidden in the ground. A rope lies coiled on their path.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 11, '"Terrors surround the wicked and trouble them at every step.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 12, 'Their vigor is depleted by hunger, and calamity waits for them to stumble.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 13, 'Disease eats their skin; death devours their limbs.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 14, 'They are torn from the security of their tent, and they are brought down to the king of terrors.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 15, 'The home of the wicked will disappear beneath a fiery barrage of burning sulfur.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 16, 'Their roots will dry up, and their branches will wither.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 17, 'All memory of their existence will perish from the earth. No one will remember them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 18, 'They will be thrust from light into darkness, driven from the world.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 19, 'They will have neither children nor grandchildren, nor any survivor in their home country.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 20, 'People in the west are appalled at their fate; people in the east are horrified.', 'NLT'),
(22, 18, 21, 'They will say, `This was the home of a wicked person, the place of one who rejected God.''"', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 1, 'Then Job spoke again:', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 2, '"How long will you torture me? How long will you try to break me with your words?', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 3, 'Ten times now you have meant to insult me. You should be ashamed of dealing with me so harshly.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 4, 'And even if I have sinned, that is my concern, not yours.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 5, 'You are trying to overcome me, using my humiliation as evidence of my sin,', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 6, 'but it is God who has wronged me. I cannot defend myself, for I am like a city under siege.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 7, '"I cry out for help, but no one hears me. I protest, but there is no justice.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 8, 'God has blocked my way and plunged my path into darkness.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 9, 'He has stripped me of my honor and removed the crown from my head.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 10, 'He has demolished me on every side, and I am finished. He has destroyed my hope.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 11, 'His fury burns against me; he counts me as an enemy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 12, 'His troops advance. They build up roads to attack me. They camp all around my tent.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 13, '"My relatives stay far away, and my friends have turned against me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 14, 'My neighbors and my close friends are all gone.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 15, 'The members of my household have forgotten me. The servant girls consider me a stranger. I am like a foreigner to them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 16, 'I call my servant, but he doesn''t come; I even plead with him!', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 17, 'My breath is repulsive to my wife. I am loathsome to my own family.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 18, 'Even young children despise me. When I stand to speak, they turn their backs on me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 19, 'My close friends abhor me. Those I loved have turned against me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 20, 'I have been reduced to skin and bones and have escaped death by the skin of my teeth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 21, '"Have mercy on me, my friends, have mercy, for the hand of God has struck me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 22, 'Why must you persecute me as God does? Why aren''t you satisfied with my anguish?', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 23, '"Oh, that my words could be written. Oh, that they could be inscribed on a monument,', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 24, 'carved with an iron chisel and filled with lead, engraved forever in the rock.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 25, '"But as for me, I know that my Redeemer lives, and that he will stand upon the earth at last.', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 26, 'And after my body has decayed, yet in my body I will see God!', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 27, 'I will see him for myself. Yes, I will see him with my own eyes. I am overwhelmed at the thought!', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 28, '"How dare you go on persecuting me, saying, `It''s his own fault''?', 'NLT'),
(22, 19, 29, 'I warn you, you yourselves are in danger of punishment for your attitude. Then you will know that there is judgment."', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 1, 'Then Zophar the Naamathite replied:', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 2, '"I must reply because I am greatly disturbed.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 3, 'I have had to endure your insults, but now my spirit prompts me to reply.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 4, '"Don''t you realize that ever since people were first placed on the earth,', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 5, 'the triumph of the wicked has been short-lived and the joy of the godless has been only temporary?', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 6, 'Though the godless man''s pride reaches to the heavens and though his head touches the clouds,', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 7, 'yet he will perish forever, thrown away like his own dung. Those who knew him will ask, `Where is he?''', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 8, 'He will fade like a dream and not be found. He will vanish like a vision in the night.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 9, 'Neither his friends nor his family will ever see him again.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 10, 'His children will beg from the poor, for he must give back his ill-gotten wealth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 11, 'He was just a young man, but his bones will lie in the dust.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 12, '"He enjoyed the taste of his wickedness, letting it melt under his tongue.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 13, 'He savored it, holding it long in his mouth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 14, 'But suddenly, the food he has eaten turns sour within him, a poisonous venom in his stomach.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 15, 'He will vomit the wealth he swallowed. God won''t let him keep it down.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 16, 'He will suck the poison of snakes. The viper will kill him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 17, 'He will never again enjoy abundant streams of olive oil or rivers of milk and honey.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 18, 'His labors will not be rewarded. His wealth will bring him no joy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 19, 'For he oppressed the poor and left them destitute. He foreclosed on their homes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 20, 'He was always greedy but never satisfied. Of all the things he dreamed about, nothing remains.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 21, 'Nothing is left after he finishes gorging himself; therefore, his prosperity will not endure.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 22, '"In the midst of plenty, he will run into trouble, and disasters will destroy him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 23, 'May God give him a bellyful of trouble. May God rain down his anger upon him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 24, 'He will try to escape, but God''s arrow will pierce him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 25, 'The arrow is pulled from his body, and the arrowhead glistens with blood. The terrors of death are upon him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 26, '"His treasures will be lost in deepest darkness. A wildfire will devour his goods, consuming all he has left.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 27, 'The heavens will reveal his guilt, and the earth will give testimony against him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 28, 'A flood will sweep away his house. God''s anger will descend on him in torrents.', 'NLT'),
(22, 20, 29, 'This is the fate that awaits the wicked. It is the inheritance decreed by God."', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 1, 'Then Job spoke again:', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 2, '"Listen closely to what I am saying. You can console me by listening to me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 3, 'Bear with me, and let me speak. After I have spoken, you may mock me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 4, '"My complaint is with God, not with people. No wonder I''m so impatient.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 5, 'Look at me and be stunned. Put your hand over your mouth in shock.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 6, 'When I think about what I am saying, I shudder. My body trembles.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 7, '"The truth is that the wicked live to a good old age. They grow old and wealthy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 8, 'They live to see their children grow to maturity, and they enjoy their grandchildren.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 9, 'Their homes are safe from every fear, and God does not punish them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 10, 'Their bulls never fail to breed. Their cows bear calves without miscarriage.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 11, 'Their children skip about like lambs in a flock of sheep.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 12, 'They sing with tambourine and harp. They make merry to the sound of the flute.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 13, 'They spend their days in prosperity; then they go down to the grave in peace.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 14, 'All this, even though they say to God, `Go away. We want no part of you and your ways.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 15, 'Who is the Almighty, and why should we obey him? What good will it do us if we pray?''', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 16, 'But their prosperity is not of their own doing, so I will have nothing to do with that kind of thinking.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 17, '"Yet the wicked get away with it time and time again. They rarely have trouble, and God skips them when he distributes sorrows in his anger.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 18, 'Are they driven before the wind like straw? Are they carried away by the storm? Not at all!', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 19, '" `Well,'' you say, `at least God will punish their children!'' But I say that God should punish the ones who sin, not their children! Let them feel their own penalty.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 20, 'Let their own eyes see their destruction. Let them drink deeply of the anger of the Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 21, 'For when they are dead, they will not care what happens to their family.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 22, '"But who can teach a lesson to God, the supreme Judge?', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 23, 'One person dies in prosperity and security,', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 24, 'the very picture of good health.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 25, 'Another person dies in bitter poverty, never having tasted the good life.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 26, 'Both alike are buried in the same dust, both eaten by the same worms.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 27, '"Look, I know your thoughts. I know the schemes you plot against me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 28, 'You will tell me of rich and wicked people who came to disaster because of their sins.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 29, 'But I tell you to ask those who have been around, and they can tell you the truth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 30, 'Evil people are spared in times of calamity and are allowed to escape.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 31, 'No one rebukes them openly. No one repays them for what they have done.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 32, 'When they are carried to the grave, an honor guard keeps watch at their tomb.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 33, 'A great funeral procession goes to the cemetery. Many pay their respects as the body is laid to rest and the earth gives sweet repose.', 'NLT'),
(22, 21, 34, '"How can you comfort me? All your explanations are wrong!"', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 1, 'Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied:', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 2, '"Can a person''s actions be of benefit to God? Can even a wise person be helpful to him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 3, 'Is it any pleasure to the Almighty if you are righteous? Would it be any gain to him if you were perfect?', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 4, 'Is it because of your reverence for him that he accuses and judges you?', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 5, 'Not at all! It is because of your wickedness! Your guilt has no limit!', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 6, '"For example, you must have lent money to your friend and then kept the clothing he gave you as a pledge. Yes, you stripped him to the bone.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 7, 'You must have refused water for the thirsty and food for the hungry.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 8, 'After all, you think the land belongs to the powerful and that those who are privileged have a right to it!', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 9, 'You must have sent widows away without helping them and crushed the strength of orphans.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 10, 'That is why you are surrounded by traps and sudden fears.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 11, 'That is why you cannot see in the darkness, and waves of water cover you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 12, '"God is so great--higher than the heavens, higher than the farthest stars.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 13, 'But you reply, `That''s why God can''t see what I am doing! How can he judge through the thick darkness?', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 14, 'For thick clouds swirl about him, and he cannot see us. He is way up there, walking on the vault of heaven.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 15, '"Will you continue on the old paths where evil people have walked?', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 16, 'They were snatched away in the prime of life, and the foundations of their lives were washed away forever.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 17, 'For they said to God, `Leave us alone! What can the Almighty do for us?''', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 18, 'But they forgot that he had filled their homes with good things, so I will have nothing to do with that kind of thinking.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 19, '"Now the righteous will be happy to see the wicked destroyed, and the innocent will laugh them to scorn.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 20, 'They will say, `Surely our enemies have been destroyed. The last of them have been consumed in the fire.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 21, '"Stop quarreling with God! If you agree with him, you will have peace at last, and things will go well for you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 22, 'Listen to his instructions, and store them in your heart.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 23, 'If you return to the Almighty and clean up your life, you will be restored.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 24, 'Give up your lust for money, and throw your precious gold into the river.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 25, 'Then the Almighty himself will be your treasure. He will be your precious silver!', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 26, '"Then you will delight yourself in the Almighty and look up to God.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 27, 'You will pray to him, and he will hear you, and you will fulfill your vows to him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 28, 'Whatever you decide to do will be accomplished, and light will shine on the road ahead of you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 29, 'If someone is brought low and you say, `Help him up,'' God will save the downcast.', 'NLT'),
(22, 22, 30, 'Then even sinners will be rescued by your pure hands."', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 1, 'Then Job spoke again:', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 2, '"My complaint today is still a bitter one, and I try hard not to groan aloud.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 3, 'If only I knew where to find God, I would go to his throne and talk with him there.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 4, 'I would lay out my case and present my arguments.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 5, 'Then I would listen to his reply and understand what he says to me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 6, 'Would he merely argue with me in his greatness? No, he would give me a fair hearing.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 7, 'Fair and honest people can reason with him, so I would be acquitted by my Judge.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 8, '"I go east, but he is not there. I go west, but I cannot find him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 9, 'I do not see him in the north, for he is hidden. I turn to the south, but I cannot find him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 10, 'But he knows where I am going. And when he has tested me like gold in a fire, he will pronounce me innocent.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 11, '"For I have stayed in God''s paths; I have followed his ways and not turned aside.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 12, 'I have not departed from his commands but have treasured his word in my heart.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 13, 'Nevertheless, his mind concerning me remains unchanged, and who can turn him from his purposes? Whatever he wants to do, he does.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 14, 'So he will do for me all he has planned. He controls my destiny.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 15, 'No wonder I am so terrified in his presence. When I think of it, terror grips me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 16, 'God has made my heart faint; the Almighty has terrified me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 23, 17, 'Darkness is all around me; thick, impenetrable darkness is everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 1, '"Why doesn''t the Almighty open the court and bring judgment? Why must the godly wait for him in vain?', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 2, 'Evil people steal land by moving the boundary markers. They steal flocks of sheep,', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 3, 'and they even take donkeys from the poor and fatherless. A poor widow must surrender her valuable ox as collateral for a loan.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 4, 'The poor are kicked aside; the needy must hide together for safety.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 5, 'Like the wild donkeys in the desert, the poor must spend all their time just getting enough to keep body and soul together. They go into the desert to search for food for their children.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 6, 'They harvest a field they do not own, and they glean in the vineyards of the wicked.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 7, 'All night they lie naked in the cold, without clothing or covering.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 8, 'They are soaked by mountain showers, and they huddle against the rocks for want of a home.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 9, '"The wicked snatch a widow''s child from her breast; they take the baby as a pledge for a loan.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 10, 'The poor must go about naked, without any clothing. They are forced to carry food while they themselves are starving.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 11, 'They press out olive oil without being allowed to taste it, and they tread in the winepress as they suffer from thirst.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 12, 'The groans of the dying rise from the city, and the wounded cry for help, yet God does not respond to their moaning.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 13, '"Wicked people rebel against the light. They refuse to acknowledge its ways. They will not stay in its paths.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 14, 'The murderer rises in the early dawn to kill the poor and needy; at night he is a thief.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 15, 'The adulterer waits for the twilight, for he says, `No one will see me then.'' He masks his face so no one will know him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 16, 'They break into houses at night and sleep in the daytime. They are not acquainted with the light.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 17, 'The black night is their morning. They ally themselves with the terrors of the darkness.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 18, '"But they disappear from the earth as quickly as foam is swept down a river. Everything they own is cursed, so that no one enters their vineyard.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 19, 'Death consumes sinners just as drought and heat consume snow.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 20, 'Even the sinner''s own mother will forget him. Worms will find him sweet to eat. No one will remember him. Wicked people are broken like a tree in the storm.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 21, 'For they have taken advantage of the childless who have no protecting sons. They refuse to help the needy widows.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 22, '"God, in his power, drags away the rich. They may rise high, but they have no assurance in life.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 23, 'They may be allowed to live in security, but God is always watching them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 24, 'And though they are great now, in a moment they will be gone like all others, withered like heads of grain.', 'NLT'),
(22, 24, 25, '"Can anyone claim otherwise? Who can prove me wrong?"', 'NLT'),
(22, 25, 1, 'Then Bildad the Shuhite replied:', 'NLT'),
(22, 25, 2, '"God is powerful and dreadful. He enforces peace in the heavens.', 'NLT'),
(22, 25, 3, 'Who is able to count his heavenly army? Does his light not shine on all the earth?', 'NLT'),
(22, 25, 4, 'How can a mere mortal stand before God and claim to be righteous? Who in all the earth is pure?', 'NLT'),
(22, 25, 5, 'God is so glorious that even the moon and stars scarcely shine compared to him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 25, 6, 'How much less are mere people, who are but worms in his sight?"', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 1, 'Then Job spoke again:', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 2, '"How you have helped the powerless! How you have saved a person who has no strength!', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 3, 'How you have enlightened my stupidity! What wise things you have said!', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 4, 'Where have you gotten all these wise sayings? Whose spirit speaks through you?', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 5, '"The dead tremble in their place beneath the waters.', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 6, 'The underworld is naked in God''s presence. There is no cover for the place of destruction.', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 7, 'God stretches the northern sky over empty space and hangs the earth on nothing.', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 8, 'He wraps the rain in his thick clouds, and the clouds do not burst with the weight.', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 9, 'He shrouds his throne with his clouds.', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 10, 'He created the horizon when he separated the waters; he set the boundaries for day and night.', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 11, 'The foundations of heaven tremble at his rebuke.', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 12, 'By his power the sea grew calm. By his skill he crushed the great sea monster.', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 13, 'His Spirit made the heavens beautiful, and his power pierced the gliding serpent.', 'NLT'),
(22, 26, 14, '"These are some of the minor things he does, merely a whisper of his power. Who can understand the thunder of his power?"', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 1, 'Job continued speaking:', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 2, '"I make this vow by the living God, who has taken away my rights, by the Almighty who has embittered my soul.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 3, 'As long as I live, while I have breath from God,', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 4, 'my lips will speak no evil, and my tongue will speak no lies.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 5, 'I will never concede that you are right; until I die, I will defend my innocence.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 6, 'I will maintain my innocence without wavering. My conscience is clear for as long as I live.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 7, '"May my enemy be punished like the wicked, my adversary like evil men.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 8, 'For what hope do the godless have when God cuts them off and takes away their life?', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 9, 'Will God listen to their cry when trouble comes upon them?', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 10, 'Can they take delight in the Almighty? Can they call to God at any time?', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 11, '"I will teach you about God''s power. I will not conceal anything that concerns the Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 12, 'But I don''t need to, for you yourselves have seen all this; yet you are saying all these useless things to me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 13, '"This is what the wicked will receive from God; this is their inheritance from the Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 14, 'If they have a multitude of children, their children will die in war or starve to death.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 15, 'Those who survive will be brought down to the grave by a plague, with no one to mourn them, not even their wives.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 16, '"Evil people may have all the money in the world, and they may store away mounds of clothing.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 17, 'But the righteous will wear that clothing, and the innocent will divide all that money.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 18, 'The houses built by the wicked are as fragile as a spiderweb, as flimsy as a shelter made of branches.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 19, '"The wicked go to bed rich but wake up to find that all their wealth is gone.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 20, 'Terror overwhelms them, and they are blown away in the storms of the night.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 21, 'The east wind carries them away, and they are gone. It sweeps them away.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 22, 'It whirls down on them without mercy. They struggle to flee from its power.', 'NLT'),
(22, 27, 23, 'But everyone jeers at them and mocks them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 1, '"People know how to mine silver and refine gold.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 2, 'They know how to dig iron from the earth and smelt copper from stone.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 3, 'They know how to put light into darkness and explore the farthest, darkest regions of the earth as they search for ore.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 4, 'They sink a mine shaft into the earth far from where anyone lives. They descend on ropes, swinging back and forth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 5, 'Bread comes from the earth, but below the surface the earth is melted as by fire.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 6, '"People know how to find sapphires and gold dust--', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 7, 'treasures that no bird of prey can see, no falcon''s eye observe--', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 8, 'for they are deep within the mines. No wild animal has ever walked upon those treasures; no lion has set his paw there.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 9, 'People know how to tear apart flinty rocks and overturn the roots of mountains.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 10, 'They cut tunnels in the rocks and uncover precious stones.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 11, 'They dam up the trickling streams and bring to light the hidden treasures.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 12, '"But do people know where to find wisdom? Where can they find understanding?', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 13, 'No one knows where to find it, for it is not found among the living.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 14, '`It is not here,'' says the ocean. `Nor is it here,'' says the sea.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 15, '"It cannot be bought for gold or silver.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 16, 'Its value is greater than all the gold of Ophir, greater than precious onyx stone or sapphires.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 17, 'Wisdom is far more valuable than gold and crystal. It cannot be purchased with jewels mounted in fine gold.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 18, 'Coral and valuable rock crystal are worthless in trying to get it. The price of wisdom is far above pearls.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 19, 'Topaz from Ethiopia cannot be exchanged for it. Its value is greater than the purest gold.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 20, '"But do people know where to find wisdom? Where can they find understanding?', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 21, 'For it is hidden from the eyes of all humanity. Even the sharp-eyed birds in the sky cannot discover it.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 22, 'But Destruction and Death say, `We have heard a rumor of where wisdom can be found.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 23, '"God surely knows where it can be found,', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 24, 'for he looks throughout the whole earth, under all the heavens.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 25, 'He made the winds blow and determined how much rain should fall.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 26, 'He made the laws of the rain and prepared a path for the lightning.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 27, 'Then, when he had done all this, he saw wisdom and measured it. He established it and examined it thoroughly.', 'NLT'),
(22, 28, 28, 'And this is what he says to all humanity: `The fear of the Lord is true wisdom; to forsake evil is real understanding.''"', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 1, 'Job continued speaking:', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 2, '"I long for the years gone by when God took care of me,', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 3, 'when he lighted the way before me and I walked safely through the darkness.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 4, 'In my early years, the friendship of God was felt in my home.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 5, 'The Almighty was still with me, and my children were around me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 6, 'In those days my cows produced milk in abundance, and my olive groves poured out streams of olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 7, '"Those were the days when I went to the city gate and took my place among the honored leaders.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 8, 'The young stepped aside when they saw me, and even the aged rose in respect at my coming.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 9, 'The princes stood in silence and put their hands over their mouths.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 10, 'The highest officials of the city stood quietly, holding their tongues in respect.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 11, '"All who heard of me praised me. All who saw me spoke well of me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 12, 'For I helped the poor in their need and the orphans who had no one to help them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 13, 'I helped those who had lost hope, and they blessed me. And I caused the widows'' hearts to sing for joy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 14, 'All I did was just and honest. Righteousness covered me like a robe, and I wore justice like a turban.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 15, 'I served as eyes for the blind and feet for the lame.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 16, 'I was a father to the poor and made sure that even strangers received a fair trial.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 17, 'I broke the jaws of godless oppressors and made them release their victims.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 18, '"I thought, `Surely I will die surrounded by my family after a long, good life.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 19, 'For I am like a tree whose roots reach the water, whose branches are refreshed with the dew.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 20, 'New honors are constantly bestowed on me, and my strength is continually renewed.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 21, '"Everyone listened to me and valued my advice. They were silent as they waited for me to speak.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 22, 'And after I spoke, they had nothing to add, for my counsel satisfied them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 23, 'They longed for me to speak as they longed for rain. They waited eagerly, for my words were as refreshing as the spring rain.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 24, 'When they were discouraged, I smiled at them. My look of approval was precious to them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 29, 25, 'I told them what they should do and presided over them as their chief. I lived as a king among his troops and as one who comforts those who mourn.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 1, '"But now I am mocked by those who are younger than I, by young men whose fathers are not worthy to run with my sheepdogs.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 2, 'A lot of good they are to me--those worn-out wretches!', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 3, 'They are gaunt with hunger and flee to the deserts and the wastelands, desolate and gloomy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 4, 'They eat coarse leaves, and they burn the roots of shrubs for heat.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 5, 'They are driven from civilization, and people shout after them as if they were thieves.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 6, 'So now they live in frightening ravines and in caves and among the rocks.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 7, 'They sound like animals as they howl among the bushes; they huddle together for shelter beneath the nettles.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 8, 'They are nameless fools, outcasts of civilization.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 9, '"And now their sons mock me with their vulgar song! They taunt me!', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 10, 'They despise me and won''t come near me, except to spit in my face.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 11, 'For God has cut the cords of my tent. He has humbled me, so they have thrown off all restraint.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 12, 'These outcasts oppose me to my face. They send me sprawling; they lay traps in my path.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 13, 'They block my road and do everything they can to hasten my calamity, knowing full well that I have no one to help me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 14, 'They come at me from all directions. They rush upon me when I am down.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 15, 'I live in terror now. They hold me in contempt, and my prosperity has vanished as a cloud before a strong wind.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 16, '"And now my heart is broken. Depression haunts my days.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 17, 'My weary nights are filled with pain as though something were relentlessly gnawing at my bones.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 18, 'With a strong hand, God grabs my garment. He grips me by the collar of my tunic.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 19, 'He has thrown me into the mud. I have become as dust and ashes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 20, '"I cry to you, O God, but you don''t answer me. I stand before you, and you don''t bother to look.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 21, 'You have become cruel toward me. You persecute me with your great power.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 22, 'You throw me into the whirlwind and destroy me in the storm.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 23, 'And I know that you are sending me to my death--the destination of all who live.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 24, '"Surely no one would turn against the needy when they cry for help.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 25, 'Did I not weep for those in trouble? Was I not deeply grieved for the needy?', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 26, 'So I looked for good, but evil came instead. I waited for the light, but darkness fell.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 27, 'My heart is troubled and restless. Days of affliction have come upon me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 28, 'I walk in gloom, without sunlight. I stand in the public square and cry for help.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 29, 'But instead, I am considered a brother to jackals and a companion to ostriches.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 30, 'My skin has turned dark, and my bones burn with fever.', 'NLT'),
(22, 30, 31, 'My harp plays sad music, and my flute accompanies those who weep.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 1, '"I made a covenant with my eyes not to look with lust upon a young woman.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 2, 'What has God above chosen for us? What is our inheritance from the Almighty on high?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 3, 'It is calamity for the wicked, misfortune for those who do evil.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 4, 'He sees everything I do and every step I take.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 5, '"Have I lied to anyone or deceived anyone?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 6, 'Let God judge me on the scales of justice, for he knows my integrity.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 7, 'If I have strayed from his pathway, or if my heart has lusted for what my eyes have seen, or if I am guilty of any other sin,', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 8, 'then let someone else harvest the crops I have planted, and let all that I have planted be uprooted.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 9, '"If my heart has been seduced by a woman, or if I have lusted for my neighbor''s wife,', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 10, 'then may my wife belong to another man; may other men sleep with her.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 11, 'For lust is a shameful sin, a crime that should be punished.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 12, 'It is a devastating fire that destroys to hell. It would wipe out everything I own.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 13, '"If I have been unfair to my male or female servants, if I have refused to hear their complaints,', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 14, 'how could I face God? What could I say when he questioned me about it?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 15, 'For God created both me and my servants. He created us both.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 16, '"Have I refused to help the poor, or crushed the hopes of widows who looked to me for help?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 17, 'Have I been stingy with my food and refused to share it with hungry orphans?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 18, 'No, from childhood I have cared for orphans, and all my life I have cared for widows.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 19, 'Whenever I saw someone who was homeless and without clothes,', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 20, 'did they not praise me for providing wool clothing to keep them warm?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 21, 'If my arm has abused an orphan because I thought I could get away with it,', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 22, 'then let my shoulder be wrenched out of place! Let my arm be torn from its socket!', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 23, 'That would be better than facing the judgment sent by God. For if the majesty of God opposes me, what hope is there?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 24, '"Have I put my trust in money or felt secure because of my gold?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 25, 'Does my happiness depend on my wealth and all that I own?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 26, 'Have I looked at the sun shining in the skies, or the moon walking down its silver pathway,', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 27, 'and been secretly enticed in my heart to worship them?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 28, 'If so, I should be punished by the judges, for it would mean I had denied the God of heaven.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 29, '"Have I ever rejoiced when my enemies came to ruin or become excited when harm came their way?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 30, 'No, I have never cursed anyone or asked for revenge.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 31, 'My servants have never let others go hungry.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 32, 'I have never turned away a stranger but have opened my doors to everyone.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 33, 'Have I tried to hide my sins as people normally do, hiding my guilt in a closet?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 34, 'Have I feared the crowd and its contempt, so that I refused to acknowledge my sin and would not go outside?', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 35, '"If only I had someone who would listen to me and try to see my side! Look, I will sign my name to my defense. Let the Almighty show me that I am wrong. Let my accuser write out the charges against me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 36, 'I would face the accusation proudly. I would treasure it like a crown.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 37, 'For I would tell him exactly what I have done. I would come before him like a prince.', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 38, '"If my land accuses me and all its furrows weep together,', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 39, 'or if I have stolen its crops or murdered its owners,', 'NLT'),
(22, 31, 40, 'then let thistles grow on that land instead of wheat and weeds instead of barley." Job''s words are ended.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 1, 'Job''s three friends refused to reply further to him because he kept insisting on his innocence.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 2, 'Then Elihu son of Barakel the Buzite, of the clan of Ram, became angry. He was angry because Job refused to admit that he had sinned and that God was right in punishing him.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 3, 'He was also angry with Job''s three friends because they had condemned God by their inability to answer Job''s arguments.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 4, 'Elihu had waited for the others to speak because they were older than he.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 5, 'But when he saw that they had no further reply, he spoke out angrily.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 6, 'Elihu son of Barakel the Buzite said, "I am young and you are old, so I held back and did not dare to tell you what I think.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 7, 'I thought, `Those who are older should speak, for wisdom comes with age.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 8, 'Surely it is God''s Spirit within people, the breath of the Almighty within them, that makes them intelligent.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 9, 'But sometimes the elders are not wise. Sometimes the aged do not understand justice.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 10, 'So listen to me and let me express my opinion.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 11, '"I have waited all this time, listening very carefully to your arguments, listening to you grope for words.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 12, 'I have listened, but not one of you has refuted Job or answered his arguments.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 13, 'And don''t tell me, `He is too wise for us. Only God can convince him.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 14, 'If Job had been arguing with me, I would not answer with that kind of logic!', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 15, 'You sit there baffled, with no further response.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 16, 'Should I continue to wait, now that you are silent? Must I also remain silent?', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 17, 'No, I will say my piece. I will speak my mind. I surely will.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 18, 'For I am pent up and full of words, and the spirit within me urges me on.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 19, 'I am like a wine cask without a vent. My words are ready to burst out!', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 20, 'I must speak to find relief, so let me give my answers.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 21, 'I won''t play favorites or try to flatter anyone.', 'NLT'),
(22, 32, 22, 'And if I tried, my Creator would soon do away with me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 1, '"Listen, Job, to what I have to say.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 2, 'Now that I have begun to speak, let me continue.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 3, 'I speak with all sincerity; I speak the truth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 4, 'For the Spirit of God has made me, and the breath of the Almighty gives me life.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 5, 'Answer me, if you can; make your case and take your stand.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 6, '"Look, you and I are the same before God. I, too, was formed from clay.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 7, 'So you don''t need to be afraid of me. I am not some great person to make you nervous and afraid.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 8, '"You have said it in my hearing. I have heard your very words.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 9, 'You said, `I am pure; I am innocent; I have not sinned.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 10, 'God is picking a quarrel with me, and he considers me to be his enemy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 11, 'He puts my feet in the stocks and watches every move I make.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 12, '"In this you are not right, and I will show you why. As you yourself have said, `God is greater than any person.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 13, 'So why are you bringing a charge against him? You say, `He does not respond to people''s complaints.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 14, 'But God speaks again and again, though people do not recognize it.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 15, 'He speaks in dreams, in visions of the night when deep sleep falls on people as they lie in bed.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 16, 'He whispers in their ear and terrifies them with his warning.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 17, 'He causes them to change their minds; he keeps them from pride.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 18, 'He keeps them from the grave, from crossing over the river of death.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 19, 'Or God disciplines people with sickness and pain, with ceaseless aching in their bones.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 20, 'They lose their appetite and do not care for even the most delicious food.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 21, 'They waste away to skin and bones.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 22, 'They are at death''s door; the angels of death wait for them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 23, '"But if a special messenger from heaven is there to intercede for a person, to declare that he is upright,', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 24, 'God will be gracious and say, `Set him free. Do not make him die, for I have found a ransom for his life.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 25, 'Then his body will become as healthy as a child''s, firm and youthful again.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 26, 'When he prays to God, he will be accepted. And God will receive him with joy and restore him to good standing.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 27, 'He will declare to his friends, `I sinned, but it was not worth it.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 28, 'God rescued me from the grave, and now my life is filled with light.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 29, '"Yes, God often does these things for people.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 30, 'He rescues them from the grave so they may live in the light of the living.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 31, 'Mark this well, Job. Listen to me, and let me say more.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 32, 'But if you have anything to say, go ahead. I want to hear it, for I am anxious to see you justified.', 'NLT'),
(22, 33, 33, 'But if not, then listen to me. Keep silent and I will teach you wisdom!"', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 1, 'Then Elihu said:', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 2, '"Listen to me, you wise men. Pay attention, you who have knowledge.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 3, '`Just as the mouth tastes good food, the ear tests the words it hears.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 4, 'So let us discern for ourselves what is right; let us learn together what is good.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 5, 'For Job has said, `I am innocent, but God has taken away my rights.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 6, 'I am innocent, but they call me a liar. My suffering is incurable, even though I have not sinned.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 7, '"Has there ever been a man as arrogant as Job, with his thirst for irreverent talk?', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 8, 'He seeks the companionship of evil people. He spends his time with wicked men.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 9, 'He has even said, `Why waste time trying to please God?''', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 10, '"Listen to me, you who have understanding. Everyone knows that God doesn''t sin! The Almighty can do no wrong.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 11, 'He repays people according to their deeds. He treats people according to their ways.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 12, 'There is no truer statement than this: God will not do wrong. The Almighty cannot twist justice.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 13, 'Who put the world in his care? Who has set the whole world in place?', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 14, 'If God were to take back his spirit and withdraw his breath,', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 15, 'all life would cease, and humanity would turn again to dust.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 16, '"Listen now and try to understand.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 17, 'Could God govern if he hated justice? Are you going to condemn the almighty Judge?', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 18, 'For he says to kings and nobles, `You are wicked and unjust.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 19, 'He doesn''t care how great a person may be, and he doesn''t pay any more attention to the rich than to the poor. He made them all.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 20, 'In a moment they die. At midnight they all pass away; the mighty are removed without human hand.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 21, '"For God carefully watches the way people live; he sees everything they do.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 22, 'No darkness is thick enough to hide the wicked from his eyes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 23, 'For it is not up to mortals to decide when to come before God in judgment.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 24, 'He brings the mighty to ruin without asking anyone, and he sets up others in their places.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 25, 'He watches what they do, and in the night he overturns them, destroying them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 26, 'He openly strikes them down for their wickedness.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 27, 'For they turned aside from following him. They have no respect for any of his ways.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 28, 'So they cause the poor to cry out, catching God''s attention. Yes, he hears the cries of the needy.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 29, 'When he is quiet, who can make trouble? But when he hides his face, who can find him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 30, 'He prevents the godless from ruling so they cannot be a snare to the people.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 31, '"Why don''t people say to God, `I have sinned, but I will sin no more''?', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 32, 'Or `I don''t know what evil I have done; tell me, and I will stop at once''?', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 33, '"Must God tailor his justice to your demands? But you have rejected him! The choice is yours, not mine. Go ahead, share your wisdom with us.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 34, 'After all, bright people will tell me, and wise people will hear me say,', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 35, '`Job speaks without knowledge; his words lack insight.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 36, 'Job, you deserve the maximum penalty for the wicked way you have talked.', 'NLT'),
(22, 34, 37, 'For now you have added rebellion and blasphemy against God to your other sins."', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 1, 'Then Elihu said:', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 2, '"Do you think it is right for you to claim, `I am righteous before God''?', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 3, 'Yet you also ask, `What''s the use of living a righteous life? How will it benefit me?''', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 4, '"I will answer you and all your friends, too.', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 5, 'Look up into the sky and see the clouds high above you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 6, 'If you sin, what do you accomplish against him? Even if you sin again and again, what effect will it have on him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 7, 'If you are good, is this some great gift to him? What could you possibly give him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 8, 'No, your sins affect only people like yourself, and your good deeds affect only other people.', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 9, '"The oppressed cry out beneath the wrongs that are done to them. They groan beneath the power of the mighty.', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 10, 'Yet they don''t ask, `Where is God my Creator, the one who gives songs in the night?', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 11, 'Where is the one who makes us wiser than the animals and birds?''', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 12, '"And if they do cry out and God does not answer, it is because of their pride.', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 13, 'But it is wrong to say God doesn''t listen, to say the Almighty isn''t concerned.', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 14, 'And it is even more false to say he doesn''t see what is going on. He will bring about justice if you will only wait.', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 15, 'But do you cry out against him because he does not respond in anger?', 'NLT'),
(22, 35, 16, 'Job, you have protested in vain. You have spoken like a fool."', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 1, 'Elihu continued speaking:', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 2, '"Let me go on, and I will show you the truth of what I am saying. For I have not finished defending God!', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 3, 'I will give you many illustrations of the righteousness of my Creator.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 4, 'I am telling you the honest truth, for I am a man of well-rounded knowledge.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 5, '"God is mighty, yet he does not despise anyone! He is mighty in both power and understanding.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 6, 'He does not let the wicked live but gives justice to the afflicted.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 7, 'His eyes never leave the innocent, but he establishes and exalts them with kings forever.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 8, 'If troubles come upon them and they are enslaved and afflicted,', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 9, 'he takes the trouble to show them the reason. He shows them their sins, for they have behaved proudly.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 10, 'He gets their attention and says they must turn away from evil.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 11, '"If they listen and obey God, then they will be blessed with prosperity throughout their lives. All their years will be pleasant.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 12, 'But if they refuse to listen to him, they will perish in battle and die from lack of understanding.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 13, 'For the godless are full of resentment. Even when he punishes them, they refuse to cry out to him for help.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 14, 'They die young after wasting their lives in immoral living.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 15, 'But by means of their suffering, he rescues those who suffer. For he gets their attention through adversity.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 16, '"God has led you away from danger, giving you freedom. You have prospered in a wide and pleasant valley.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 17, 'But you are too obsessed with judgment on the godless. Don''t worry, justice will be upheld.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 18, 'But watch out, or you may be seduced with wealth. Don''t let yourself be bribed into sin.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 19, 'Could all your wealth and mighty efforts keep you from distress?', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 20, 'Do not long for the cover of night, for that is when people will be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 21, 'Be on guard! Turn back from evil, for it was to prevent you from getting into a life of evil that God sent this suffering.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 22, '"Look, God is all-powerful. Who is a teacher like him?', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 23, 'No one can tell him what to do. No one can say to him, `You have done wrong.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 24, 'Instead, glorify his mighty works, singing songs of praise.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 25, 'Everyone has seen these things, but only from a distance.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 26, '"Look, God is exalted beyond what we can understand. His years are without number.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 27, 'He draws up the water vapor and then distills it into rain.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 28, 'The rain pours down from the clouds, and everyone benefits from it.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 29, 'Can anyone really understand the spreading of the clouds and the thunder that rolls forth from heaven?', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 30, 'See how he spreads the lightning around him and how it lights up the depths of the sea.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 31, 'By his mighty acts he governs the people, giving them food in abundance.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 32, 'He fills his hands with lightning bolts. He hurls each at its target.', 'NLT'),
(22, 36, 33, 'The thunder announces his presence; the storm announces his indignant anger.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 1, '"My heart pounds as I think of this. It leaps within me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 2, 'Listen carefully to the thunder of God''s voice as it rolls from his mouth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 3, 'It rolls across the heavens, and his lightning flashes out in every direction.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 4, 'Then comes the roaring of the thunder--the tremendous voice of his majesty. He does not restrain the thunder when he speaks.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 5, 'God''s voice is glorious in the thunder. We cannot comprehend the greatness of his power.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 6, '"He directs the snow to fall on the earth and tells the rain to pour down.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 7, 'Everyone stops working at such a time so they can recognize his power.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 8, 'The wild animals hide in the rocks or in their dens.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 9, 'The stormy wind comes from its chamber, and the driving winds bring the cold.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 10, 'God''s breath sends the ice, freezing wide expanses of water.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 11, 'He loads the clouds with moisture, and they flash with his lightning.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 12, 'The clouds turn around and around under his direction. They do whatever he commands throughout the earth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 13, 'He causes things to happen on earth, either as a punishment or as a sign of his unfailing love.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 14, '"Listen, Job; stop and consider the wonderful miracles of God!', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 15, 'Do you know how God controls the storm and causes the lightning to flash forth from his clouds?', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 16, 'Do you understand how he balances the clouds with wonderful perfection and skill?', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 17, 'When you are sweltering in your clothes and the south wind dies down and everything is still,', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 18, 'he makes the skies reflect the heat like a giant mirror. Can you do that?', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 19, '"You think you know so much, so teach the rest of us what to say to God. We are too ignorant to make our own arguments.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 20, 'Should God be told that I want to speak? Can we speak when we are confused?', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 21, 'We cannot look at the sun, for it shines brightly in the sky when the wind clears away the clouds.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 22, 'Golden splendor comes from the mountain of God. He is clothed in dazzling splendor.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 23, 'We cannot imagine the power of the Almighty, yet he is so just and merciful that he does not oppress us.', 'NLT'),
(22, 37, 24, 'No wonder people everywhere fear him. People who are truly wise show him reverence."', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 1, 'Then the LORD answered Job from the whirlwind:', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 2, '"Who is this that questions my wisdom with such ignorant words?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 3, 'Brace yourself, because I have some questions for you, and you must answer them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 4, '"Where were you when I laid the foundations of the earth? Tell me, if you know so much.', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 5, 'Do you know how its dimensions were determined and who did the surveying?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 6, 'What supports its foundations, and who laid its cornerstone', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 7, 'as the morning stars sang together and all the angels shouted for joy?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 8, '"Who defined the boundaries of the sea as it burst from the womb,', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 9, 'and as I clothed it with clouds and thick darkness?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 10, 'For I locked it behind barred gates, limiting its shores.', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 11, 'I said, `Thus far and no farther will you come. Here your proud waves must stop!''', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 12, '"Have you ever commanded the morning to appear and caused the dawn to rise in the east?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 13, 'Have you ever told the daylight to spread to the ends of the earth, to bring an end to the night''s wickedness?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 14, 'For the features of the earth take shape as the light approaches, and the dawn is robed in red.', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 15, 'The light disturbs the haunts of the wicked, and it stops the arm that is raised in violence.', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 16, '"Have you explored the springs from which the seas come? Have you walked about and explored their depths?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 17, 'Do you know where the gates of death are located? Have you seen the gates of utter gloom?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 18, 'Do you realize the extent of the earth? Tell me about it if you know!', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 19, '"Where does the light come from, and where does the darkness go?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 20, 'Can you take it to its home? Do you know how to get there?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 21, 'But of course you know all this! For you were born before it was all created, and you are so very experienced!', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 22, '"Have you visited the treasuries of the snow? Have you seen where the hail is made and stored?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 23, 'I have reserved it for the time of trouble, for the day of battle and war.', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 24, 'Where is the path to the origin of light? Where is the home of the east wind?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 25, '"Who created a channel for the torrents of rain? Who laid out the path for the lightning?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 26, 'Who makes the rain fall on barren land, in a desert where no one lives?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 27, 'Who sends the rain that satisfies the parched ground and makes the tender grass spring up?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 28, '"Does the rain have a father? Where does dew come from?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 29, 'Who is the mother of the ice? Who gives birth to the frost from the heavens?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 30, 'For the water turns to ice as hard as rock, and the surface of the water freezes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 31, '"Can you hold back the movements of the stars? Are you able to restrain the Pleiades or Orion?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 32, 'Can you ensure the proper sequence of the seasons or guide the constellation of the Bear with her cubs across the heavens?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 33, 'Do you know the laws of the universe and how God rules the earth?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 34, '"Can you shout to the clouds and make it rain?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 35, 'Can you make lightning appear and cause it to strike as you direct it?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 36, 'Who gives intuition and instinct?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 37, 'Who is wise enough to count all the clouds? Who can tilt the water jars of heaven,', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 38, 'turning the dry dust to clumps of mud?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 39, '"Can you stalk prey for a lioness and satisfy the young lions'' appetites', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 40, 'as they lie in their dens or crouch in the thicket?', 'NLT'),
(22, 38, 41, 'Who provides food for the ravens when their young cry out to God as they wander about in hunger?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 1, '"Do you know when the mountain goats give birth? Have you watched as the wild deer are born?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 2, 'Do you know how many months they carry their young? Are you aware of the time of their delivery?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 3, 'They crouch down to give birth to their young and deliver their offspring.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 4, 'Their young grow up in the open fields, then leave their parents and never return.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 5, '"Who makes the wild donkey wild?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 6, 'I have placed it in the wilderness; its home is the wasteland.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 7, 'It hates the noise of the city, and it has no driver to shout at it.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 8, 'The mountains are its pastureland, where it searches for every blade of grass.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 9, '"Will the wild ox consent to being tamed? Will it stay in your stall?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 10, 'Can you hitch a wild ox to a plow? Will it plow a field for you?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 11, 'Since it is so strong, can you trust it? Can you go away and trust the ox to do your work?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 12, 'Can you rely on it to return, bringing your grain to the threshing floor?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 13, '"The ostrich flaps her wings grandly, but they are no match for the feathers of the stork.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 14, 'She lays her eggs on top of the earth, letting them be warmed in the dust.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 15, 'She doesn''t worry that a foot might crush them or that wild animals might destroy them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 16, 'She is harsh toward her young, as if they were not her own. She is unconcerned though they die,', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 17, 'for God has deprived her of wisdom. He has given her no understanding.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 18, 'But whenever she jumps up to run, she passes the swiftest horse with its rider.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 19, '"Have you given the horse its strength or clothed its neck with a flowing mane?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 20, 'Did you give it the ability to leap forward like a locust? Its majestic snorting is something to hear!', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 21, 'It paws the earth and rejoices in its strength. When it charges to war,', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 22, 'it is unafraid. It does not run from the sword.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 23, 'The arrows rattle against it, and the spear and javelin flash.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 24, 'Fiercely it paws the ground and rushes forward into battle when the trumpet blows.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 25, 'It snorts at the sound of the bugle. It senses the battle even at a distance. It quivers at the noise of battle and the shout of the captain''s commands.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 26, '"Are you the one who makes the hawk soar and spread its wings to the south?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 27, 'Is it at your command that the eagle rises to the heights to make its nest?', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 28, 'It lives on the cliffs, making its home on a distant, rocky crag.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 29, 'From there it hunts its prey, keeping watch with piercing eyes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 39, 30, 'Its nestlings gulp down blood, for it feeds on the carcass of the slaughtered."', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 1, 'Then the LORD said to Job,', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 2, '"Do you still want to argue with the Almighty? You are God''s critic, but do you have the answers?"', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 3, 'Then Job replied to the LORD,', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 4, '"I am nothing--how could I ever find the answers? I will put my hand over my mouth in silence.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 5, 'I have said too much already. I have nothing more to say."', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 6, 'Then the LORD answered Job from the whirlwind:', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 7, '"Brace yourself, because I have some questions for you, and you must answer them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 8, 'Are you going to discredit my justice and condemn me so you can say you are right?', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 9, 'Are you as strong as God, and can you thunder with a voice like his?', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 10, 'All right then, put on your robes of state, your majesty and splendor.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 11, 'Give vent to your anger. Let it overflow against the proud.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 12, 'Humiliate the proud with a glance; walk on the wicked where they stand.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 13, 'Bury them in the dust. Imprison them in the world of the dead.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 14, 'Then even I would praise you, for your own strength would save you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 15, '"Take a look at the mighty hippopotamus. I made it, just as I made you. It eats grass like an ox.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 16, 'See its powerful loins and the muscles of its belly.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 17, 'Its tail is as straight as a cedar. The sinews of its thighs are tightly knit together.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 18, 'Its bones are tubes of bronze. Its limbs are bars of iron.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 19, 'It is a prime example of God''s amazing handiwork. Only its Creator can threaten it.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 20, 'The mountains offer it their best food, where all the wild animals play.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 21, 'It lies down under the lotus plants, hidden by the reeds.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 22, 'The lotus plants give it shade among the willows beside the stream.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 23, 'It is not disturbed by raging rivers, not even when the swelling Jordan rushes down upon it.', 'NLT'),
(22, 40, 24, 'No one can catch it off guard or put a ring in its nose and lead it away.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 1, '"Can you catch a crocodile with a hook or put a noose around its jaw?', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 2, 'Can you tie it with a rope through the nose or pierce its jaw with a spike?', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 3, 'Will it beg you for mercy or implore you for pity?', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 4, 'Will it agree to work for you? Can you make it be your slave for life?', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 5, 'Can you make it a pet like a bird, or give it to your little girls to play with?', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 6, 'Will merchants try to buy it? Will they sell it in their shops?', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 7, 'Will its hide be hurt by darts, or its head by a harpoon?', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 8, 'If you lay a hand on it, you will never forget the battle that follows, and you will never try it again!', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 9, '"No, it is useless to try to capture it. The hunter who attempts it will be thrown down.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 10, 'And since no one dares to disturb the crocodile, who would dare to stand up to me?', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 11, 'Who will confront me and remain safe? Everything under heaven is mine.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 12, '"I want to emphasize the tremendous strength in the crocodile''s limbs and throughout its enormous frame.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 13, 'Who can strip off its hide, and who can penetrate its double layer of armor?', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 14, 'Who could pry open its jaws? For its teeth are terrible!', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 15, 'The overlapping scales on its back make a shield.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 16, 'They are close together so no air can get between them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 17, 'They lock together so nothing can penetrate them.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 18, '"When it sneezes, it flashes light! Its eyes are like the red of dawn.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 19, 'Fire and sparks leap from its mouth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 20, 'Smoke streams from its nostrils like steam from a boiling pot on a fire of dry rushes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 21, 'Yes, its breath would kindle coals, for flames shoot from its mouth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 22, '"The tremendous strength in its neck strikes terror wherever it goes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 23, 'Its flesh is hard and firm, not soft and fat.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 24, 'Its heart is as hard as rock, as hard as a millstone.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 25, 'When it rises, the mighty are afraid, gripped by terror.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 26, 'No sword can stop it, nor spear nor dart nor pointed shaft.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 27, 'To the crocodile, iron is nothing but straw, and bronze is rotten wood.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 28, 'Arrows cannot make it flee. Stones shot from a sling are as ineffective as straw.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 29, 'Clubs do no good, and it laughs at the swish of the javelins.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 30, 'Its belly is covered with scales as sharp as glass. They tear up the ground as it drags through the mud.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 31, '"The crocodile makes the water boil with its commotion. It churns the depths.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 32, 'The water glistens in its wake. One would think the sea had turned white.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 33, 'There is nothing else so fearless anywhere on earth.', 'NLT'),
(22, 41, 34, 'Of all the creatures, it is the proudest. It is the king of beasts."', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 1, 'Then Job replied to the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 2, '"I know that you can do anything, and no one can stop you.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 3, 'You ask, `Who is this that questions my wisdom with such ignorance?'' It is I. And I was talking about things I did not understand, things far too wonderful for me.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 4, '"You said, `Listen and I will speak! I have some questions for you, and you must answer them.''', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 5, '"I had heard about you before, but now I have seen you with my own eyes.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 6, 'I take back everything I said, and I sit in dust and ashes to show my repentance."', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 7, 'After the LORD had finished speaking to Job, he said to Eliphaz the Temanite: "I am angry with you and with your two friends, for you have not been right in what you said about me, as my servant Job was.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 8, 'Now take seven young bulls and seven rams and go to my servant Job and offer a burnt offering for yourselves. My servant Job will pray for you, and I will accept his prayer on your behalf. I will not treat you as you deserve, for you have not been right in what you said about me, as my servant Job was."', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 9, 'So Eliphaz the Temanite, Bildad the Shuhite, and Zophar the Naamathite did as the LORD commanded them, and the LORD accepted Job''s prayer.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 10, 'When Job prayed for his friends, the LORD restored his fortunes. In fact, the LORD gave him twice as much as before!', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 11, 'Then all his brothers, sisters, and former friends came and feasted with him in his home. And they consoled him and comforted him because of all the trials the LORD had brought against him. And each of them brought him a gift of money and a gold ring.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 12, 'So the LORD blessed Job in the second half of his life even more than in the beginning. For now he had fourteen thousand sheep, six thousand camels, one thousand teams of oxen, and one thousand female donkeys.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 13, 'He also gave Job seven more sons and three more daughters.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 14, 'He named his first daughter Jemimah, the second Keziah, and the third Keren-happuch.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 15, 'In all the land there were no other women as lovely as the daughters of Job. And their father put them into his will along with their brothers.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 16, 'Job lived 140 years after that, living to see four generations of his children and grandchildren.', 'NLT'),
(22, 42, 17, 'Then he died, an old man who had lived a long, good life.', 'NLT'),
(23, 1, 1, 'Oh, the joys of those who do not follow the advice of the wicked, or stand around with sinners, or join in with scoffers.', 'NLT'),
(23, 1, 2, 'But they delight in doing everything the LORD wants; day and night they think about his law.', 'NLT'),
(23, 1, 3, 'They are like trees planted along the riverbank, bearing fruit each season without fail. Their leaves never wither, and in all they do, they prosper.', 'NLT'),
(23, 1, 4, 'But this is not true of the wicked. They are like worthless chaff, scattered by the wind.', 'NLT'),
(23, 1, 5, 'They will be condemned at the time of judgment. Sinners will have no place among the godly.', 'NLT'),
(23, 1, 6, 'For the LORD watches over the path of the godly, but the path of the wicked leads to destruction.', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 1, 'Why do the nations rage? Why do the people waste their time with futile plans?', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 2, 'The kings of the earth prepare for battle; the rulers plot together against the LORD and against his anointed one.', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 3, '"Let us break their chains," they cry, "and free ourselves from this slavery."', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 4, 'But the one who rules in heaven laughs. The Lord scoffs at them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 5, 'Then in anger he rebukes them, terrifying them with his fierce fury.', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 6, 'For the LORD declares, "I have placed my chosen king on the throne in Jerusalem, my holy city. "', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 7, 'The king proclaims the LORD''s decree: "The LORD said to me, `You are my son. Today I have become your Father.', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 8, 'Only ask, and I will give you the nations as your inheritance, the ends of the earth as your possession.', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 9, 'You will break them with an iron rod and smash them like clay pots.''"', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 10, 'Now then, you kings, act wisely! Be warned, you rulers of the earth!', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 11, 'Serve the LORD with reverent fear, and rejoice with trembling.', 'NLT'),
(23, 2, 12, 'Submit to God''s royal son, or he will become angry, and you will be destroyed in the midst of your pursuits--for his anger can flare up in an instant. But what joy for all who find protection in him!', 'NLT'),
(23, 3, 1, 'O LORD, I have so many enemies; so many are against me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 3, 2, 'So many are saying, "God will never rescue him!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 3, 3, 'But you, O LORD, are a shield around me, my glory, and the one who lifts my head high.', 'NLT'),
(23, 3, 4, 'I cried out to the LORD, and he answered me from his holy mountain.', 'NLT'),
(23, 3, 5, 'I lay down and slept. I woke up in safety, for the LORD was watching over me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 3, 6, 'I am not afraid of ten thousand enemies who surround me on every side.', 'NLT'),
(23, 3, 7, 'Arise, O LORD! Rescue me, my God! Slap all my enemies in the face! Shatter the teeth of the wicked!', 'NLT'),
(23, 3, 8, 'Victory comes from you, O LORD. May your blessings rest on your people.', 'NLT'),
(23, 4, 1, 'Answer me when I call, O God who declares me innocent. Take away my distress. Have mercy on me and hear my prayer.', 'NLT'),
(23, 4, 2, 'How long will you people ruin my reputation? How long will you make these groundless accusations? How long will you pursue lies?', 'NLT'),
(23, 4, 3, 'You can be sure of this: The LORD has set apart the godly for himself. The LORD will answer when I call to him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 4, 4, 'Don''t sin by letting anger gain control over you. Think about it overnight and remain silent.', 'NLT'),
(23, 4, 5, 'Offer proper sacrifices, and trust in the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 4, 6, 'Many people say, "Who will show us better times?" Let the smile of your face shine on us, LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 4, 7, 'You have given me greater joy than those who have abundant harvests of grain and wine.', 'NLT'),
(23, 4, 8, 'I will lie down in peace and sleep, for you alone, O LORD, will keep me safe.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 1, 'O LORD, hear me as I pray; pay attention to my groaning.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 2, 'Listen to my cry for help, my King and my God, for I will never pray to anyone but you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 3, 'Listen to my voice in the morning, LORD. Each morning I bring my requests to you and wait expectantly.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 4, 'O God, you take no pleasure in wickedness; you cannot tolerate the slightest sin.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 5, 'Therefore, the proud will not be allowed to stand in your presence, for you hate all who do evil.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 6, 'You will destroy those who tell lies. The LORD detests murderers and deceivers.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 7, 'Because of your unfailing love, I can enter your house; with deepest awe I will worship at your Temple.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 8, 'Lead me in the right path, O LORD, or my enemies will conquer me. Tell me clearly what to do, and show me which way to turn.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 9, 'My enemies cannot speak one truthful word. Their deepest desire is to destroy others. Their talk is foul, like the stench from an open grave. Their speech is filled with flattery.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 10, 'O God, declare them guilty. Let them be caught in their own traps. Drive them away because of their many sins, for they rebel against you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 11, 'But let all who take refuge in you rejoice; let them sing joyful praises forever. Protect them, so all who love your name may be filled with joy.', 'NLT'),
(23, 5, 12, 'For you bless the godly, O LORD, surrounding them with your shield of love.', 'NLT'),
(23, 6, 1, 'O LORD, do not rebuke me in your anger or discipline me in your rage.', 'NLT'),
(23, 6, 2, 'Have compassion on me, LORD, for I am weak. Heal me, LORD, for my body is in agony.', 'NLT'),
(23, 6, 3, 'I am sick at heart. How long, O LORD, until you restore me?', 'NLT'),
(23, 6, 4, 'Return, O LORD, and rescue me. Save me because of your unfailing love.', 'NLT'),
(23, 6, 5, 'For in death, who remembers you? Who can praise you from the grave?', 'NLT'),
(23, 6, 6, 'I am worn out from sobbing. Every night tears drench my bed; my pillow is wet from weeping.', 'NLT'),
(23, 6, 7, 'My vision is blurred by grief; my eyes are worn out because of all my enemies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 6, 8, 'Go away, all you who do evil, for the LORD has heard my crying.', 'NLT'),
(23, 6, 9, 'The LORD has heard my plea; the LORD will answer my prayer.', 'NLT'),
(23, 6, 10, 'May all my enemies be disgraced and terrified. May they suddenly turn back in shame.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 1, 'I come to you for protection, O LORD my God. Save me from my persecutors--rescue me!', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 2, 'If you don''t, they will maul me like a lion, tearing me to pieces with no one to rescue me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 3, 'O LORD my God, if I have done wrong or am guilty of injustice,', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 4, 'if I have betrayed a friend or plundered my enemy without cause,', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 5, 'then let my enemies capture me. Let them trample me into the ground. Let my honor be left in the dust.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 6, 'Arise, O LORD, in anger! Stand up against the fury of my enemies! Wake up, my God, and bring justice!', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 7, 'Gather the nations before you. Sit on your throne high above them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 8, 'The LORD passes judgment on the nations. Declare me righteous, O LORD, for I am innocent, O Most High!', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 9, 'End the wickedness of the ungodly, but help all those who obey you. For you look deep within the mind and heart, O righteous God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 10, 'God is my shield, saving those whose hearts are true and right.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 11, 'God is a judge who is perfectly fair. He is angry with the wicked every day.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 12, 'If a person does not repent, God will sharpen his sword; he will bend and string his bow.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 13, 'He will prepare his deadly weapons and ignite his flaming arrows.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 14, 'The wicked conceive evil; they are pregnant with trouble and give birth to lies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 15, 'They dig a pit to trap others and then fall into it themselves.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 16, 'They make trouble, but it backfires on them. They plan violence for others, but it falls on their own heads.', 'NLT'),
(23, 7, 17, 'I will thank the LORD because he is just; I will sing praise to the name of the LORD Most High.', 'NLT'),
(23, 8, 1, 'O LORD, our Lord, the majesty of your name fills the earth! Your glory is higher than the heavens.', 'NLT'),
(23, 8, 2, 'You have taught children and nursing infants to give you praise. They silence your enemies who were seeking revenge.', 'NLT'),
(23, 8, 3, 'When I look at the night sky and see the work of your fingers--the moon and the stars you have set in place--', 'NLT'),
(23, 8, 4, 'what are mortals that you should think of us, mere humans that you should care for us?', 'NLT'),
(23, 8, 5, 'For you made us only a little lower than God, and you crowned us with glory and honor.', 'NLT'),
(23, 8, 6, 'You put us in charge of everything you made, giving us authority over all things--', 'NLT'),
(23, 8, 7, 'the sheep and the cattle and all the wild animals,', 'NLT'),
(23, 8, 8, 'the birds in the sky, the fish in the sea, and everything that swims the ocean currents.', 'NLT'),
(23, 8, 9, 'O LORD, our Lord, the majesty of your name fills the earth!', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 1, 'I will thank you, LORD, with all my heart; I will tell of all the marvelous things you have done.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 2, 'I will be filled with joy because of you. I will sing praises to your name, O Most High.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 3, 'My enemies turn away in retreat; they are overthrown and destroyed before you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 4, 'For you have judged in my favor; from your throne, you have judged with fairness.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 5, 'You have rebuked the nations and destroyed the wicked; you have wiped out their names forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 6, 'My enemies have met their doom; their cities are perpetual ruins. Even the memory of their uprooted cities is lost.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 7, 'But the LORD reigns forever, executing judgment from his throne.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 8, 'He will judge the world with justice and rule the nations with fairness.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 9, 'The LORD is a shelter for the oppressed, a refuge in times of trouble.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 10, 'Those who know your name trust in you, for you, O LORD, have never abandoned anyone who searches for you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 11, 'Sing praises to the LORD who reigns in Jerusalem. Tell the world about his unforgettable deeds.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 12, 'For he who avenges murder cares for the helpless. He does not ignore those who cry to him for help.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 13, 'LORD, have mercy on me. See how I suffer at the hands of those who hate me. Snatch me back from the jaws of death.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 14, 'Save me, so I can praise you publicly at Jerusalem''s gates, so I can rejoice that you have rescued me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 15, 'The nations have fallen into the pit they dug for others. They have been caught in their own trap.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 16, 'The LORD is known for his justice. The wicked have trapped themselves in their own snares.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 17, 'The wicked will go down to the grave. This is the fate of all the nations who ignore God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 18, 'For the needy will not be forgotten forever; the hopes of the poor will not always be crushed.', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 19, 'Arise, O LORD! Do not let mere mortals defy you! Let the nations be judged in your presence!', 'NLT'),
(23, 9, 20, 'Make them tremble in fear, O LORD. Let them know they are merely human.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 1, 'O LORD, why do you stand so far away? Why do you hide when I need you the most?', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 2, 'Proud and wicked people viciously oppress the poor. Let them be caught in the evil they plan for others.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 3, 'For they brag about their evil desires; they praise the greedy and curse the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 4, 'These wicked people are too proud to seek God. They seem to think that God is dead.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 5, 'Yet they succeed in everything they do. They do not see your punishment awaiting them. They pour scorn on all their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 6, 'They say to themselves, "Nothing bad will ever happen to us! We will be free of trouble forever!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 7, 'Their mouths are full of cursing, lies, and threats. Trouble and evil are on the tips of their tongues.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 8, 'They lurk in dark alleys, murdering the innocent who pass by. They are always searching for some helpless victim.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 9, 'Like lions they crouch silently, waiting to pounce on the helpless. Like hunters they capture their victims and drag them away in nets.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 10, 'The helpless are overwhelmed and collapse; they fall beneath the strength of the wicked.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 11, 'The wicked say to themselves, "God isn''t watching! He will never notice!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 12, 'Arise, O LORD! Punish the wicked, O God! Do not forget the helpless!', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 13, 'Why do the wicked get away with cursing God? How can they think, "God will never call us to account"?', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 14, 'But you do see the trouble and grief they cause. You take note of it and punish them. The helpless put their trust in you. You are the defender of orphans.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 15, 'Break the arms of these wicked, evil people! Go after them until the last one is destroyed!', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 16, 'The LORD is king forever and ever! Let those who worship other gods be swept from the land.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 17, 'LORD, you know the hopes of the helpless. Surely you will listen to their cries and comfort them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 10, 18, 'You will bring justice to the orphans and the oppressed, so people can no longer terrify them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 11, 1, 'I trust in the LORD for protection. So why do you say to me, "Fly to the mountains for safety!', 'NLT'),
(23, 11, 2, 'The wicked are stringing their bows and setting their arrows in the bowstrings. They shoot from the shadows at those who do right.', 'NLT'),
(23, 11, 3, 'The foundations of law and order have collapsed. What can the righteous do?"', 'NLT'),
(23, 11, 4, 'But the LORD is in his holy Temple; the LORD still rules from heaven. He watches everything closely, examining everyone on earth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 11, 5, 'The LORD examines both the righteous and the wicked. He hates everyone who loves violence.', 'NLT'),
(23, 11, 6, 'He rains down blazing coals on the wicked, punishing them with burning sulfur and scorching winds.', 'NLT'),
(23, 11, 7, 'For the LORD is righteous, and he loves justice. Those who do what is right will see his face.', 'NLT'),
(23, 12, 1, 'Help, O LORD, for the godly are fast disappearing! The faithful have vanished from the earth!', 'NLT'),
(23, 12, 2, 'Neighbors lie to each other, speaking with flattering lips and insincere hearts.', 'NLT'),
(23, 12, 3, 'May the LORD bring their flattery to an end and silence their proud tongues.', 'NLT'),
(23, 12, 4, 'They say, "We will lie to our hearts'' content. Our lips are our own--who can stop us?"', 'NLT'),
(23, 12, 5, 'The LORD replies, "I have seen violence done to the helpless, and I have heard the groans of the poor. Now I will rise up to rescue them, as they have longed for me to do."', 'NLT'),
(23, 12, 6, 'The LORD''s promises are pure, like silver refined in a furnace, purified seven times over.', 'NLT'),
(23, 12, 7, 'Therefore, LORD, we know you will protect the oppressed, preserving them forever from this lying generation,', 'NLT'),
(23, 12, 8, 'even though the wicked strut about, and evil is praised throughout the land.', 'NLT'),
(23, 13, 1, 'O LORD, how long will you forget me? Forever? How long will you look the other way?', 'NLT'),
(23, 13, 2, 'How long must I struggle with anguish in my soul, with sorrow in my heart every day? How long will my enemy have the upper hand?', 'NLT'),
(23, 13, 3, 'Turn and answer me, O LORD my God! Restore the light to my eyes, or I will die.', 'NLT'),
(23, 13, 4, 'Don''t let my enemies gloat, saying, "We have defeated him!" Don''t let them rejoice at my downfall.', 'NLT'),
(23, 13, 5, 'But I trust in your unfailing love. I will rejoice because you have rescued me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 13, 6, 'I will sing to the LORD because he has been so good to me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 14, 1, 'Only fools say in their hearts, "There is no God." They are corrupt, and their actions are evil; no one does good!', 'NLT'),
(23, 14, 2, 'The LORD looks down from heaven on the entire human race; he looks to see if there is even one with real understanding, one who seeks for God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 14, 3, 'But no, all have turned away from God; all have become corrupt. No one does good, not even one!', 'NLT'),
(23, 14, 4, 'Will those who do evil never learn? They eat up my people like bread; they wouldn''t think of praying to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 14, 5, 'Terror will grip them, for God is with those who obey him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 14, 6, 'The wicked frustrate the plans of the oppressed, but the LORD will protect his people.', 'NLT'),
(23, 14, 7, 'Oh, that salvation would come from Mount Zion to rescue Israel! For when the LORD restores his people, Jacob will shout with joy, and Israel will rejoice.', 'NLT'),
(23, 15, 1, 'Who may worship in your sanctuary, LORD? Who may enter your presence on your holy hill?', 'NLT'),
(23, 15, 2, 'Those who lead blameless lives and do what is right, speaking the truth from sincere hearts.', 'NLT'),
(23, 15, 3, 'Those who refuse to slander others or harm their neighbors or speak evil of their friends.', 'NLT'),
(23, 15, 4, 'Those who despise persistent sinners, and honor the faithful followers of the LORD and keep their promises even when it hurts.', 'NLT'),
(23, 15, 5, 'Those who do not charge interest on the money they lend, and who refuse to accept bribes to testify against the innocent. Such people will stand firm forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 1, 'Keep me safe, O God, for I have come to you for refuge.', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 2, 'I said to the LORD, "You are my Master! All the good things I have are from you."', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 3, 'The godly people in the land are my true heroes! I take pleasure in them!', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 4, 'Those who chase after other gods will be filled with sorrow. I will not take part in their sacrifices or even speak the names of their gods.', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 5, 'LORD, you alone are my inheritance, my cup of blessing. You guard all that is mine.', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 6, 'The land you have given me is a pleasant land. What a wonderful inheritance!', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 7, 'I will bless the LORD who guides me; even at night my heart instructs me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 8, 'I know the LORD is always with me. I will not be shaken, for he is right beside me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 9, 'No wonder my heart is filled with joy, and my mouth shouts his praises! My body rests in safety.', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 10, 'For you will not leave my soul among the dead or allow your godly one to rot in the grave.', 'NLT'),
(23, 16, 11, 'You will show me the way of life, granting me the joy of your presence and the pleasures of living with you forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 1, 'O LORD, hear my plea for justice. Listen to my cry for help. Pay attention to my prayer, for it comes from an honest heart.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 2, 'Declare me innocent, for you know those who do right.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 3, 'You have tested my thoughts and examined my heart in the night. You have scrutinized me and found nothing amiss, for I am determined not to sin in what I say.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 4, 'I have followed your commands, which have kept me from going along with cruel and evil people.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 5, 'My steps have stayed on your path; I have not wavered from following you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 6, 'I am praying to you because I know you will answer, O God. Bend down and listen as I pray.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 7, 'Show me your unfailing love in wonderful ways. You save with your strength those who seek refuge from their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 8, 'Guard me as the apple of your eye. Hide me in the shadow of your wings.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 9, 'Protect me from wicked people who attack me, from murderous enemies who surround me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 10, 'They are without pity. Listen to their boasting.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 11, 'They track me down, surround me, and throw me to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 12, 'They are like hungry lions, eager to tear me apart--like young lions in hiding, waiting for their chance.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 13, 'Arise, O LORD! Stand against them and bring them to their knees! Rescue me from the wicked with your sword!', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 14, 'Save me by your mighty hand, O LORD, from those whose only concern is earthly gain. May they have their punishment in full. May their children inherit more of the same, and may the judgment continue to their children''s children.', 'NLT'),
(23, 17, 15, 'But because I have done what is right, I will see you. When I awake, I will be fully satisfied, for I will see you face to face.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 1, 'I love you, LORD; you are my strength.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 2, 'The LORD is my rock, my fortress, and my savior; my God is my rock, in whom I find protection. He is my shield, the strength of my salvation, and my stronghold.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 3, 'I will call on the LORD, who is worthy of praise, for he saves me from my enemies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 4, 'The ropes of death surrounded me; the floods of destruction swept over me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 5, 'The grave wrapped its ropes around me; death itself stared me in the face.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 6, 'But in my distress I cried out to the LORD; yes, I prayed to my God for help. He heard me from his sanctuary; my cry reached his ears.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 7, 'Then the earth quaked and trembled; the foundations of the mountains shook; they quaked because of his anger.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 8, 'Smoke poured from his nostrils; fierce flames leaped from his mouth; glowing coals flamed forth from him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 9, 'He opened the heavens and came down; dark storm clouds were beneath his feet.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 10, 'Mounted on a mighty angel, he flew, soaring on the wings of the wind.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 11, 'He shrouded himself in darkness, veiling his approach with dense rain clouds.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 12, 'The brilliance of his presence broke through the clouds, raining down hail and burning coals.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 13, 'The LORD thundered from heaven; the Most High gave a mighty shout.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 14, 'He shot his arrows and scattered his enemies; his lightning flashed, and they were greatly confused.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 15, 'Then at your command, O LORD, at the blast of your breath, the bottom of the sea could be seen, and the foundations of the earth were laid bare.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 16, 'He reached down from heaven and rescued me; he drew me out of deep waters.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 17, 'He delivered me from my powerful enemies, from those who hated me and were too strong for me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 18, 'They attacked me at a moment when I was weakest, but the LORD upheld me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 19, 'He led me to a place of safety; he rescued me because he delights in me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 20, 'The LORD rewarded me for doing right; he compensated me because of my innocence.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 21, 'For I have kept the ways of the LORD; I have not turned from my God to follow evil.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 22, 'For all his laws are constantly before me; I have never abandoned his principles.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 23, 'I am blameless before God; I have kept myself from sin.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 24, 'The LORD rewarded me for doing right, because of the innocence of my hands in his sight.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 25, 'To the faithful you show yourself faithful; to those with integrity you show integrity.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 26, 'To the pure you show yourself pure, but to the wicked you show yourself hostile.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 27, 'You rescue those who are humble, but you humiliate the proud.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 28, 'LORD, you have brought light to my life; my God, you light up my darkness.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 29, 'In your strength I can crush an army; with my God I can scale any wall.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 30, 'As for God, his way is perfect. All the LORD''s promises prove true. He is a shield for all who look to him for protection.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 31, 'For who is God except the LORD? Who but our God is a solid rock?', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 32, 'God arms me with strength; he has made my way safe.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 33, 'He makes me as surefooted as a deer, leading me safely along the mountain heights.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 34, 'He prepares me for battle; he strengthens me to draw a bow of bronze.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 35, 'You have given me the shield of your salvation. Your right hand supports me; your gentleness has made me great.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 36, 'You have made a wide path for my feet to keep them from slipping.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 37, 'I chased my enemies and caught them; I did not stop until they were conquered.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 38, 'I struck them down so they could not get up; they fell beneath my feet.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 39, 'You have armed me with strength for the battle; you have subdued my enemies under my feet.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 40, 'You made them turn and run; I have destroyed all who hated me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 41, 'They called for help, but no one came to rescue them. They cried to the LORD, but he refused to answer them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 42, 'I ground them as fine as dust carried by the wind. I swept them into the gutter like dirt.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 43, 'You gave me victory over my accusers. You appointed me as the ruler over nations; people I don''t even know now serve me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 44, 'As soon as they hear of me, they submit; foreigners cringe before me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 45, 'They all lose their courage and come trembling from their strongholds.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 46, 'The LORD lives! Blessed be my rock! May the God of my salvation be exalted!', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 47, 'He is the God who pays back those who harm me; he subdues the nations under me', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 48, 'and rescues me from my enemies. You hold me safe beyond the reach of my enemies; you save me from violent opponents.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 49, 'For this, O LORD, I will praise you among the nations; I will sing joyfully to your name.', 'NLT'),
(23, 18, 50, 'You give great victories to your king; you show unfailing love to your anointed, to David and all his descendants forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 1, 'The heavens tell of the glory of God. The skies display his marvelous craftsmanship.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 2, 'Day after day they continue to speak; night after night they make him known.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 3, 'They speak without a sound or a word; their voice is silent in the skies;', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 4, 'yet their message has gone out to all the earth, and their words to all the world. The sun lives in the heavens where God placed it.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 5, 'It bursts forth like a radiant bridegroom after his wedding. It rejoices like a great athlete eager to run the race.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 6, 'The sun rises at one end of the heavens and follows its course to the other end. Nothing can hide from its heat.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 7, 'The law of the LORD is perfect, reviving the soul. The decrees of the LORD are trustworthy, making wise the simple.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 8, 'The commandments of the LORD are right, bringing joy to the heart. The commands of the LORD are clear, giving insight to life.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 9, 'Reverence for the LORD is pure, lasting forever. The laws of the LORD are true; each one is fair.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 10, 'They are more desirable than gold, even the finest gold. They are sweeter than honey, even honey dripping from the comb.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 11, 'They are a warning to those who hear them; there is great reward for those who obey them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 12, 'How can I know all the sins lurking in my heart? Cleanse me from these hidden faults.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 13, 'Keep me from deliberate sins! Don''t let them control me. Then I will be free of guilt and innocent of great sin.', 'NLT'),
(23, 19, 14, 'May the words of my mouth and the thoughts of my heart be pleasing to you, O LORD, my rock and my redeemer.', 'NLT'),
(23, 20, 1, 'In times of trouble, may the LORD respond to your cry. May the God of Israel keep you safe from all harm.', 'NLT'),
(23, 20, 2, 'May he send you help from his sanctuary and strengthen you from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(23, 20, 3, 'May he remember all your gifts and look favorably on your burnt offerings.', 'NLT'),
(23, 20, 4, 'May he grant your heart''s desire and fulfill all your plans.', 'NLT'),
(23, 20, 5, 'May we shout for joy when we hear of your victory, flying banners to honor our God. May the LORD answer all your prayers.', 'NLT'),
(23, 20, 6, 'Now I know that the LORD saves his anointed king. He will answer him from his holy heaven and rescue him by his great power.', 'NLT'),
(23, 20, 7, 'Some nations boast of their armies and weapons, but we boast in the LORD our God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 20, 8, 'Those nations will fall down and collapse, but we will rise up and stand firm.', 'NLT'),
(23, 20, 9, 'Give victory to our king, O LORD! Respond to our cry for help.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 1, 'How the king rejoices in your strength, O LORD! He shouts with joy because of your victory.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 2, 'For you have given him his heart''s desire; you have held back nothing that he requested.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 3, 'You welcomed him back with success and prosperity. You placed a crown of finest gold on his head.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 4, 'He asked you to preserve his life, and you have granted his request. The days of his life stretch on forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 5, 'Your victory brings him great honor, and you have clothed him with splendor and majesty.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 6, 'You have endowed him with eternal blessings. You have given him the joy of being in your presence.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 7, 'For the king trusts in the LORD. The unfailing love of the Most High will keep him from stumbling.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 8, 'You will capture all your enemies. Your strong right hand will seize all those who hate you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 9, 'You will destroy them as in a flaming furnace when you appear. The LORD will consume them in his anger; fire will devour them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 10, 'You will wipe their children from the face of the earth; they will never have descendants.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 11, 'Although they plot against you, their evil schemes will never succeed.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 12, 'For they will turn and run when they see your arrows aimed at them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 21, 13, 'We praise you, LORD, for all your glorious power. With music and singing we celebrate your mighty acts.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 1, 'My God, my God! Why have you forsaken me? Why do you remain so distant? Why do you ignore my cries for help?', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 2, 'Every day I call to you, my God, but you do not answer. Every night you hear my voice, but I find no relief.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 3, 'Yet you are holy. The praises of Israel surround your throne.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 4, 'Our ancestors trusted in you, and you rescued them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 5, 'You heard their cries for help and saved them. They put their trust in you and were never disappointed.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 6, 'But I am a worm and not a man. I am scorned and despised by all!', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 7, 'Everyone who sees me mocks me. They sneer and shake their heads, saying,', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 8, '"Is this the one who relies on the LORD? Then let the LORD save him! If the LORD loves him so much, let the LORD rescue him!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 9, 'Yet you brought me safely from my mother''s womb and led me to trust you when I was a nursing infant.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 10, 'I was thrust upon you at my birth. You have been my God from the moment I was born.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 11, 'Do not stay so far from me, for trouble is near, and no one else can help me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 12, 'My enemies surround me like a herd of bulls; fierce bulls of Bashan have hemmed me in!', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 13, 'Like roaring lions attacking their prey, they come at me with open mouths.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 14, 'My life is poured out like water, and all my bones are out of joint. My heart is like wax, melting within me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 15, 'My strength has dried up like sunbaked clay. My tongue sticks to the roof of my mouth. You have laid me in the dust and left me for dead.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 16, 'My enemies surround me like a pack of dogs; an evil gang closes in on me. They have pierced my hands and feet.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 17, 'I can count every bone in my body. My enemies stare at me and gloat.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 18, 'They divide my clothes among themselves and throw dice for my garments.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 19, 'O LORD, do not stay away! You are my strength; come quickly to my aid!', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 20, 'Rescue me from a violent death; spare my precious life from these dogs.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 21, 'Snatch me from the lions'' jaws, and from the horns of these wild oxen.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 22, 'Then I will declare the wonder of your name to my brothers and sisters. I will praise you among all your people.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 23, 'Praise the LORD, all you who fear him! Honor him, all you descendants of Jacob! Show him reverence, all you descendants of Israel!', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 24, 'For he has not ignored the suffering of the needy. He has not turned and walked away. He has listened to their cries for help.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 25, 'I will praise you among all the people; I will fulfill my vows in the presence of those who worship you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 26, 'The poor will eat and be satisfied. All who seek the LORD will praise him. Their hearts will rejoice with everlasting joy.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 27, 'The whole earth will acknowledge the LORD and return to him. People from every nation will bow down before him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 28, 'For the LORD is king! He rules all the nations.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 29, 'Let the rich of the earth feast and worship. Let all mortals--those born to die--bow down in his presence.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 30, 'Future generations will also serve him. Our children will hear about the wonders of the Lord.', 'NLT'),
(23, 22, 31, 'His righteous acts will be told to those yet unborn. They will hear about everything he has done.', 'NLT'),
(23, 23, 1, 'The LORD is my shepherd; I have everything I need.', 'NLT'),
(23, 23, 2, 'He lets me rest in green meadows; he leads me beside peaceful streams.', 'NLT'),
(23, 23, 3, 'He renews my strength. He guides me along right paths, bringing honor to his name.', 'NLT'),
(23, 23, 4, 'Even when I walk through the dark valley of death, I will not be afraid, for you are close beside me. Your rod and your staff protect and comfort me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 23, 5, 'You prepare a feast for me in the presence of my enemies. You welcome me as a guest, anointing my head with oil. My cup overflows with blessings.', 'NLT'),
(23, 23, 6, 'Surely your goodness and unfailing love will pursue me all the days of my life, and I will live in the house of the LORD forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 24, 1, 'The earth is the LORD''s, and everything in it. The world and all its people belong to him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 24, 2, 'For he laid the earth''s foundation on the seas and built it on the ocean depths.', 'NLT'),
(23, 24, 3, 'Who may climb the mountain of the LORD? Who may stand in his holy place?', 'NLT'),
(23, 24, 4, 'Only those whose hands and hearts are pure, who do not worship idols and never tell lies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 24, 5, 'They will receive the LORD''s blessing and have right standing with God their savior.', 'NLT'),
(23, 24, 6, 'They alone may enter God''s presence and worship the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(23, 24, 7, 'Open up, ancient gates! Open up, ancient doors, and let the King of glory enter.', 'NLT'),
(23, 24, 8, 'Who is the King of glory? The LORD, strong and mighty, the LORD, invincible in battle.', 'NLT'),
(23, 24, 9, 'Open up, ancient gates! Open up, ancient doors, and let the King of glory enter.', 'NLT'),
(23, 24, 10, 'Who is the King of glory? The LORD Almighty--he is the King of glory.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 1, 'To you, O LORD, I lift up my soul.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 2, 'I trust in you, my God! Do not let me be disgraced, or let my enemies rejoice in my defeat.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 3, 'No one who trusts in you will ever be disgraced, but disgrace comes to those who try to deceive others.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 4, 'Show me the path where I should walk, O LORD; point out the right road for me to follow.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 5, 'Lead me by your truth and teach me, for you are the God who saves me. All day long I put my hope in you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 6, 'Remember, O LORD, your unfailing love and compassion, which you have shown from long ages past.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 7, 'Forgive the rebellious sins of my youth; look instead through the eyes of your unfailing love, for you are merciful, O LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 8, 'The LORD is good and does what is right; he shows the proper path to those who go astray.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 9, 'He leads the humble in what is right, teaching them his way.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 10, 'The LORD leads with unfailing love and faithfulness all those who keep his covenant and obey his decrees.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 11, 'For the honor of your name, O LORD, forgive my many, many sins.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 12, 'Who are those who fear the LORD? He will show them the path they should choose.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 13, 'They will live in prosperity, and their children will inherit the Promised Land.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 14, 'Friendship with the LORD is reserved for those who fear him. With them he shares the secrets of his covenant.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 15, 'My eyes are always looking to the LORD for help, for he alone can rescue me from the traps of my enemies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 16, 'Turn to me and have mercy on me, for I am alone and in deep distress.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 17, 'My problems go from bad to worse. Oh, save me from them all!', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 18, 'Feel my pain and see my trouble. Forgive all my sins.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 19, 'See how many enemies I have, and how viciously they hate me!', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 20, 'Protect me! Rescue my life from them! Do not let me be disgraced, for I trust in you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 21, 'May integrity and honesty protect me, for I put my hope in you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 25, 22, 'O God, ransom Israel from all its troubles.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 1, 'Declare me innocent, O LORD, for I have acted with integrity; I have trusted in the LORD without wavering.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 2, 'Put me on trial, LORD, and cross-examine me. Test my motives and affections.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 3, 'For I am constantly aware of your unfailing love, and I have lived according to your truth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 4, 'I do not spend time with liars or go along with hypocrites.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 5, 'I hate the gatherings of those who do evil, and I refuse to join in with the wicked.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 6, 'I wash my hands to declare my innocence. I come to your altar, O LORD,', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 7, 'singing a song of thanksgiving and telling of all your miracles.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 8, 'I love your sanctuary, LORD, the place where your glory shines.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 9, 'Don''t let me suffer the fate of sinners. Don''t condemn me along with murderers.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 10, 'Their hands are dirty with wicked schemes, and they constantly take bribes.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 11, 'But I am not like that; I do what is right. So in your mercy, save me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 26, 12, 'I have taken a stand, and I will publicly praise the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 1, 'The LORD is my light and my salvation--so why should I be afraid? The LORD protects me from danger--so why should I tremble?', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 2, 'When evil people come to destroy me, when my enemies and foes attack me, they will stumble and fall.', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 3, 'Though a mighty army surrounds me, my heart will know no fear. Even if they attack me, I remain confident.', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 4, 'The one thing I ask of the LORD--the thing I seek most--is to live in the house of the LORD all the days of my life, delighting in the LORD''s perfections and meditating in his Temple.', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 5, 'For he will conceal me there when troubles come; he will hide me in his sanctuary. He will place me out of reach on a high rock.', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 6, 'Then I will hold my head high, above my enemies who surround me. At his Tabernacle I will offer sacrifices with shouts of joy, singing and praising the LORD with music.', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 7, 'Listen to my pleading, O LORD. Be merciful and answer me!', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 8, 'My heart has heard you say, "Come and talk with me." And my heart responds, "LORD, I am coming."', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 9, 'Do not hide yourself from me. Do not reject your servant in anger. You have always been my helper. Don''t leave me now; don''t abandon me, O God of my salvation!', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 10, 'Even if my father and mother abandon me, the LORD will hold me close.', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 11, 'Teach me how to live, O LORD. Lead me along the path of honesty, for my enemies are waiting for me to fall.', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 12, 'Do not let me fall into their hands. For they accuse me of things I''ve never done and breathe out violence against me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 13, 'Yet I am confident that I will see the LORD''s goodness while I am here in the land of the living.', 'NLT'),
(23, 27, 14, 'Wait patiently for the LORD. Be brave and courageous. Yes, wait patiently for the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 28, 1, 'O LORD, you are my rock of safety. Please help me; don''t refuse to answer me. For if you are silent, I might as well give up and die.', 'NLT'),
(23, 28, 2, 'Listen to my prayer for mercy as I cry out to you for help, as I lift my hands toward your holy sanctuary.', 'NLT'),
(23, 28, 3, 'Don''t drag me away with the wicked--with those who do evil--those who speak friendly words to their neighbors while planning evil in their hearts.', 'NLT'),
(23, 28, 4, 'Give them the punishment they so richly deserve! Measure it out in proportion to their wickedness. Pay them back for all their evil deeds! Give them a taste of what they have done to others.', 'NLT'),
(23, 28, 5, 'They care nothing for what the LORD has done or for what his hands have made. So he will tear them down like old buildings, and they will never be rebuilt!', 'NLT'),
(23, 28, 6, 'Praise the LORD! For he has heard my cry for mercy.', 'NLT'),
(23, 28, 7, 'The LORD is my strength, my shield from every danger. I trust in him with all my heart. He helps me, and my heart is filled with joy. I burst out in songs of thanksgiving.', 'NLT'),
(23, 28, 8, 'The LORD protects his people and gives victory to his anointed king.', 'NLT'),
(23, 28, 9, 'Save your people! Bless Israel, your special possession! Lead them like a shepherd, and carry them forever in your arms.', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 1, 'Give honor to the LORD, you angels; give honor to the LORD for his glory and strength.', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 2, 'Give honor to the LORD for the glory of his name. Worship the LORD in the splendor of his holiness.', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 3, 'The voice of the LORD echoes above the sea. The God of glory thunders. The LORD thunders over the mighty sea.', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 4, 'The voice of the LORD is powerful; the voice of the LORD is full of majesty.', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 5, 'The voice of the LORD splits the mighty cedars; the LORD shatters the cedars of Lebanon.', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 6, 'He makes Lebanon''s mountains skip like a calf and Mount Hermon to leap like a young bull.', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 7, 'The voice of the LORD strikes with lightning bolts.', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 8, 'The voice of the LORD makes the desert quake; the LORD shakes the desert of Kadesh.', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 9, 'The voice of the LORD twists mighty oaks and strips the forests bare. In his Temple everyone shouts, "Glory!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 10, 'The LORD rules over the floodwaters. The LORD reigns as king forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 29, 11, 'The LORD gives his people strength. The LORD blesses them with peace.', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 1, 'I will praise you, LORD, for you have rescued me. You refused to let my enemies triumph over me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 2, 'O LORD my God, I cried out to you for help, and you restored my health.', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 3, 'You brought me up from the grave, O LORD. You kept me from falling into the pit of death.', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 4, 'Sing to the LORD, all you godly ones! Praise his holy name.', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 5, 'His anger lasts for a moment, but his favor lasts a lifetime! Weeping may go on all night, but joy comes with the morning.', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 6, 'When I was prosperous I said, "Nothing can stop me now!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 7, 'Your favor, O LORD, made me as secure as a mountain. Then you turned away from me, and I was shattered.', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 8, 'I cried out to you, O LORD. I begged the Lord for mercy, saying,', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 9, '"What will you gain if I die, if I sink down into the grave? Can my dust praise you from the grave? Can it tell the world of your faithfulness?', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 10, 'Hear me, LORD, and have mercy on me. Help me, O LORD."', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 11, 'You have turned my mourning into joyful dancing. You have taken away my clothes of mourning and clothed me with joy,', 'NLT'),
(23, 30, 12, 'that I might sing praises to you and not be silent. O LORD my God, I will give you thanks forever!', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 1, 'O LORD, I have come to you for protection; don''t let me be put to shame. Rescue me, for you always do what is right.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 2, 'Bend down and listen to me; rescue me quickly. Be for me a great rock of safety, a fortress where my enemies cannot reach me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 3, 'You are my rock and my fortress. For the honor of your name, lead me out of this peril.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 4, 'Pull me from the trap my enemies set for me, for I find protection in you alone.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 5, 'I entrust my spirit into your hand. Rescue me, LORD, for you are a faithful God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 6, 'I hate those who worship worthless idols. I trust in the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 7, 'I am overcome with joy because of your unfailing love, for you have seen my troubles, and you care about the anguish of my soul.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 8, 'You have not handed me over to my enemy but have set me in a safe place.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 9, 'Have mercy on me, LORD, for I am in distress. My sight is blurred because of my tears. My body and soul are withering away.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 10, 'I am dying from grief; my years are shortened by sadness. Misery has drained my strength; I am wasting away from within.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 11, 'I am scorned by all my enemies and despised by my neighbors--even my friends are afraid to come near me. When they see me on the street, they turn the other way.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 12, 'I have been ignored as if I were dead, as if I were a broken pot.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 13, 'I have heard the many rumors about me, and I am surrounded by terror. My enemies conspire against me, plotting to take my life.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 14, 'But I am trusting you, O LORD, saying, "You are my God!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 15, 'My future is in your hands. Rescue me from those who hunt me down relentlessly.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 16, 'Let your favor shine on your servant. In your unfailing love, save me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 17, 'Don''t let me be disgraced, O LORD, for I call out to you for help. Let the wicked be disgraced; let them lie silent in the grave.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 18, 'May their lying lips be silenced--those proud and arrogant lips that accuse the godly.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 19, 'Your goodness is so great! You have stored up great blessings for those who honor you. You have done so much for those who come to you for protection, blessing them before the watching world.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 20, 'You hide them in the shelter of your presence, safe from those who conspire against them. You shelter them in your presence, far from accusing tongues.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 21, 'Praise the LORD, for he has shown me his unfailing love. He kept me safe when my city was under attack.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 22, 'In sudden fear I had cried out, "I have been cut off from the LORD!" But you heard my cry for mercy and answered my call for help.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 23, 'Love the LORD, all you faithful ones! For the LORD protects those who are loyal to him, but he harshly punishes all who are arrogant.', 'NLT'),
(23, 31, 24, 'So be strong and take courage, all you who put your hope in the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 1, 'Oh, what joy for those whose rebellion is forgiven, whose sin is put out of sight!', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 2, 'Yes, what joy for those whose record the LORD has cleared of sin, whose lives are lived in complete honesty!', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 3, 'When I refused to confess my sin, I was weak and miserable, and I groaned all day long.', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 4, 'Day and night your hand of discipline was heavy on me. My strength evaporated like water in the summer heat.', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 5, 'Finally, I confessed all my sins to you and stopped trying to hide them. I said to myself, "I will confess my rebellion to the LORD." And you forgave me! All my guilt is gone.', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 6, 'Therefore, let all the godly confess their rebellion to you while there is time, that they may not drown in the floodwaters of judgment.', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 7, 'For you are my hiding place; you protect me from trouble. You surround me with songs of victory.', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 8, 'The LORD says, "I will guide you along the best pathway for your life. I will advise you and watch over you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 9, 'Do not be like a senseless horse or mule that needs a bit and bridle to keep it under control."', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 10, 'Many sorrows come to the wicked, but unfailing love surrounds those who trust the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 32, 11, 'So rejoice in the LORD and be glad, all you who obey him! Shout for joy, all you whose hearts are pure!', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 1, 'Let the godly sing with joy to the LORD, for it is fitting to praise him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 2, 'Praise the LORD with melodies on the lyre; make music for him on the ten-stringed harp.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 3, 'Sing new songs of praise to him; play skillfully on the harp and sing with joy.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 4, 'For the word of the LORD holds true, and everything he does is worthy of our trust.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 5, 'He loves whatever is just and good, and his unfailing love fills the earth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 6, 'The LORD merely spoke, and the heavens were created. He breathed the word, and all the stars were born.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 7, 'He gave the sea its boundaries and locked the oceans in vast reservoirs.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 8, 'Let everyone in the world fear the LORD, and let everyone stand in awe of him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 9, 'For when he spoke, the world began! It appeared at his command.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 10, 'The LORD shatters the plans of the nations and thwarts all their schemes.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 11, 'But the LORD''s plans stand firm forever; his intentions can never be shaken.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 12, 'What joy for the nation whose God is the LORD, whose people he has chosen for his own.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 13, 'The LORD looks down from heaven and sees the whole human race.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 14, 'From his throne he observes all who live on the earth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 15, 'He made their hearts, so he understands everything they do.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 16, 'The best-equipped army cannot save a king, nor is great strength enough to save a warrior.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 17, 'Don''t count on your warhorse to give you victory--for all its strength, it cannot save you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 18, 'But the LORD watches over those who fear him, those who rely on his unfailing love.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 19, 'He rescues them from death and keeps them alive in times of famine.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 20, 'We depend on the LORD alone to save us. Only he can help us, protecting us like a shield.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 21, 'In him our hearts rejoice, for we are trusting in his holy name.', 'NLT'),
(23, 33, 22, 'Let your unfailing love surround us, LORD, for our hope is in you alone.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 1, 'I will praise the LORD at all times. I will constantly speak his praises.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 2, 'I will boast only in the LORD; let all who are discouraged take heart.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 3, 'Come, let us tell of the LORD''s greatness; let us exalt his name together.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 4, 'I prayed to the LORD, and he answered me, freeing me from all my fears.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 5, 'Those who look to him for help will be radiant with joy; no shadow of shame will darken their faces.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 6, 'I cried out to the LORD in my suffering, and he heard me. He set me free from all my fears.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 7, 'For the angel of the LORD guards all who fear him, and he rescues them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 8, 'Taste and see that the LORD is good. Oh, the joys of those who trust in him!', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 9, 'Let the LORD''s people show him reverence, for those who honor him will have all they need.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 10, 'Even strong young lions sometimes go hungry, but those who trust in the LORD will never lack any good thing.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 11, 'Come, my children, and listen to me, and I will teach you to fear the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 12, 'Do any of you want to live a life that is long and good?', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 13, 'Then watch your tongue! Keep your lips from telling lies!', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 14, 'Turn away from evil and do good. Work hard at living in peace with others.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 15, 'The eyes of the LORD watch over those who do right; his ears are open to their cries for help.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 16, 'But the LORD turns his face against those who do evil; he will erase their memory from the earth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 17, 'The LORD hears his people when they call to him for help. He rescues them from all their troubles.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 18, 'The LORD is close to the brokenhearted; he rescues those who are crushed in spirit.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 19, 'The righteous face many troubles, but the LORD rescues them from each and every one.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 20, 'For the LORD protects them from harm--not one of their bones will be broken!', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 21, 'Calamity will surely overtake the wicked, and those who hate the righteous will be punished.', 'NLT'),
(23, 34, 22, 'But the LORD will redeem those who serve him. Everyone who trusts in him will be freely pardoned.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 1, 'O LORD, oppose those who oppose me. Declare war on those who are attacking me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 2, 'Put on your armor, and take up your shield. Prepare for battle, and come to my aid.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 3, 'Lift up your spear and javelin and block the way of my enemies. Let me hear you say, "I am your salvation!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 4, 'Humiliate and disgrace those trying to kill me; turn them back in confusion.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 5, 'Blow them away like chaff in the wind--a wind sent by the angel of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 6, 'Make their path dark and slippery, with the angel of the LORD pursuing them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 7, 'Although I did them no wrong, they laid a trap for me. Although I did them no wrong, they dug a pit for me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 8, 'So let sudden ruin overtake them! Let them be caught in the snare they set for me! Let them fall to destruction in the pit they dug for me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 9, 'Then I will rejoice in the LORD. I will be glad because he rescues me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 10, 'I will praise him from the bottom of my heart: "LORD, who can compare with you? Who else rescues the weak and helpless from the strong? Who else protects the poor and needy from those who want to rob them?"', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 11, 'Malicious witnesses testify against me. They accuse me of things I don''t even know about.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 12, 'They repay me with evil for the good I do. I am sick with despair.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 13, 'Yet when they were ill, I grieved for them. I even fasted and prayed for them, but my prayers returned unanswered.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 14, 'I was sad, as though they were my friends or family, as if I were grieving for my own mother.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 15, 'But they are glad now that I am in trouble; they gleefully join together against me. I am attacked by people I don''t even know; they hurl slander at me continually.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 16, 'They mock me with the worst kind of profanity, and they snarl at me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 17, 'How long, O Lord, will you look on and do nothing? Rescue me from their fierce attacks. Protect my life from these lions!', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 18, 'Then I will thank you in front of the entire congregation. I will praise you before all the people.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 19, 'Don''t let my treacherous enemies rejoice over my defeat. Don''t let those who hate me without cause gloat over my sorrow.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 20, 'They don''t talk of peace; they plot against innocent people who are minding their own business.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 21, 'They shout that they have seen me doing wrong. "Aha," they say. "Aha! With our own eyes we saw him do it!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 22, 'O LORD, you know all about this. Do not stay silent. Don''t abandon me now, O Lord.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 23, 'Wake up! Rise to my defense! Take up my case, my God and my Lord.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 24, 'Declare me "not guilty," O LORD my God, for you give justice. Don''t let my enemies laugh about me in my troubles.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 25, 'Don''t let them say, "Look! We have what we wanted! Now we will eat him alive!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 26, 'May those who rejoice at my troubles be humiliated and disgraced. May those who triumph over me be covered with shame and dishonor.', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 27, 'But give great joy to those who have stood with me in my defense. Let them continually say, "Great is the LORD, who enjoys helping his servant."', 'NLT'),
(23, 35, 28, 'Then I will tell everyone of your justice and goodness, and I will praise you all day long.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 1, 'Sin whispers to the wicked, deep within their hearts. They have no fear of God to restrain them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 2, 'In their blind conceit, they cannot see how wicked they really are.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 3, 'Everything they say is crooked and deceitful. They refuse to act wisely or do what is good.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 4, 'They lie awake at night, hatching sinful plots. Their course of action is never good. They make no attempt to turn from evil.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 5, 'Your unfailing love, O LORD, is as vast as the heavens; your faithfulness reaches beyond the clouds.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 6, 'Your righteousness is like the mighty mountains, your justice like the ocean depths. You care for people and animals alike, O LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 7, 'How precious is your unfailing love, O God! All humanity finds shelter in the shadow of your wings.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 8, 'You feed them from the abundance of your own house, letting them drink from your rivers of delight.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 9, 'For you are the fountain of life, the light by which we see.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 10, 'Pour out your unfailing love on those who love you; give justice to those with honest hearts.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 11, 'Don''t let the proud trample me; don''t let the wicked push me around.', 'NLT'),
(23, 36, 12, 'Look! They have fallen! They have been thrown down, never to rise again.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 1, 'Don''t worry about the wicked. Don''t envy those who do wrong.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 2, 'For like grass, they soon fade away. Like springtime flowers, they soon wither.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 3, 'Trust in the LORD and do good. Then you will live safely in the land and prosper.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 4, 'Take delight in the LORD, and he will give you your heart''s desires.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 5, 'Commit everything you do to the LORD. Trust him, and he will help you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 6, 'He will make your innocence as clear as the dawn, and the justice of your cause will shine like the noonday sun.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 7, 'Be still in the presence of the LORD, and wait patiently for him to act. Don''t worry about evil people who prosper or fret about their wicked schemes.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 8, 'Stop your anger! Turn from your rage! Do not envy others--it only leads to harm.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 9, 'For the wicked will be destroyed, but those who trust in the LORD will possess the land.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 10, 'In a little while, the wicked will disappear. Though you look for them, they will be gone.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 11, 'Those who are gentle and lowly will possess the land; they will live in prosperous security.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 12, 'The wicked plot against the godly; they snarl at them in defiance.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 13, 'But the Lord just laughs, for he sees their day of judgment coming.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 14, 'The wicked draw their swords and string their bows to kill the poor and the oppressed, to slaughter those who do right.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 15, 'But they will be stabbed through the heart with their own swords, and their bows will be broken.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 16, 'It is better to be godly and have little than to be evil and possess much.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 17, 'For the strength of the wicked will be shattered, but the LORD takes care of the godly.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 18, 'Day by day the LORD takes care of the innocent, and they will receive a reward that lasts forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 19, 'They will survive through hard times; even in famine they will have more than enough.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 20, 'But the wicked will perish. The LORD''s enemies are like flowers in a field--they will disappear like smoke.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 21, 'The wicked borrow and never repay, but the godly are generous givers.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 22, 'Those blessed by the LORD will inherit the land, but those cursed by him will die.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 23, 'The steps of the godly are directed by the LORD. He delights in every detail of their lives.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 24, 'Though they stumble, they will not fall, for the LORD holds them by the hand.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 25, 'Once I was young, and now I am old. Yet I have never seen the godly forsaken, nor seen their children begging for bread.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 26, 'The godly always give generous loans to others, and their children are a blessing.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 27, 'Turn from evil and do good, and you will live in the land forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 28, 'For the LORD loves justice, and he will never abandon the godly. He will keep them safe forever, but the children of the wicked will perish.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 29, 'The godly will inherit the land and will live there forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 30, 'The godly offer good counsel; they know what is right from wrong.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 31, 'They fill their hearts with God''s law, so they will never slip from his path.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 32, 'Those who are evil spy on the godly, waiting for an excuse to kill them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 33, 'But the LORD will not let the wicked succeed or let the godly be condemned when they are brought before the judge.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 34, 'Don''t be impatient for the LORD to act! Travel steadily along his path. He will honor you, giving you the land. You will see the wicked destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 35, 'I myself have seen it happen--proud and evil people thriving like mighty trees.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 36, 'But when I looked again, they were gone! Though I searched for them, I could not find them!', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 37, 'Look at those who are honest and good, for a wonderful future lies before those who love peace.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 38, 'But the wicked will be destroyed; they have no future.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 39, 'The LORD saves the godly; he is their fortress in times of trouble.', 'NLT'),
(23, 37, 40, 'The LORD helps them, rescuing them from the wicked. He saves them, and they find shelter in him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 1, 'O LORD, don''t rebuke me in your anger! Don''t discipline me in your rage!', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 2, 'Your arrows have struck deep, and your blows are crushing me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 3, 'Because of your anger, my whole body is sick; my health is broken because of my sins.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 4, 'My guilt overwhelms me--it is a burden too heavy to bear.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 5, 'My wounds fester and stink because of my foolish sins.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 6, 'I am bent over and racked with pain. My days are filled with grief.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 7, 'A raging fever burns within me, and my health is broken.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 8, 'I am exhausted and completely crushed. My groans come from an anguished heart.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 9, 'You know what I long for, Lord; you hear my every sigh.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 10, 'My heart beats wildly, my strength fails, and I am going blind.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 11, 'My loved ones and friends stay away, fearing my disease. Even my own family stands at a distance.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 12, 'Meanwhile, my enemies lay traps for me; they make plans to ruin me. They think up treacherous deeds all day long.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 13, 'But I am deaf to all their threats. I am silent before them as one who cannot speak.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 14, 'I choose to hear nothing, and I make no reply.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 15, 'For I am waiting for you, O LORD. You must answer for me, O Lord my God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 16, 'I prayed, "Don''t let my enemies gloat over me or rejoice at my downfall."', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 17, 'I am on the verge of collapse, facing constant pain.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 18, 'But I confess my sins; I am deeply sorry for what I have done.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 19, 'My enemies are many; they hate me though I have done nothing against them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 20, 'They repay me evil for good and oppose me because I stand for the right.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 21, 'Do not abandon me, LORD. Do not stand at a distance, my God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 38, 22, 'Come quickly to help me, O Lord my savior.', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 1, 'I said to myself, "I will watch what I do and not sin in what I say. I will curb my tongue when the ungodly are around me."', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 2, 'But as I stood there in silence--not even speaking of good things--the turmoil within me grew to the bursting point.', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 3, 'My thoughts grew hot within me and began to burn, igniting a fire of words:', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 4, '"LORD, remind me how brief my time on earth will be. Remind me that my days are numbered, and that my life is fleeing away.', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 5, 'My life is no longer than the width of my hand. An entire lifetime is just a moment to you; human existence is but a breath."', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 6, 'We are merely moving shadows, and all our busy rushing ends in nothing. We heap up wealth for someone else to spend.', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 7, 'And so, Lord, where do I put my hope? My only hope is in you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 8, 'Rescue me from my rebellion, for even fools mock me when I rebel.', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 9, 'I am silent before you; I won''t say a word. For my punishment is from you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 10, 'Please, don''t punish me anymore! I am exhausted by the blows from your hand.', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 11, 'When you discipline people for their sins, their lives can be crushed like the life of a moth. Human existence is as frail as breath.', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 12, 'Hear my prayer, O LORD! Listen to my cries for help! Don''t ignore my tears. For I am your guest--a traveler passing through, as my ancestors were before me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 39, 13, 'Spare me so I can smile again before I am gone and exist no more.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 1, 'I waited patiently for the LORD to help me, and he turned to me and heard my cry.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 2, 'He lifted me out of the pit of despair, out of the mud and the mire. He set my feet on solid ground and steadied me as I walked along.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 3, 'He has given me a new song to sing, a hymn of praise to our God. Many will see what he has done and be astounded. They will put their trust in the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 4, 'Oh, the joys of those who trust the LORD, who have no confidence in the proud, or in those who worship idols.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 5, 'O LORD my God, you have done many miracles for us. Your plans for us are too numerous to list. If I tried to recite all your wonderful deeds, I would never come to the end of them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 6, 'You take no delight in sacrifices or offerings. Now that you have made me listen, I finally understand--you don''t require burnt offerings or sin offerings.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 7, 'Then I said, "Look, I have come. And this has been written about me in your scroll:', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 8, 'I take joy in doing your will, my God, for your law is written on my heart."', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 9, 'I have told all your people about your justice. I have not been afraid to speak out, as you, O LORD, well know.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 10, 'I have not kept this good news hidden in my heart; I have talked about your faithfulness and saving power. I have told everyone in the great assembly of your unfailing love and faithfulness.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 11, 'LORD, don''t hold back your tender mercies from me. My only hope is in your unfailing love and faithfulness.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 12, 'For troubles surround me--too many to count! They pile up so high I can''t see my way out. They are more numerous than the hairs on my head. I have lost all my courage.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 13, 'Please, LORD, rescue me! Come quickly, LORD, and help me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 14, 'May those who try to destroy me be humiliated and put to shame. May those who take delight in my trouble be turned back in disgrace.', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 15, 'Let them be horrified by their shame, for they said, "Aha! We''ve got him now!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 16, 'But may all who search for you be filled with joy and gladness. May those who love your salvation repeatedly shout, "The LORD is great!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 40, 17, 'As for me, I am poor and needy, but the Lord is thinking about me right now. You are my helper and my savior. Do not delay, O my God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 1, 'Oh, the joys of those who are kind to the poor. The LORD rescues them in times of trouble.', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 2, 'The LORD protects them and keeps them alive. He gives them prosperity and rescues them from their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 3, 'The LORD nurses them when they are sick and eases their pain and discomfort.', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 4, '"O LORD," I prayed, "have mercy on me. Heal me, for I have sinned against you."', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 5, 'But my enemies say nothing but evil about me. "How soon will he die and be forgotten?" they ask.', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 6, 'They visit me as if they are my friends, but all the while they gather gossip, and when they leave, they spread it everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 7, 'All who hate me whisper about me, imagining the worst for me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 8, '"Whatever he has, it is fatal," they say. "He will never get out of that bed!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 9, 'Even my best friend, the one I trusted completely, the one who shared my food, has turned against me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 10, 'LORD, have mercy on me. Make me well again, so I can pay them back!', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 11, 'I know that you are pleased with me, for you have not let my enemy triumph over me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 12, 'You have preserved my life because I am innocent; you have brought me into your presence forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 41, 13, 'Bless the LORD, the God of Israel, who lives forever from eternal ages past. Amen and amen!', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 1, 'As the deer pants for streams of water, so I long for you, O God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 2, 'I thirst for God, the living God. When can I come and stand before him?', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 3, 'Day and night, I have only tears for food, while my enemies continually taunt me, saying, "Where is this God of yours?"', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 4, 'My heart is breaking as I remember how it used to be: I walked among the crowds of worshipers, leading a great procession to the house of God, singing for joy and giving thanks--it was the sound of a great celebration!', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 5, 'Why am I discouraged? Why so sad? I will put my hope in God! I will praise him again--my Savior and', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 6, 'my God! Now I am deeply discouraged, but I will remember your kindness--from Mount Hermon, the source of the Jordan, from the land of Mount Mizar.', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 7, 'I hear the tumult of the raging seas as your waves and surging tides sweep over me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 8, 'Through each day the LORD pours his unfailing love upon me, and through each night I sing his songs, praying to God who gives me life.', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 9, '"O God my rock," I cry, "Why have you forsaken me? Why must I wander in darkness, oppressed by my enemies?"', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 10, 'Their taunts pierce me like a fatal wound. They scoff, "Where is this God of yours?"', 'NLT'),
(23, 42, 11, 'Why am I discouraged? Why so sad? I will put my hope in God! I will praise him again--my Savior and my God!', 'NLT'),
(23, 43, 1, 'O God, take up my cause! Defend me against these ungodly people. Rescue me from these unjust liars.', 'NLT'),
(23, 43, 2, 'For you are God, my only safe haven. Why have you tossed me aside? Why must I wander around in darkness, oppressed by my enemies?', 'NLT'),
(23, 43, 3, 'Send out your light and your truth; let them guide me. Let them lead me to your holy mountain, to the place where you live.', 'NLT'),
(23, 43, 4, 'There I will go to the altar of God, to God--the source of all my joy. I will praise you with my harp, O God, my God!', 'NLT'),
(23, 43, 5, 'Why am I discouraged? Why so sad? I will put my hope in God! I will praise him again--my Savior and my God!', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 1, 'O God, we have heard it with our own ears--our ancestors have told us of all you did in other days, in days long ago:', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 2, 'You drove out the pagan nations and gave all the land to our ancestors; you crushed their enemies, setting our ancestors free.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 3, 'They did not conquer the land with their swords; it was not their own strength that gave them victory. It was by your mighty power that they succeeded; it was because you favored them and smiled on them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 4, 'You are my King and my God. You command victories for your people.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 5, 'Only by your power can we push back our enemies; only in your name can we trample our foes.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 6, 'I do not trust my bow; I do not count on my sword to save me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 7, 'It is you who gives us victory over our enemies; it is you who humbles those who hate us.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 8, 'O God, we give glory to you all day long and constantly praise your name.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 9, 'But now you have tossed us aside in dishonor. You no longer lead our armies to battle.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 10, 'You make us retreat from our enemies and allow them to plunder our land.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 11, 'You have treated us like sheep waiting to be slaughtered; you have scattered us among the nations.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 12, 'You sold us--your precious people--for a pittance. You valued us at nothing at all.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 13, 'You have caused all our neighbors to mock us. We are an object of scorn and derision to the nations around us.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 14, 'You have made us the butt of their jokes; we are scorned by the whole world.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 15, 'We can''t escape the constant humiliation; shame is written across our faces.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 16, 'All we hear are the taunts of our mockers. All we see are our vengeful enemies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 17, 'All this has happened despite our loyalty to you. We have not violated your covenant.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 18, 'Our hearts have not deserted you. We have not strayed from your path.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 19, 'Yet you have crushed us in the desert. You have covered us with darkness and death.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 20, 'If we had turned away from worshiping our God or spread our hands in prayer to foreign gods,', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 21, 'God would surely have known it, for he knows the secrets of every heart.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 22, 'For your sake we are killed every day; we are being slaughtered like sheep.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 23, 'Wake up, O Lord! Why do you sleep? Get up! Do not reject us forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 24, 'Why do you look the other way? Why do you ignore our suffering and oppression?', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 25, 'We collapse in the dust, lying face down in the dirt.', 'NLT'),
(23, 44, 26, 'Rise up! Come and help us! Save us because of your unfailing love.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 1, 'My heart overflows with a beautiful thought! I will recite a lovely poem to the king, for my tongue is like the pen of a skillful poet.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 2, 'You are the most handsome of all. Gracious words stream from your lips. God himself has blessed you forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 3, 'Put on your sword, O mighty warrior! You are so glorious, so majestic!', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 4, 'In your majesty, ride out to victory, defending truth, humility, and justice. Go forth to perform awe-inspiring deeds!', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 5, 'Your arrows are sharp, piercing your enemies'' hearts. The nations fall before you, lying down beneath your feet.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 6, 'Your throne, O God, endures forever and ever. Your royal power is expressed in justice.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 7, 'You love what is right and hate what is wrong. Therefore God, your God, has anointed you, pouring out the oil of joy on you more than on anyone else.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 8, 'Your robes are perfumed with myrrh, aloes, and cassia. In palaces decorated with ivory, you are entertained by the music of harps.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 9, 'Kings'' daughters are among your concubines. At your right side stands the queen, wearing jewelry of finest gold from Ophir!', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 10, 'Listen to me, O royal daughter; take to heart what I say. Forget your people and your homeland far away.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 11, 'For your royal husband delights in your beauty; honor him, for he is your lord.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 12, 'The princes of Tyre will shower you with gifts. People of great wealth will entreat your favor.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 13, 'The bride, a princess, waits within her chamber, dressed in a gown woven with gold.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 14, 'In her beautiful robes, she is led to the king, accompanied by her bridesmaids.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 15, 'What a joyful, enthusiastic procession as they enter the king''s palace!', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 16, 'Your sons will become kings like their father. You will make them rulers over many lands.', 'NLT'),
(23, 45, 17, 'I will bring honor to your name in every generation. Therefore, the nations will praise you forever and ever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 1, 'God is our refuge and strength, always ready to help in times of trouble.', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 2, 'So we will not fear, even if earthquakes come and the mountains crumble into the sea.', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 3, 'Let the oceans roar and foam. Let the mountains tremble as the waters surge!', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 4, 'A river brings joy to the city of our God, the sacred home of the Most High.', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 5, 'God himself lives in that city; it cannot be destroyed. God will protect it at the break of day.', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 6, 'The nations are in an uproar, and kingdoms crumble! God thunders, and the earth melts!', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 7, 'The LORD Almighty is here among us; the God of Israel is our fortress.', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 8, 'Come, see the glorious works of the LORD: See how he brings destruction upon the world', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 9, 'and causes wars to end throughout the earth. He breaks the bow and snaps the spear in two; he burns the shields with fire.', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 10, '"Be silent, and know that I am God! I will be honored by every nation. I will be honored throughout the world."', 'NLT'),
(23, 46, 11, 'The LORD Almighty is here among us; the God of Israel is our fortress.', 'NLT'),
(23, 47, 1, 'Come, everyone, and clap your hands for joy! Shout to God with joyful praise!', 'NLT'),
(23, 47, 2, 'For the LORD Most High is awesome. He is the great King of all the earth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 47, 3, 'He subdues the nations before us, putting our enemies beneath our feet.', 'NLT'),
(23, 47, 4, 'He chose the Promised Land as our inheritance, the proud possession of Jacob''s descendants, whom he loves.', 'NLT'),
(23, 47, 5, 'God has ascended with a mighty shout. The LORD has ascended with trumpets blaring.', 'NLT'),
(23, 47, 6, 'Sing praise to God, sing praises; sing praise to our King, sing praises!', 'NLT'),
(23, 47, 7, 'For God is the King over all the earth. Praise him with a psalm!', 'NLT'),
(23, 47, 8, 'God reigns above the nations, sitting on his holy throne.', 'NLT'),
(23, 47, 9, 'The rulers of the world have gathered together. They join us in praising the God of Abraham. For all the kings of the earth belong to God. He is highly honored everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 1, 'How great is the LORD, and how much we should praise him in the city of our God, which is on his holy mountain!', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 2, 'It is magnificent in elevation--the whole earth rejoices to see it! Mount Zion, the holy mountain, is the city of the great King!', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 3, 'God himself is in Jerusalem''s towers. He reveals himself as her defender.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 4, 'The kings of the earth joined forces and advanced against the city.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 5, 'But when they saw it, they were stunned; they were terrified and ran away.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 6, 'They were gripped with terror, like a woman writhing in the pain of childbirth', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 7, 'or like the mighty ships of Tarshish being shattered by a powerful east wind.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 8, 'We had heard of the city''s glory, but now we have seen it ourselves--the city of the LORD Almighty. It is the city of our God; he will make it safe forever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 9, 'O God, we meditate on your unfailing love as we worship in your Temple.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 10, 'As your name deserves, O God, you will be praised to the ends of the earth. Your strong right hand is filled with victory.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 11, 'Let the people on Mount Zion rejoice. Let the towns of Judah be glad, for your judgments are just.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 12, 'Go, inspect the city of Jerusalem. Walk around and count the many towers.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 13, 'Take note of the fortified walls, and tour all the citadels, that you may describe them to future generations.', 'NLT'),
(23, 48, 14, 'For that is what God is like. He is our God forever and ever, and he will be our guide until we die.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 1, 'Listen to this, all you people! Pay attention, everyone in the world!', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 2, 'High and low, rich and poor--listen!', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 3, 'For my words are wise, and my thoughts are filled with insight.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 4, 'I listen carefully to many proverbs and solve riddles with inspiration from a harp.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 5, 'There is no need to fear when times of trouble come, when enemies are surrounding me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 6, 'They trust in their wealth and boast of great riches.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 7, 'Yet they cannot redeem themselves from death by paying a ransom to God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 8, 'Redemption does not come so easily, for no one can ever pay enough', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 9, 'to live forever and never see the grave.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 10, 'Those who are wise must finally die, just like the foolish and senseless, leaving all their wealth behind.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 11, 'The grave is their eternal home, where they will stay forever. They may name their estates after themselves, but they leave their wealth to others.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 12, 'They will not last long despite their riches--they will die like the animals.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 13, 'This is the fate of fools, though they will be remembered as being so wise.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 14, 'Like sheep, they are led to the grave, where death will be their shepherd. In the morning the godly will rule over them. Their bodies will rot in the grave, far from their grand estates.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 15, 'But as for me, God will redeem my life. He will snatch me from the power of death.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 16, 'So don''t be dismayed when the wicked grow rich, and their homes become ever more splendid.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 17, 'For when they die, they carry nothing with them. Their wealth will not follow them into the grave.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 18, 'In this life they consider themselves fortunate, and the world loudly applauds their success.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 19, 'But they will die like all others before them and never again see the light of day.', 'NLT'),
(23, 49, 20, 'People who boast of their wealth don''t understand that they will die like the animals.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 1, 'The mighty God, the LORD, has spoken; he has summoned all humanity from east to west!', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 2, 'From Mount Zion, the perfection of beauty, God shines in glorious radiance.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 3, 'Our God approaches with the noise of thunder. Fire devours everything in his way, and a great storm rages around him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 4, 'Heaven and earth will be his witnesses as he judges his people:', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 5, '"Bring my faithful people to me--those who made a covenant with me by giving sacrifices."', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 6, 'Then let the heavens proclaim his justice, for God himself will be the judge.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 7, '"O my people, listen as I speak. Here are my charges against you, O Israel: I am God, your God!', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 8, 'I have no complaint about your sacrifices or the burnt offerings you constantly bring to my altar.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 9, 'But I want no more bulls from your barns; I want no more goats from your pens.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 10, 'For all the animals of the forest are mine, and I own the cattle on a thousand hills.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 11, 'Every bird of the mountains and all the animals of the field belong to me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 12, 'If I were hungry, I would not mention it to you, for all the world is mine and everything in it.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 13, 'I don''t need the bulls you sacrifice; I don''t need the blood of goats.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 14, 'What I want instead is your true thanks to God; I want you to fulfill your vows to the Most High.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 15, 'Trust me in your times of trouble, and I will rescue you, and you will give me glory."', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 16, 'But God says to the wicked: "Recite my laws no longer, and don''t pretend that you obey me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 17, 'For you refuse my discipline and treat my laws like trash.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 18, 'When you see a thief, you help him, and you spend your time with adulterers.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 19, 'Your mouths are filled with wickedness, and your tongues are full of lies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 20, 'You sit around and slander a brother--your own mother''s son.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 21, 'While you did all this, I remained silent, and you thought I didn''t care. But now I will rebuke you, listing all my charges against you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 22, 'Repent, all of you who ignore me, or I will tear you apart, and no one will help you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 50, 23, 'But giving thanks is a sacrifice that truly honors me. If you keep to my path, I will reveal to you the salvation of God."', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 1, 'Have mercy on me, O God, because of your unfailing love. Because of your great compassion, blot out the stain of my sins.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 2, 'Wash me clean from my guilt. Purify me from my sin.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 3, 'For I recognize my shameful deeds--they haunt me day and night.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 4, 'Against you, and you alone, have I sinned; I have done what is evil in your sight. You will be proved right in what you say, and your judgment against me is just.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 5, 'For I was born a sinner--yes, from the moment my mother conceived me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 6, 'But you desire honesty from the heart, so you can teach me to be wise in my inmost being.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 7, 'Purify me from my sins, and I will be clean; wash me, and I will be whiter than snow.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 8, 'Oh, give me back my joy again; you have broken me--now let me rejoice.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 9, 'Don''t keep looking at my sins. Remove the stain of my guilt.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 10, 'Create in me a clean heart, O God. Renew a right spirit within me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 11, 'Do not banish me from your presence, and don''t take your Holy Spirit from me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 12, 'Restore to me again the joy of your salvation, and make me willing to obey you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 13, 'Then I will teach your ways to sinners, and they will return to you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 14, 'Forgive me for shedding blood, O God who saves; then I will joyfully sing of your forgiveness.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 15, 'Unseal my lips, O Lord, that I may praise you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 16, 'You would not be pleased with sacrifices, or I would bring them. If I brought you a burnt offering, you would not accept it.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 17, 'The sacrifice you want is a broken spirit. A broken and repentant heart, O God, you will not despise.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 18, 'Look with favor on Zion and help her; rebuild the walls of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(23, 51, 19, 'Then you will be pleased with worthy sacrifices and with our whole burnt offerings; and bulls will again be sacrificed on your altar.', 'NLT'),
(23, 52, 1, 'You call yourself a hero, do you? Why boast about this crime of yours, you who have disgraced God''s people?', 'NLT'),
(23, 52, 2, 'All day long you plot destruction. Your tongue cuts like a sharp razor; you''re an expert at telling lies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 52, 3, 'You love evil more than good and lies more than truth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 52, 4, 'You love to say things that harm others, you liar!', 'NLT'),
(23, 52, 5, 'But God will strike you down once and for all. He will pull you from your home and drag you from the land of the living.', 'NLT'),
(23, 52, 6, 'The righteous will see it and be amazed. They will laugh and say,', 'NLT'),
(23, 52, 7, '"Look what happens to mighty warriors who do not trust in God. They trust their wealth instead and grow more and more bold in their wickedness."', 'NLT'),
(23, 52, 8, 'But I am like an olive tree, thriving in the house of God. I trust in God''s unfailing love forever and ever.', 'NLT'),
(23, 52, 9, 'I will praise you forever, O God, for what you have done. I will wait for your mercies in the presence of your people.', 'NLT'),
(23, 53, 1, 'Only fools say in their hearts, "There is no God." They are corrupt, and their actions are evil; no one does good!', 'NLT'),
(23, 53, 2, 'God looks down from heaven on the entire human race; he looks to see if there is even one with real understanding, one who seeks for God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 53, 3, 'But no, all have turned away from God; all have become corrupt. No one does good, not even one!', 'NLT'),
(23, 53, 4, 'Will those who do evil never learn? They eat up my people like bread; they wouldn''t think of praying to God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 53, 5, 'But then terror will grip them, terror like they have never known before. God will scatter the bones of your enemies. You will put them to shame, for God has rejected them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 53, 6, 'Oh, that salvation would come from Mount Zion to rescue Israel! For when God restores his people, Jacob will shout with joy, and Israel will rejoice.', 'NLT'),
(23, 54, 1, 'Come with great power, O God, and rescue me! Defend me with your might.', 'NLT'),
(23, 54, 2, 'O God, listen to my prayer. Pay attention to my plea.', 'NLT'),
(23, 54, 3, 'For strangers are attacking me; violent men are trying to kill me. They care nothing for God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 54, 4, 'But God is my helper. The Lord is the one who keeps me alive!', 'NLT'),
(23, 54, 5, 'May my enemies'' plans for evil be turned against them. Do as you promised and put an end to them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 54, 6, 'I will sacrifice a voluntary offering to you; I will praise your name, O LORD, for it is good.', 'NLT'),
(23, 54, 7, 'For you will rescue me from my troubles and help me to triumph over my enemies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 1, 'Listen to my prayer, O God. Do not ignore my cry for help!', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 2, 'Please listen and answer me, for I am overwhelmed by my troubles.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 3, 'My enemies shout at me, making loud and wicked threats. They bring trouble on me, hunting me down in their anger.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 4, 'My heart is in anguish. The terror of death overpowers me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 5, 'Fear and trembling overwhelm me. I can''t stop shaking.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 6, 'Oh, how I wish I had wings like a dove; then I would fly away and rest!', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 7, 'I would fly far away to the quiet of the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 8, 'How quickly I would escape--far away from this wild storm of hatred.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 9, 'Destroy them, Lord, and confuse their speech, for I see violence and strife in the city.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 10, 'Its walls are patrolled day and night against invaders, but the real danger is wickedness within the city.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 11, 'Murder and robbery are everywhere there; threats and cheating are rampant in the streets.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 12, 'It is not an enemy who taunts me--I could bear that. It is not my foes who so arrogantly insult me--I could have hidden from them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 13, 'Instead, it is you--my equal, my companion and close friend.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 14, 'What good fellowship we enjoyed as we walked together to the house of God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 15, 'Let death seize my enemies by surprise; let the grave swallow them alive, for evil makes its home within them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 16, 'But I will call on God, and the LORD will rescue me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 17, 'Morning, noon, and night I plead aloud in my distress, and the LORD hears my voice.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 18, 'He rescues me and keeps me safe from the battle waged against me, even though many still oppose me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 19, 'God, who is king forever, will hear me and will humble them. For my enemies refuse to change their ways; they do not fear God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 20, 'As for this friend of mine, he betrayed me; he broke his promises.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 21, 'His words are as smooth as cream, but in his heart is war. His words are as soothing as lotion, but underneath are daggers!', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 22, 'Give your burdens to the LORD, and he will take care of you. He will not permit the godly to slip and fall.', 'NLT'),
(23, 55, 23, 'But you, O God, will send the wicked down to the pit of destruction. Murderers and liars will die young, but I am trusting you to save me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 1, 'O God, have mercy on me. The enemy troops press in on me. My foes attack me all day long.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 2, 'My slanderers hound me constantly, and many are boldly attacking me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 3, 'But when I am afraid, I put my trust in you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 4, 'O God, I praise your word. I trust in God, so why should I be afraid? What can mere mortals do to me?', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 5, 'They are always twisting what I say; they spend their days plotting ways to harm me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 6, 'They come together to spy on me--watching my every step, eager to kill me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 7, 'Don''t let them get away with their wickedness; in your anger, O God, throw them to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 8, 'You keep track of all my sorrows. You have collected all my tears in your bottle. You have recorded each one in your book.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 9, 'On the very day I call to you for help, my enemies will retreat. This I know: God is on my side.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 10, 'O God, I praise your word. Yes, LORD, I praise your word.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 11, 'I trust in God, so why should I be afraid? What can mere mortals do to me?', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 12, 'I will fulfill my vows to you, O God, and offer a sacrifice of thanks for your help.', 'NLT'),
(23, 56, 13, 'For you have rescued me from death; you have kept my feet from slipping. So now I can walk in your presence, O God, in your life-giving light.', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 1, 'Have mercy on me, O God, have mercy! I look to you for protection. I will hide beneath the shadow of your wings until this violent storm is past.', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 2, 'I cry out to God Most High, to God who will fulfill his purpose for me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 3, 'He will send help from heaven to save me, rescuing me from those who are out to get me. My God will send forth his unfailing love and faithfulness.', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 4, 'I am surrounded by fierce lions who greedily devour human prey--whose teeth pierce like spears and arrows, and whose tongues cut like swords.', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 5, 'Be exalted, O God, above the highest heavens! May your glory shine over all the earth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 6, 'My enemies have set a trap for me. I am weary from distress. They have dug a deep pit in my path, but they themselves have fallen into it.', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 7, 'My heart is confident in you, O God; no wonder I can sing your praises!', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 8, 'Wake up, my soul! Wake up, O harp and lyre! I will waken the dawn with my song.', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 9, 'I will thank you, Lord, in front of all the people. I will sing your praises among the nations.', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 10, 'For your unfailing love is as high as the heavens. Your faithfulness reaches to the clouds.', 'NLT'),
(23, 57, 11, 'Be exalted, O God, above the highest heavens. May your glory shine over all the earth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 1, 'Justice--do you rulers know the meaning of the word? Do you judge the people fairly?', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 2, 'No, all your dealings are crooked; you hand out violence instead of justice.', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 3, 'These wicked people are born sinners; even from birth they have lied and gone their own way.', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 4, 'They spit poison like deadly snakes; they are like cobras that refuse to listen,', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 5, 'ignoring the tunes of the snake charmers, no matter how skillfully they play.', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 6, 'Break off their fangs, O God! Smash the jaws of these lions, O LORD!', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 7, 'May they disappear like water into thirsty ground. Make their weapons useless in their hands.', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 8, 'May they be like snails that dissolve into slime, like a stillborn child who will never see the sun.', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 9, 'God will sweep them away, both young and old, faster than a pot heats on an open flame.', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 10, 'The godly will rejoice when they see injustice avenged. They will wash their feet in the blood of the wicked.', 'NLT'),
(23, 58, 11, 'Then at last everyone will say, "There truly is a reward for those who live for God; surely there is a God who judges justly here on earth."', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 1, 'Rescue me from my enemies, O God. Protect me from those who have come to destroy me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 2, 'Rescue me from these criminals; save me from these murderers.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 3, 'They have set an ambush for me. Fierce enemies are out there waiting, though I have done them no wrong, O LORD.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 4, 'Despite my innocence, they prepare to kill me. Rise up and help me! Look on my plight!', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 5, 'O LORD God Almighty, the God of Israel, rise up to punish hostile nations. Show no mercy to wicked traitors.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 6, 'They come at night, snarling like vicious dogs as they prowl the streets.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 7, 'Listen to the filth that comes from their mouths, the piercing swords that fly from their lips. "Who can hurt us?" they sneer.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 8, 'But LORD, you laugh at them. You scoff at all the hostile nations.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 9, 'You are my strength; I wait for you to rescue me, for you, O God, are my place of safety.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 10, 'In his unfailing love, my God will come and help me. He will let me look down in triumph on all my enemies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 11, 'Don''t kill them, for my people soon forget such lessons; stagger them with your power, and bring them to their knees, O Lord our shield.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 12, 'Because of the sinful things they say, because of the evil that is on their lips, let them be captured by their pride, their curses, and their lies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 13, 'Destroy them in your anger! Wipe them out completely! Then the whole world will know that God reigns in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 14, 'My enemies come out at night, snarling like vicious dogs as they prowl the streets.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 15, 'They scavenge for food but go to sleep unsatisfied.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 16, 'But as for me, I will sing about your power. I will shout with joy each morning because of your unfailing love. For you have been my refuge, a place of safety in the day of distress.', 'NLT'),
(23, 59, 17, 'O my Strength, to you I sing praises, for you, O God, are my refuge, the God who shows me unfailing love.', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 1, 'You have rejected us, O God, and broken our defenses. You have been angry with us; now restore us to your favor.', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 2, 'You have shaken our land and split it open. Seal the cracks before it completely collapses.', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 3, 'You have been very hard on us, making us drink wine that sent us reeling.', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 4, 'But you have raised a banner for those who honor you--a rallying point in the face of attack.', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 5, 'Use your strong right arm to save us, and rescue your beloved people.', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 6, 'God has promised this by his holiness: "I will divide up Shechem with joy. I will measure out the valley of Succoth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 7, 'Gilead is mine, and Manasseh is mine. Ephraim will produce my warriors, and Judah will produce my kings.', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 8, 'Moab will become my lowly servant, and Edom will be my slave. I will shout in triumph over the Philistines."', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 9, 'But who will bring me into the fortified city? Who will bring me victory over Edom?', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 10, 'Have you rejected us, O God? Will you no longer march with our armies?', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 11, 'Oh, please help us against our enemies, for all human help is useless.', 'NLT'),
(23, 60, 12, 'With God''s help we will do mighty things, for he will trample down our foes.', 'NLT'),
(23, 61, 1, 'O God, listen to my cry! Hear my prayer!', 'NLT'),
(23, 61, 2, 'From the ends of the earth, I will cry to you for help, for my heart is overwhelmed. Lead me to the towering rock of safety,', 'NLT'),
(23, 61, 3, 'for you are my safe refuge, a fortress where my enemies cannot reach me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 61, 4, 'Let me live forever in your sanctuary, safe beneath the shelter of your wings!', 'NLT'),
(23, 61, 5, 'For you have heard my vows, O God. You have given me an inheritance reserved for those who fear your name.', 'NLT'),
(23, 61, 6, 'Add many years to the life of the king! May his years span the generations!', 'NLT'),
(23, 61, 7, 'May he reign under God''s protection forever. Appoint your unfailing love and faithfulness to watch over him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 61, 8, 'Then I will always sing praises to your name as I fulfill my vows day after day.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 1, 'I wait quietly before God, for my salvation comes from him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 2, 'He alone is my rock and my salvation, my fortress where I will never be shaken.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 3, 'So many enemies against one man--all of them trying to kill me. To them I''m just a broken-down wall or a tottering fence.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 4, 'They plan to topple me from my high position. They delight in telling lies about me. They are friendly to my face, but they curse me in their hearts.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 5, 'I wait quietly before God, for my hope is in him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 6, 'He alone is my rock and my salvation, my fortress where I will not be shaken.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 7, 'My salvation and my honor come from God alone. He is my refuge, a rock where no enemy can reach me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 8, 'O my people, trust in him at all times. Pour out your heart to him, for God is our refuge.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 9, 'From the greatest to the lowliest--all are nothing in his sight. If you weigh them on the scales, they are lighter than a puff of air.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 10, 'Don''t try to get rich by extortion or robbery. And if your wealth increases, don''t make it the center of your life.', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 11, 'God has spoken plainly, and I have heard it many times: Power, O God, belongs to you;', 'NLT'),
(23, 62, 12, 'unfailing love, O Lord, is yours. Surely you judge all people according to what they have done.', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 1, 'O God, you are my God; I earnestly search for you. My soul thirsts for you; my whole body longs for you in this parched and weary land where there is no water.', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 2, 'I have seen you in your sanctuary and gazed upon your power and glory.', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 3, 'Your unfailing love is better to me than life itself; how I praise you!', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 4, 'I will honor you as long as I live, lifting up my hands to you in prayer.', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 5, 'You satisfy me more than the richest of foods. I will praise you with songs of joy.', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 6, 'I lie awake thinking of you, meditating on you through the night.', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 7, 'I think how much you have helped me; I sing for joy in the shadow of your protecting wings.', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 8, 'I follow close behind you; your strong right hand holds me securely.', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 9, 'But those plotting to destroy me will come to ruin. They will go down into the depths of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 10, 'They will die by the sword and become the food of jackals.', 'NLT'),
(23, 63, 11, 'But the king will rejoice in God. All who trust in him will praise him, while liars will be silenced.', 'NLT'),
(23, 64, 1, 'O God, listen to my complaint. Do not let my enemies'' threats overwhelm me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 64, 2, 'Protect me from the plots of the wicked, from the scheming of those who do evil.', 'NLT'),
(23, 64, 3, 'Sharp tongues are the swords they wield; bitter words are the arrows they aim.', 'NLT'),
(23, 64, 4, 'They shoot from ambush at the innocent, attacking suddenly and fearlessly.', 'NLT'),
(23, 64, 5, 'They encourage each other to do evil and plan how to set their traps. "Who will ever notice?" they ask.', 'NLT'),
(23, 64, 6, 'As they plot their crimes, they say, "We have devised the perfect plan!" Yes, the human heart and mind are cunning.', 'NLT'),
(23, 64, 7, 'But God himself will shoot them down. Suddenly, his arrows will pierce them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 64, 8, 'Their own words will be turned against them, destroying them. All who see it happening will shake their heads in scorn.', 'NLT'),
(23, 64, 9, 'Then everyone will stand in awe, proclaiming the mighty acts of God, realizing all the amazing things he does.', 'NLT'),
(23, 64, 10, 'The godly will rejoice in the LORD and find shelter in him. And those who do what is right will praise him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 1, 'What mighty praise, O God, belongs to you in Zion. We will fulfill our vows to you,', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 2, 'for you answer our prayers, and to you all people will come.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 3, 'Though our hearts are filled with sins, you forgive them all.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 4, 'What joy for those you choose to bring near, those who live in your holy courts. What joys await us inside your holy Temple.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 5, 'You faithfully answer our prayers with awesome deeds, O God our savior. You are the hope of everyone on earth, even those who sail on distant seas.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 6, 'You formed the mountains by your power and armed yourself with mighty strength.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 7, 'You quieted the raging oceans with their pounding waves and silenced the shouting of the nations.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 8, 'Those who live at the ends of the earth stand in awe of your wonders. From where the sun rises to where it sets, you inspire shouts of joy.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 9, 'You take care of the earth and water it, making it rich and fertile. The rivers of God will not run dry; they provide a bountiful harvest of grain, for you have ordered it so.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 10, 'You drench the plowed ground with rain, melting the clods and leveling the ridges. You soften the earth with showers and bless its abundant crops.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 11, 'You crown the year with a bountiful harvest; even the hard pathways overflow with abundance.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 12, 'The wilderness becomes a lush pasture, and the hillsides blossom with joy.', 'NLT'),
(23, 65, 13, 'The meadows are clothed with flocks of sheep, and the valleys are carpeted with grain. They all shout and sing for joy!', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 1, 'Shout joyful praises to God, all the earth!', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 2, 'Sing about the glory of his name! Tell the world how glorious he is.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 3, 'Say to God, "How awesome are your deeds! Your enemies cringe before your mighty power.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 4, 'Everything on earth will worship you; they will sing your praises, shouting your name in glorious songs."', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 5, 'Come and see what our God has done, what awesome miracles he does for his people!', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 6, 'He made a dry path through the Red Sea, and his people went across on foot. Come, let us rejoice in who he is.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 7, 'For by his great power he rules forever. He watches every movement of the nations; let no rebel rise in defiance.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 8, 'Let the whole world bless our God and sing aloud his praises.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 9, 'Our lives are in his hands, and he keeps our feet from stumbling.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 10, 'You have tested us, O God; you have purified us like silver melted in a crucible.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 11, 'You captured us in your net and laid the burden of slavery on our backs.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 12, 'You sent troops to ride across our broken bodies. We went through fire and flood. But you brought us to a place of great abundance.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 13, 'Now I come to your Temple with burnt offerings to fulfill the vows I made to you--', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 14, 'yes, the sacred vows you heard me make when I was in deep trouble.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 15, 'That is why I am sacrificing burnt offerings to you--the best of my rams as a pleasing aroma. And I will sacrifice bulls and goats.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 16, 'Come and listen, all you who fear God, and I will tell you what he did for me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 17, 'For I cried out to him for help, praising him as I spoke.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 18, 'If I had not confessed the sin in my heart, my Lord would not have listened.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 19, 'But God did listen! He paid attention to my prayer.', 'NLT'),
(23, 66, 20, 'Praise God, who did not ignore my prayer and did not withdraw his unfailing love from me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 67, 1, 'May God be merciful and bless us. May his face shine with favor upon us.', 'NLT'),
(23, 67, 2, 'May your ways be known throughout the earth, your saving power among people everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(23, 67, 3, 'May the nations praise you, O God. Yes, may all the nations praise you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 67, 4, 'How glad the nations will be, singing for joy, because you govern them with justice and direct the actions of the whole world.', 'NLT'),
(23, 67, 5, 'May the nations praise you, O God. Yes, may all the nations praise you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 67, 6, 'Then the earth will yield its harvests, and God, our God, will richly bless us.', 'NLT'),
(23, 67, 7, 'Yes, God will bless us, and people all over the world will fear him.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 1, 'Arise, O God, and scatter your enemies. Let those who hate God run for their lives.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 2, 'Drive them off like smoke blown by the wind. Melt them like wax in fire. Let the wicked perish in the presence of God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 3, 'But let the godly rejoice. Let them be glad in God''s presence. Let them be filled with joy.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 4, 'Sing praises to God and to his name! Sing loud praises to him who rides the clouds. His name is the LORD--rejoice in his presence!', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 5, 'Father to the fatherless, defender of widows--this is God, whose dwelling is holy.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 6, 'God places the lonely in families; he sets the prisoners free and gives them joy. But for rebels, there is only famine and distress.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 7, 'O God, when you led your people from Egypt, when you marched through the wilderness,', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 8, 'the earth trembled, and the heavens poured rain before you, the God of Sinai, before God, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 9, 'You sent abundant rain, O God, to refresh the weary Promised Land.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 10, 'There your people finally settled, and with a bountiful harvest, O God, you provided for your needy people.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 11, 'The Lord announces victory, and throngs of women shout the happy news.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 12, 'Enemy kings and their armies flee, while the women of Israel divide the plunder.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 13, 'Though they lived among the sheepfolds, now they are covered with silver and gold, as a dove is covered by its wings.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 14, 'The Almighty scattered the enemy kings like a blowing snowstorm on Mount Zalmon.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 15, 'The majestic mountains of Bashan stretch high into the sky.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 16, 'Why do you look with envy, O rugged mountains, at Mount Zion, where God has chosen to live, where the LORD himself will live forever?', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 17, 'Surrounded by unnumbered thousands of chariots, the Lord came from Mount Sinai into his sanctuary.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 18, 'When you ascended to the heights, you led a crowd of captives. You received gifts from the people, even from those who rebelled against you. Now the LORD God will live among us here.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 19, 'Praise the Lord; praise God our savior! For each day he carries us in his arms.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 20, 'Our God is a God who saves! The Sovereign LORD rescues us from death.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 21, 'But God will smash the heads of his enemies, crushing the skulls of those who love their guilty ways.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 22, 'The Lord says, "I will bring my enemies down from Bashan; I will bring them up from the depths of the sea.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 23, 'You, my people, will wash your feet in their blood, and even your dogs will get their share!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 24, 'Your procession has come into view, O God--the procession of my God and King as he goes into the sanctuary.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 25, 'Singers are in front, musicians are behind; with them are young women playing tambourines.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 26, 'Praise God, all you people of Israel; praise the LORD, the source of Israel''s life.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 27, 'Look, the little tribe of Benjamin leads the way. Then comes a great throng of rulers from Judah and all the rulers of Zebulun and Naphtali.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 28, 'Summon your might, O God. Display your power, O God, as you have in the past.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 29, 'The kings of the earth are bringing tribute to your Temple in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 30, 'Rebuke these enemy nations--these wild animals lurking in the reeds, this herd of bulls among the weaker calves. Humble those who demand tribute from us. Scatter the nations that delight in war.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 31, 'Let Egypt come with gifts of precious metals; let Ethiopia bow in submission to God.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 32, 'Sing to God, you kingdoms of the earth. Sing praises to the Lord.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 33, 'Sing to the one who rides across the ancient heavens, his mighty voice thundering from the sky.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 34, 'Tell everyone about God''s power. His majesty shines down on Israel; his strength is mighty in the heavens.', 'NLT'),
(23, 68, 35, 'God is awesome in his sanctuary. The God of Israel gives power and strength to his people. Praise be to God!', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 1, 'Save me, O God, for the floodwaters are up to my neck.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 2, 'Deeper and deeper I sink into the mire; I can''t find a foothold to stand on. I am in deep water, and the floods overwhelm me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 3, 'I am exhausted from crying for help; my throat is parched and dry. My eyes are swollen with weeping, waiting for my God to help me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 4, 'Those who hate me without cause are more numerous than the hairs on my head. These enemies who seek to destroy me are doing so without cause. They attack me with lies, demanding that I give back what I didn''t steal.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 5, 'O God, you know how foolish I am; my sins cannot be hidden from you.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 6, 'Don''t let those who trust in you stumble because of me, O Sovereign LORD Almighty. Don''t let me cause them to be humiliated, O God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 7, 'For I am mocked and shamed for your sake; humiliation is written all over my face.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 8, 'Even my own brothers pretend they don''t know me; they treat me like a stranger.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 9, 'Passion for your house burns within me, so those who insult you are also insulting me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 10, 'When I weep and fast before the LORD, they scoff at me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 11, 'When I dress in sackcloth to show sorrow, they make fun of me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 12, 'I am the favorite topic of town gossip, and all the drunkards sing about me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 13, 'But I keep right on praying to you, LORD, hoping this is the time you will show me favor. In your unfailing love, O God, answer my prayer with your sure salvation.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 14, 'Pull me out of the mud; don''t let me sink any deeper! Rescue me from those who hate me, and pull me from these deep waters.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 15, 'Don''t let the floods overwhelm me, or the deep waters swallow me, or the pit of death devour me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 16, 'Answer my prayers, O LORD, for your unfailing love is wonderful. Turn and take care of me, for your mercy is so plentiful.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 17, 'Don''t hide from your servant; answer me quickly, for I am in deep trouble!', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 18, 'Come and rescue me; free me from all my enemies.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 19, 'You know the insults I endure--the humiliation and disgrace. You have seen all my enemies and know what they have said.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 20, 'Their insults have broken my heart, and I am in despair. If only one person would show some pity; if only one would turn and comfort me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 21, 'But instead, they give me poison for food; they offer me sour wine to satisfy my thirst.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 22, 'Let the bountiful table set before them become a snare, and let their security become a trap.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 23, 'Let their eyes go blind so they cannot see, and let their bodies grow weaker and weaker.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 24, 'Pour out your fury on them; consume them with your burning anger.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 25, 'May their homes become desolate and their tents be deserted.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 26, 'To those you have punished, they add insult to injury; they scoff at the pain of those you have hurt.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 27, 'Pile their sins up high, and don''t let them go free.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 28, 'Erase their names from the Book of Life; don''t let them be counted among the righteous.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 29, 'I am suffering and in pain. Rescue me, O God, by your saving power.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 30, 'Then I will praise God''s name with singing, and I will honor him with thanksgiving.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 31, 'For this will please the LORD more than sacrificing an ox or presenting a bull with its horns and hooves.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 32, 'The humble will see their God at work and be glad. Let all who seek God''s help live in joy.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 33, 'For the LORD hears the cries of his needy ones; he does not despise his people who are oppressed.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 34, 'Praise him, O heaven and earth, the seas and all that move in them.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 35, 'For God will save Jerusalem and rebuild the towns of Judah. His people will live there and take possession of the land.', 'NLT'),
(23, 69, 36, 'The descendants of those who obey him will inherit the land, and those who love him will live there in safety.', 'NLT'),
(23, 70, 1, 'Please, God, rescue me! Come quickly, LORD, and help me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 70, 2, 'May those who try to destroy me be humiliated and put to shame. May those who take delight in my trouble be turned back in disgrace.', 'NLT'),
(23, 70, 3, 'Let them be horrified by their shame, for they said, "Aha! We''ve got him now!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 70, 4, 'But may all who search for you be filled with joy and gladness. May those who love your salvation repeatedly shout, "God is great!"', 'NLT'),
(23, 70, 5, 'But I am poor and needy; please hurry to my aid, O God. You are my helper and my savior; O LORD, do not delay!', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 1, 'O LORD, you are my refuge; never let me be disgraced.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 2, 'Rescue me! Save me from my enemies, for you are just. Turn your ear to listen and set me free.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 3, 'Be to me a protecting rock of safety, where I am always welcome. Give the order to save me, for you are my rock and my fortress.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 4, 'My God, rescue me from the power of the wicked, from the clutches of cruel oppressors.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 5, 'O Lord, you alone are my hope. I''ve trusted you, O LORD, from childhood.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 6, 'Yes, you have been with me from birth; from my mother''s womb you have cared for me. No wonder I am always praising you!', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 7, 'My life is an example to many, because you have been my strength and protection.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 8, 'That is why I can never stop praising you; I declare your glory all day long.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 9, 'And now, in my old age, don''t set me aside. Don''t abandon me when my strength is failing.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 10, 'For my enemies are whispering against me. They are plotting together to kill me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 11, 'They say, "God has abandoned him. Let''s go and get him, for there is no one to help him now."', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 12, 'O God, don''t stay away. My God, please hurry to help me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 13, 'Bring disgrace and destruction on those who accuse me. May humiliation and shame cover those who want to harm me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 14, 'But I will keep on hoping for you to help me; I will praise you more and more.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 15, 'I will tell everyone about your righteousness. All day long I will proclaim your saving power, for I am overwhelmed by how much you have done for me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 16, 'I will praise your mighty deeds, O Sovereign LORD. I will tell everyone that you alone are just and good.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 17, 'O God, you have taught me from my earliest childhood, and I have constantly told others about the wonderful things you do.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 18, 'Now that I am old and gray, do not abandon me, O God. Let me proclaim your power to this new generation, your mighty miracles to all who come after me.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 19, 'Your righteousness, O God, reaches to the highest heavens. You have done such wonderful things. Who can compare with you, O God?', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 20, 'You have allowed me to suffer much hardship, but you will restore me to life again and lift me up from the depths of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 21, 'You will restore me to even greater honor and comfort me once again.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 22, 'Then I will praise you with music on the harp, because you are faithful to your promises, O God. I will sing for you with a lyre, O Holy One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(23, 71, 23, 'I will shout for joy and sing your praises, for you have redeemed me.', 'NLT');
